y versatile and modernizing society as well as a rapidly developing economy. Currently, the country is negotiating its accession to the European Union. This article yields some factual grounding into the ongoing value-related debate concerning Turkeyâ€™s potential EU-membership. It describes a mixed-methodology study on moral reasoning in Austria and Turkey. In this study, the arguments given by individuals when evaluating ethically problematic situations in business were compared. Although there were major consistencies, a number of differences were found. These differences, however, were not in the substance (categories) of arguments used but in their relative frequency. Overall, our findings suggest that young, well-educated urban individuals from Western Christian and Eastern Islamic countries are highly consistent in their moral reasoning. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media B.V. 2007", "ex:volume": "74", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Why Is It (Un-)ethical? Comparing Potential European Partners: A Western Christian and An Eastern Islamic Country â€“ On Arguments Used in Explaining Ethical Judgments", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9223-1", "ex:pages": "101-118", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Cross-cultural comparison", "Moral reasoning", "Empirical study", "Mixed methodology"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Katharina Srnka", "ex:email": "katharina.srnka@univie.ac.at"}, {"ex:name": "A. Gegez"}, {"ex:name": "S. Arzova"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "87", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Why Firms Engage in Corruption: A Top Management Perspective", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9872-3", "ex:pages": "89-108", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Corruption", "Social ties", "Rationalization", "India"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Jamie Collins", "ex:email": "jamie_collins@baylor.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Klaus Uhlenbruck"}, {"ex:name": "Peter Rodriguez"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "81", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Is the Culture of Family Firms Really Different? A Value-based Model for Its Survival through Generations", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9493-2", "ex:pages": "261-279", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Culture", "Family firm", "Institutionalism", "Transformational leadership", "Values"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Manuel Vallejo", "ex:email": "mvallejo@ujaen.es"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "76", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Why Firms Should Not Always Maximize Profits", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9262-7", "ex:pages": "137-145", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Business ethics", "Corporate social responsibility", "Profit maximization", "Special duties", "D63", "M14"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Ivar Kolstad", "ex:email": "ivar.kolstad@cmi.no"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "83", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Impact of MBA Education on Students’ Values: Two Longitudinal Studies", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9614-y", "ex:pages": "233-246", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Mba education", "Others-oriented", "Self-monitoring", "Self-oriented", "Values change"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Venkat Krishnan", "ex:email": "web@rkvenkat.com"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:abstract": "Can or should God be considered a managerial stakeholder? While at first glance such a proposition might seem beyond the norms of stakeholder management theory or traditional management practice, further investigation suggests that there might be both theoretical and practical support for such a notion. This paper will make the argument that God both is and should be considered a managerial stakeholder for those businesspeople and business firms that accept that God exists and can affect the world. In doing so, part one of the paper first discusses the growth of religion and spirituality within the business and academic communities. Part two raises several arguments based on stakeholder theory and business reality to support the notion of God as a managerial stakeholder. Part three addresses the arguments against God as a managerial stakeholder. Part four discusses the managerial implications of considering God as a managerial stakeholder. The paper concludes with its limitations. Copyright Springer 2006", "ex:volume": "66", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "God as a Managerial Stakeholder?", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-005-5599-6", "ex:pages": "291-306", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["God", "Religion", "Spirituality", "Stakeholder theory", "Stakeholder identification", "Stakeholder salience"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Mark Schwartz", "ex:email": "schwartz@yorku.ca"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "85", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "A Three Country Comparative Analysis of Managerial CSR Perspectives: Insights From Lebanon, Syria and Jordan", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9755-7", "ex:pages": "173-192", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate social responsibility", "Managerial views", "Classical and modern paradigms", "Lebanon", "Syria", "Jordan"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Dima Jamali", "ex:email": "dj00@aub.edu.lb"}, {"ex:name": "Yusuf Sidani"}, {"ex:name": "Khalil El-Asmar"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "80", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Ethical Decisions About Sharing Music Files in the P2P Environment", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9424-2", "ex:pages": "349-365", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Peer-to-peer systems", "Ethical decision model", "Computer ethics", "Music industry", "Consumer ethics"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Rong-An Shang", "ex:email": "rashang@scu.edu.tw"}, {"ex:name": "Yu-Chen Chen", "ex:email": "cyc@scu.edu.tw"}, {"ex:name": "Pin-Cheng Chen", "ex:email": "pandean@ms45.url.com.tw"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:abstract": "If Solomon is correct in labeling businesses as community citizens because they â€œare part and parcel of the communities in which they live and flourish, and the responsibilities that they bear are ... intrinsic to their very existence as social entities,â€\\x9D then it follows that other community citizens have reciprocal duties toward them that they, as community citizens, have to any other community citizen. One of these duties is not to harm needlessly another community citizen without its permission. One issue affecting business is genetically engineering children to have characteristics, e.g., deafness, which render them disabled in work environments. Since business is a very large part of society, citizen responsibilities toward it in regard to intentionally creating deaf children should be examined. It is my contention that designing disabled offspring is unethical on the grounds that it causes undue injury to businesses without their permission in any form. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2007", "ex:volume": "71", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Deaf by Design: A Business Argument Against Engineering Disabled Offspring", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9135-0", "ex:pages": "209-227", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Business ethics", "Deaf", "Disabled", "Genetic engineering", "Amercians with disabilities act", "Individuals with disabilities education act", "Undue harm", "Acquiescence"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Dennis Cooley", "ex:email": "Dennis.Cooley@ndsu.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "78", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Integrating Ethics into Management", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9343-7", "ex:pages": "291-297", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "DomÃ¨nec MelÃ©", "ex:email": "mele@ise.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "81", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Due Process and Standard-setting: An Analysis of Due Process in Three Canadian Accounting and Auditing Standard-setting Bodies", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9540-z", "ex:pages": "679-696", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Accounting standard-setting", "Due process", "Canada"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Alan Richardson", "ex:email": "arichardson@schulich.yorku.ca"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "77", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Whistle-Blowing for Profit: An Ethical Analysis of the Federal False Claims Act", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9355-y", "ex:pages": "361-376", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Costs and benefits", "Ethics", "Federal false claims act", "Qui tam", "Whistle-blowing"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Thomas Carson"}, {"ex:name": "Mary Verdu"}, {"ex:name": "Richard Wokutch", "ex:email": "wokutch@vt.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "89", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Governance and the Common Good", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9904-z", "ex:pages": "11-18", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Audit committees", "Auditors", "Board of directors", "Common good", "Governance"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Joseph Carcello", "ex:email": "jcarcell@utk.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "We examine the perceived importance of three organizational preconditions (awareness of formal ethics codes, decision-making techniques, and availability of resources) theorized to be critical for ethics program effectiveness. In addition, we examine the importance of ethical leadership and congruence between formal ethics codes and informal ethical norms in influencing employee perceptions. Participants (n=418) from a large southern California government agency completed a survey on the perceived effectiveness of the organizationâ€™s ethics program. Results suggest that employee perceptions of organizational preconditions, ethical leadership and informal ethical norms were related to perceptions of ethics program effectiveness. Based on these findings, organizations should evaluate the presence (or absence) of essential preconditions and take steps to ensure that leaders model espoused organizational values to foster perceptions of effective ethics programs. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2006", "ex:volume": "67", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Rebounding from Corruption: Perceptions of Ethics Program Effectiveness in a Public Sector Organization", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9027-3", "ex:pages": "359-374", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Decision making", "Ethics", "Leadership", "Preconditions", "Program effectiveness"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Kathie Pelletier", "ex:email": "kathie.pelletier@cgu.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Michelle Bligh", "ex:email": "michelle.bligh@cgu.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "This paper investigates how specific notions of gender and ethnicity are integrated into diversity discourses presented on 241 top European company websites. Large European companies increasingly disclose equality and diversity policies in statements on websites. Such statements may be used to promote an ethical image of the company in terms of how well it manages diversity and guards against discrimination. In this paper, we argue that diversity statement discourses are important as they play a key part in socially constructing how diversity should be regarded in the company by minority and majority groups, as well as indicating corporate values to external stakeholders (investors, government, community, press etc.). Sometimes, the notions of gender or ethnic diversity are positioned as a liability in need of protection, whilst in others, as a source of competitive advantage. We find evidence of use of discursive tools such as problematisation, rationalisation, fixation, reframing and naturalisation of the notions of gender and ethnic diversity, reinforced by use of symbols, such as statistics, photographs, membership badges and awards. Few statements directly associate gender and ethnic diversity with enhanced corporate performance. We found that diversity statements sometimes appear to reinforce existing business stereotypes of women and people from ethnic minorities, and in a few discourses, create new ones, particularly evident in photographs illustrating the diversity web pages. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2006", "ex:volume": "68", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "(Re)Presentations of Gender and Ethnicity in Diversity Statements on European Company Websites", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9028-2", "ex:pages": "363-379", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Diversity", "Gender", "Ethnicity", "Discourse", "Corporate websites", "Europe"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Val Singh", "ex:email": "v.singh@cranfield.ac.uk"}, {"ex:name": "SÃ©bastien Point", "ex:email": "spoint@univfcomte.fr"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "89", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Reconciling CSR with the Role of the Corporation in Welfare States: The Problematic Swedish Example", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-010-0393-5", "ex:pages": "269-283", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate social responsibility", "National context", "Swedish model", "Welfare state"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Hans De Geer"}, {"ex:name": "Tommy Borglund"}, {"ex:name": "Magnus Frostenson", "ex:email": "magnus.frostenson@fek.uu.se"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "92", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Egyptian Worker: Work Beliefs and Attitudes", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0166-1", "ex:pages": "433-450", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2010", "ex:keyword": ["Work beliefs", "Work values", "Egypt", "Middle east", "Arab", "Job attitudes", "Job satisfaction", "Attitudes toward women", "Globe study"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Yusuf Sidani", "ex:email": "ys01@aub.edu.lb"}, {"ex:name": "Dima Jamali"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:abstract": "The purpose of this paper is to examine the various guidelines presented in the literature for instituting an ethics curriculum and to empirically study their effectiveness. Three questions are addressed concerning the trainability of ethics material and the proper integration and implementation of an ethics curriculum. An empirical study then tested the effect of ethics training on moral awareness and reasoning. The sample consisted of two business classes, one exposed to additional ethics curriculum (experimental), and one not exposed (control). For the experimental group, ethics exercises and discussion relevant to each topic were completed. Findings suggested gender differences such that, relative to other groups, women in the experimental group showed significantly improved moral awareness and decision-making processes. An explanation of the underlying cognitive processes is presented to explain the gender effect. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media B.V. 2006", "ex:volume": "68", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Can Business Ethics be Trained? A Study of the Ethical Decision-making Process in Business Students", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9062-0", "ex:pages": "153-164", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Business ethics", "Designing business ethics curriculum", "Ethics", "Teaching business ethics", "Teaching undergraduate business students"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Barbara Ritter", "ex:email": "britter@coastal.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "90", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Working Together: Critical Perspectives on Six Cross-Sector Partnerships in Southern Africa", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9915-9", "ex:pages": "79-89", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Cross-sector partnerships", "Critical perspectives", "South africa", "Zambia"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Melanie Rein", "ex:email": "melanie.rein@btinternet.com"}, {"ex:name": "Leda Stott", "ex:email": "lstott@globalcad.org"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:abstract": "The extent to which people identify with an organization is dependent on the attractiveness of the organizational identity, which helps individuals satisfy one or more important self-definitional needs. However, little is known about the antecedents of company identity attractiveness (IA) in a consumerâ€“company context. Drawing on theories of social identity and organizational identification, a model of the antecedents of IA is developed and tested. The findings provide empirical validation of the relationship between IA and corporate associations perceived by consumers. Our results demonstrate that the Corporate Social Responsibility (CSR) contribution to company IA is much stronger than that of Corporate Ability (CA). This may be linked to increasing competition and of decreasing CA-based variation in the marketplace. Copyright Springer 2007", "ex:volume": "71", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "â€œI Need You Too!â€\\x9D Corporate Identity Attractiveness for Consumers and The Role of Social Responsibility", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9137-y", "ex:pages": "245-260", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Consumer behavior", "Corporate social responsibility", "Identification", "Identity attractiveness", "Relationship marketing"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Longinos Marin"}, {"ex:name": "Salvador Ruiz", "ex:email": "salvruiz@um.es"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:abstract": "Most people are familiar with the traditional view of the role of ethics in the auditing profession â€“ the need for auditors with integrity and objectivity. This essay addresses a second dimension of ethics in the auditing profession â€“ the demand for auditors to assess the integrity and ethical values of clients. This second dimension is a difficult task for auditors in practice and demands a deep and robust understanding of ethics, ethical infrastructures, and the products of those infrastructures. The essay proposes how educators and researchers might facilitate that understanding. Copyright Springer 2007", "ex:volume": "70", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Through the Ethics Looking Glass: Another View of the World of Auditors and Ethics", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9079-4", "ex:pages": "5-14", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Auditing", "Ethical infrastructure", "Ethics", "Integrity"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Roger Martin", "ex:email": "rdm3h@virginia.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "84", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Worktime Demands and Work-Family Interference: Does Worktime Control Buffer the Adverse Effects of High Demands?", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9699-y", "ex:pages": "229-241", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Work–family interference", "Job demands", "Time control", "Commuting"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Sabine Geurts", "ex:email": "s.geurts@psych.ru.nl"}, {"ex:name": "Debby Beckers"}, {"ex:name": "Toon Taris"}, {"ex:name": "Michiel Kompier"}, {"ex:name": "Peter Smulders"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "90", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Pirate or Buy? The Moderating Effect of Idolatry", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0027-y", "ex:pages": "81-93", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Idolatry", "Music piracy", "Social identity theory", "Theory of planned behavior"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Chia-chen Wang", "ex:email": "92443005@cc.ncu.edu.tw"}, {"ex:name": "Chin-ta Chen"}, {"ex:name": "Shu-chen Yang"}, {"ex:name": "Cheng-kiang Farn"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "91", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Beyond the Game: Perceptions and Practices of Corporate Social Responsibility in the Professional Sport Industry", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0094-0", "ex:pages": "433-450", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2010", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate social responsibility", "Philanthropy", "Professional sport industry"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Hela Sheth", "ex:email": "hela.sheth@gmail.com"}, {"ex:name": "Kathy Babiak", "ex:email": "kbabiak@umich.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "In the economic literature on the firm, especially in the transactionâ€“cost tradition, a sharp distinction is drawn between so-called â€œmarket transactionsâ€\\x9D and â€œadministered transactions.â€\\x9D This distinction is of enormous importance for business ethics, since market transactions are governed by the competitive logic of the market, whereas administered transactions are subject to the cooperative norms that govern collective action in a bureaucracy. The widespread failure to distinguish between these two types of transactions, and thus to distinguish between adversarial and non-adversarial relations, has led many business ethicists to develop a â€œuniformâ€\\x9D moral code. Yet in market transactions, the checks and balances built into the system of commercial exchange are such as to permit more instrumental forms of behavior. In administered transactions, by contrast, these checks and balances are absent, and thus the institutional context calls for much greater exercise of moral restraint. In this paper, I begin the task of developing an adversarial ethic for business. According to this view, the competitive environment licenses a greater range of â€œself-interestedâ€\\x9D behavior, but also imposes its own constraints on the strategies that firms may adopt in the pursuit of their interests. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2007", "ex:volume": "72", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "An Adversarial Ethic for Business: or When Sun-Tzu Met the Stakeholder", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9175-5", "ex:pages": "359-374", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Adversarial ethics", "Competition", "Market failure", "Corporate social responsibility", "Philosophy of sport"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Joseph Heath", "ex:email": "joseph.heath@utoronto.ca"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "89", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "“Just” Markets from the Perspective of Catholic Social Teaching", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9908-8", "ex:pages": "29-38", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Catholic social teaching", "Economic development", "Impoverished market segments", "Inclusive capitalism", "Justice in the marketplace", "Marketing and society"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Nicholas Santos", "ex:email": "nicholas.santos@marquette.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Gene Laczniak", "ex:email": "eugene.laczniak@marquette.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:abstract": "This study analyzes the at-will employment doctrine using a tool that encompasses the complementarity of results-based utilitarian ethics, rule-based duty ethics, and virtue-based character ethics. The paper begins with a discussion of the importance of the problem followed by its evolution and current status. After describing the method of analysis, the central section evaluates the employment at-will doctrine, and is informed by Lord Actonâ€™s dictum, â€œpower tends to corrupt, and absolute power corrupts absolutely.â€\\x9D The conclusion explores the implications of the findings. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media B.V. 2007", "ex:volume": "74", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Lord Acton and Employment Doctrines: Absolute Power and the Spread of At-Will Employment", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9224-0", "ex:pages": "119-130", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["At-will employment", "Civil service reform", "Employment doctrines", "Ethical theory", "Power"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "James S. Bowman", "ex:email": "jbowman@fsu.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Jonathan P. West", "ex:email": "jwest@miami.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "90", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Direct and Multiplicative Effects of Ethical Dispositions and Ethical Climates on Personal Justice Norms: A Virtue Ethics Perspective", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0042-z", "ex:pages": "279-294", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Ethical climates", "Ethical dispositions", "Personal justice norms", "Virtue ethics theory", "Interactionist theory"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Victor Lau", "ex:email": "victorlau@cuhk.edu.hk"}, {"ex:name": "Yin Wong", "ex:email": "mgjwong@cityu.edu.hk"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "90", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Comparing Society’s Awareness of Women: Media-Portrayed Idealized Images and Physical Attractiveness", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0026-z", "ex:pages": "61-79", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Visual consumption", "Physical attractiveness", "Beauty", "Idealized image"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Chyong-Ling Lin", "ex:email": "joling888@gmail.com"}, {"ex:name": "Jin-Tsann Yeh", "ex:email": "jtyeh26@gmail.com"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:abstract": "Corporations today have been engineered by CEOs and other business advocates to look increasingly green and responsible. However, alarming cases such as Enron, Parmalat and Worldcom bear witness that a belief in corporate goodness is still nothing other than naÃ¯ve. Although many scholars seemingly recognize this, they still avoid touching on the most sensitive and problematic issues, the taboos. As a consequence, discussion of important though problematic topics is often stifled. The article identifies three â€˜grandâ€™ taboos of CSR discourse and explicitly raises them for discussion. They are the taboos of amoral business, continuous economic growth, and the political nature of CSR. It is suggested that CSR can only be as advanced as its taboos. The critical potential of the field remains underdeveloped as a consequence of the taboos, and in many cases the CSR discourse merely produces alluring but empty rhetoric about sustainability and responsible business. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media B.V. 2007", "ex:volume": "74", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Taboos in Corporate Social Responsibility Discourse", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9227-x", "ex:pages": "165-175", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Taboo", "Csr", "Corporate greening", "Growth", "Politics", "Amoral"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Tomi Kallio", "ex:email": "tomi.kallio@tse.fi"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "78", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Effects of Person–Organization Ethical Fit on Employee Attraction and Retention: Towards a Testable Explanatory Model", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9371-y", "ex:pages": "611-622", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Ethics", "Person-organization fit", "Attraction", "Retention", "Corporate social responsibility", "Corporate social performance"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "David Coldwell"}, {"ex:name": "Jon Billsberry", "ex:email": "j.billsberry@open.ac.uk"}, {"ex:name": "Nathalie Meurs"}, {"ex:name": "Philip Marsh"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:abstract": "This study continues the systematic measurement of consumersâ€™ sentiments toward business ethical practices first measured in 2004. The Business Ethics Index (BEI) comprises the four measurements representing the dimensions of â€œpersonalâ€“vicariousâ€\\x9D and â€œpastâ€“futureâ€\\x9D. A professional telephone interviewing company was hired to collect five consecutive waves of 1045 telephone interviews in an omnibus procedure. The collection of the five waves represented a sampling process which enables the creation of confidence intervals for this, and subsequent, measurements of the BEI. The overall BEI fell to 102.6 (from a revized 108.7 in 2004). The drop was attributed to a fall in consumer expectations of the future ethical behavior of business. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media B.V. 2007", "ex:volume": "72", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Business Ethics Index: USA 2006", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9163-9", "ex:pages": "163-175", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Business ethics", "Consumer sentiment", "Index"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "John Tsalikis", "ex:email": "tsalikis@fiu.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Bruce Seaton"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "85", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Examination on Philosophy-Based Management of Contemporary Japanese Corporations: Philosophy, Value Orientation and Performance", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9727-y", "ex:pages": "1-12", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate management philosophy", "Corporate value orientation", "Corporate performance"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Yingyan Wang", "ex:email": "ou@gsm.kyoto-u.ac.jp"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "84", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Broadcasting Operation Iraqi Freedom: The People Behind Cable News Ethics, Decisions, and Gender Differences", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9687-2", "ex:pages": "115-134", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Ethics", "Decision-making", "Gender differences", "Broadcast media", "Operation iraqi freedom"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Larry Boone", "ex:email": "boonel@stjohns.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Christine MacDonald", "ex:email": "crmd@optonline.net"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "“Harmonious” Norms for Global Marketing the Chinese Way", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0305-8", "ex:pages": "411-432", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["China", "Law", "Marketing", "Intellectual property", "Advertising", "World trade organization", "Harmonious society"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Leïla Choukroune", "ex:email": "Choukroune@hec.fr"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "78", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Breaking the Rules: Examining the Facilitation Effects of Moral Intensity Characteristics on the Recognition of Rule Violations", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9376-6", "ex:pages": "275-289", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Moral intensity", "Ethical decision-making", "Issue recognition", "Social contracts", "Evolutionary psychology"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "David Wasieleski", "ex:email": "wasieleski@duq.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Sefa Hayibor"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Challenge of Developing a Business Ethics in China", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9820-2", "ex:pages": "211-224", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Chinese business ethics", "Corporate social responsibility", "Confucianism"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Po Ip", "ex:email": "pkip@cc.ncu.edu.tw"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "87", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "An Analysis of the Ethical Codes of Corporations and Business Schools", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9865-2", "ex:pages": "1-13", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Aacsbi", "Corporate ethical codes", "Ethical codes", "Content of ethical codes", "Sarbanes-oxley", "Sec"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Harrison McCraw", "ex:email": "jmccraw@westga.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Kathy Moffeit"}, {"ex:name": "John O’Malley"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "81", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Unenlightened Economism: The Antecedents of Bad Corporate Governance and Ethical Decline", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9550-x", "ex:pages": "823-835", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate governance", "Economics", "Management philosophy", "Efficiency and effectiveness", "Gloomy vision", "Pretence of knowledge", "Enlightenment", "Economism", "Epistemology", "Management theory"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Matthias Huehn", "ex:email": "matthiashuehn@yahoo.de"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:abstract": "Contemporary HRM was introduced into Poland by the arrival of international corporations with their professional systems of Human Resource Management, which emphasizes ethical personnel management. This research is based on data collected from a questionnaire and interview of 40 women and men professional graduates of the 2004 Weekend MBA Program at Poznan University of Economics eliciting their perceptions of ethical issues in Polish HRM. The present Polish economic situation, with 19% unemployment, precipitates many ethical challenges. The questionnaire and interviews resulted in 217 observations and specific examples of ethical HRM issues. Examples fall in two broad categories and five specific Human Resource areas. The broad external categories are: (1) History and cultural attitudes and (2) Exploitation of the current unemployment situation. Historical and cultural attitudes influence attitudes toward work; company discipline; property and ownership; law and social expectations at work. The history of personnel departments in Socialistic Poland explains many of these attitudes. The five specific categories are: (1) Ethical issues in recruitment; (2) Ethical issues in hiring (Discrimination issues); (3) Ethical issues in performance appraisals and promotions; (4) Abuse of authority (including sexual harassment), and (5) â€œMobbingâ€\\x9D. Ethical issues in these categories include correlation with appropriate Polish Labor and Penal Laws. This research reveals some HRM ethical challenges unique to Polish HRM. The research emphasizes professional HRM and ethical expectations, which are now being recognized and accepted as a strategic component of Polish management Copyright Springer 2006", "ex:volume": "66", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Current Ethical Issues in Polish HRM", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-005-5598-7", "ex:pages": "273-290", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Human resource management", "Ethics", "Polish culture", "Polish history", "Polish labor law", "Recruiting", "Hiring", "Appraisal", "Â€œmobbingâ€\\x9d", "Unemployment"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Leo Ryan", "ex:email": "Leovryan@viatorians.com"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "92", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Analyzing the Politics of Health Care: Let’s Buy Ourselves Some Civilization", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0137-6", "ex:pages": "33-47", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2010", "ex:keyword": ["Health care", "Politics", "Ethics", "Obama", "Single-payer system"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Bill Shaw", "ex:email": "bevo1@mail.utexas.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Jessica Magaldi", "ex:email": "jmagaldi@pace.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "86", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Ethical Ideology and Ethical Judgments in the Portuguese Accounting Profession", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9845-6", "ex:pages": "227-242", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Accounting", "Business ethics", "Ethical decision-making", "Ethical ideology", "Ethical judgment", "Ethics"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Pedro Marques", "ex:email": "pedromarques@ipt.pt"}, {"ex:name": "José Azevedo-Pereira"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "86", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Antecedents of CSR Practices in MNCs’ Subsidiaries: A Stakeholder and Institutional Perspective", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0191-0", "ex:pages": "155-169", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate social responsibility", "Emerging economies", "Institutions", "International", "Legitimacy", "Multinational corporations’ subsidiaries", "Stakeholders"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Xiaohua Yang", "ex:email": "xyang14@usfca.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Cheryl Rivers", "ex:email": "crivers@usc.edu.au"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:abstract": "Given the tremendous proliferation of student plagiarism involving the Internet, the purpose of this study is to determine which theory of ethical reasoning students invoke when defending their transgressions: deontology, utilitarianism, rational self-interest, Machiavellianism, cultural relativism, or situational ethics. Understanding which theory of ethical reasoning students employ is critical, as preemptive steps can be taken by faculty to counteract this reasoning and prevent plagiarism. Additionally, it has been demonstrated that unethical behavior in school can lead to unethical behavior in business; therefore, correcting unethical behavior in school can have a positive impact on organizational ethics. To meet this objective, a content analysis was conducted on the written records of students formally charged with plagiarizing at a large West Coast university. Each case was classified according to the primary ethical reasoning that the student used to justify plagiarism. Results indicate that students predominately invoke deontology, situational ethics, and Machiavellianism. Based on these findings, specific recommendations are offered to curb plagiarism. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2007", "ex:volume": "72", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Applying Ethical Theories: Interpreting and Responding to Student Plagiarism", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9171-9", "ex:pages": "293-306", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Academic dishonesty", "Ethical reasoning", "History of copyright", "Historic views of plagiarism", "Internet plagiarism", "Teaching academic integrity", "Theories of ethics"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Neil Granitz"}, {"ex:name": "Dana Loewy", "ex:email": "dloewy@fullerton.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "90", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Responsible Entrepreneurship in Developing Countries: Understanding the Realities and Complexities", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0054-8", "ex:pages": "437-452", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Developing countries", "Responsible entrepreneurship", "Small-scale individual entrepreneurs", "Social responsibility"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Fara Azmat", "ex:email": "fara.azmat@deakin.edu.au"}, {"ex:name": "Ramanie Samaratunge"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "This article presents a theorized and conceptually informed method for the undertaking of an ethics audit organization. At an operational level, the overall integrity of an organization, it is argued, may be evaluated through the application of a conceptual framework that embraces the inter-related themes of individual responsibility, social equity and political responsibility. Finally, a method is presented for ethics audit which was developed in the auditing of a national public sector sports organization: sportscotland. This emphasizes the significance of key personnel (individuals and in groups) in producing and reproducing the organizational ethos, whilst recognizing the importance of anonymity and confidentiality throughout the 