panese religious university. In addition, students of the Japanese secular university were somewhat more sensitive to academic dishonesty practices than were students of the Japanese religious university. Copyright Springer 2006", "ex:volume": "65", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Does Religion Matter? A Comparison Study of the Ethical Beliefs of Marketing Students of Religious and Secular Universities in Japan", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-0023-4", "ex:pages": "69-86", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Comparison study", "Ethical beliefs", "Japan", "Religion"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Mohammed Rawwas", "ex:email": "rawwas@uni.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Ziad Swaidan"}, {"ex:name": "Jamal Al-Khatib"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "84", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "What is Fair: Three Perspectives", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9683-6", "ex:pages": "89-102", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Rational", "Emotional", "Spiritual", "Attitudes", "Motives", "Values"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "S. M. Patrick Primeaux", "ex:email": "primeaup@stjohns.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Frank Le Veness", "ex:email": "levenesf@stjohns.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "87", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Business and the International Human Rights Regime: A Comparison of UN Initiatives", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0297-4", "ex:pages": "401-417", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Business and human rights", "Corporate social responsibility", "Global compact", "International human rights", "Regime theory", "Transnational corporations"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Nina Seppala", "ex:email": "n.seppala@ucl.ac.uk"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "79", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Researching the Drivers of Socially Responsible Purchasing: A Cross-National Study of Supplier Diversity Initiatives", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9400-x", "ex:pages": "319-331", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Drivers of CSR", "Ethnic minority businesses", "Socially responsible purchasing", "Supplier diversity", "Supply chain"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Ian Worthington", "ex:email": "iwcor@dmu.ac.uk"}, {"ex:name": "Monder Ram"}, {"ex:name": "Harvinder Boyal"}, {"ex:name": "Mayank Shah"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "South Africaâ€™s principal corporate governance report aspires to an â€˜inclusiveâ€™ approach to corporate governance, in which companies are clearly advised to consider the interests of a variety of stakeholders. Yet, in common with many other countries, there is little discussion of the theoretical foundations and assumptions implicit in the recommended approach to corporate governance. The purpose of this article is to provide an analysis of corporate governance and the corporate environment in South Africa in terms of existing theory and models of corporate governance, and to provide a critique based on a consideration of traditional African values and the socio-economic necessities of post-apartheid South Africa. The result is the identification of an incompatibility between the current corporate environment in South Africa and the given exposition of African values. Some prospects for change are then identified. Copyright Springer 2006", "ex:volume": "68", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Theorising South Africaâ€™s Corporate Governance", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9033-5", "ex:pages": "433-448", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["African philosophy", "Corporate governance", "Inclusive approach", "South africa", "Stakeholder"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Andrew West", "ex:email": "Andrew.West@Buseco.monash.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "81", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Impact of Perceived Leader Integrity on Subordinates in a Work Team Environment", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9546-6", "ex:pages": "765-778", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Work teams", "Leader integrity", "Ethical decision-making", "Teammates"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Darin White", "ex:email": "Darin.White@bscalum.net"}, {"ex:name": "Emily Lean"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "92", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Safety and Ethics in the Global Workplace: Asymmetries in Culture and Infrastructure", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0142-9", "ex:pages": "87-106", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2010", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate citizenship", "Global workplaces", "High-risk workplaces", "Safety culture", "Safety ethics", "Transport-related workplaces"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Oswaldo Lorenzo", "ex:email": "oswaldo.lorenzo@ie.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Paul Esqueda"}, {"ex:name": "Janelle Larson"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:abstract": "The study draws attention to the transfer of management theories and practices from traditional capitalist countries such as the USA and UK to post-socialist countries that are currently experiencing radical change as they seek to introduce market reforms. It is highlighted that the efficacy of this transfer of management theories and practices is, in part, dependent upon the extent to which work-related attitudes and values vary between traditional capitalist and former socialist contexts. We highlight that practices such as Human Resource Management (HRM) and Organization Development (OD) are inextricably associated with conceptions surrounding culture and society, as well as to variables such as job satisfaction and organisational commitment. The main aim of this study is to compare various attitudes and values of employees in traditional capitalist countries and post-socialist countries. On the basis of the findings of an attitudinal survey of (NÂ =Â 5914) workers in 15 countries we conclude that certain aspects of the attitudes and values of workers in post-socialist countries and traditional capitalist countries differ significantly. Specifically, these differences were found in respect of context-related and job-related attitudes, and also in relation to the importance that the respondents attached to the subject of ethics more generally. The implications of the study are discussed particularly in relation to the transfer of management theory and practices between traditional capitalist and post-socialist contexts. Copyright Springer 2006", "ex:volume": "68", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Work-related Attitudes, Values and Radical Change in Post-Socialist Contexts: A Comparative Study", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9065-x", "ex:pages": "181-189", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Attitudes", "Values", "Capitalist", "Socialist", "Commitment", "Job satisfaction", "Ethics", "Change"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Ruth Alas", "ex:email": "ruth.alas@ebs.ee"}, {"ex:name": "Christopher Rees", "ex:email": "chris.rees@man.ac.uk"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "77", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Dark Side of Authority: Antecedents, Mechanisms, and Outcomes of Organizational Corruption", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9358-8", "ex:pages": "431-449", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Authority", "Bureaucracy", "Corruption", "Opportunity", "Motivation", "Justification", "Types of organizational corruption", "Weber", "White-collar crime"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Ruth Aguilera", "ex:email": "ruth-agu@uiuc.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Abhijeet Vadera", "ex:email": "avaderaz@uiuc.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "87", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Bribery: Australian Managers’ Experiences and Responses When Operating in International Markets", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9870-5", "ex:pages": "59-74", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Bribery", "Australia", "International", "Cross-cultural", "Critical incident technique"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Kerry Pedigo", "ex:email": "k.pedigo@curtin.edu.au"}, {"ex:name": "Verena Marshall"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "80", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Ethical Issues in Financial Reporting: Is Intentional Structuring of Lease Contracts to Avoid Capitalization Unethical?", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9436-y", "ex:pages": "45-59", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Accounting", "Accounting ethics", "Ethics and lease accounting", "Ethics of financial reporting", "Rule-based accounting", "Rule-based ethics"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Thomas Frecka", "ex:email": "Frecka.1@nd.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Varieties of Win–Win Solutions to Problems with Ethical Dimensions", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9967-x", "ex:pages": "333-349", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Win–win solutions", "Ethics"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Richard Nielsen", "ex:email": "richard.nielsen@bc.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:abstract": "Corporate social responsibility (CSR) has acquired an unquestionably high degree of relevance for a large number of different actors. Among others, academics and practitioners are developing a wide range of knowledge and best practices to further improve socially responsible competences. Within this context, one frequent question is according to what theory should general knowledge of CSR be developed, and in particular the relationship between CSR and small and medium-size enterprises (SMEs). This paper suggests that research on large firms should be based on stakeholder theory, while research on CSR among SMEs should be based on the concept of social capital. This paper first provides a theoretical and practical perspective on CSR today; the focus then shifts to the specific literature on CSR and SMEs; some data and information follow on SMEs in Europe and Italy; finally, some conclusions and questions for future research are suggested. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2006", "ex:volume": "67", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "SMEs and CSR Theory: Evidence and Implications from an Italian Perspective", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9186-2", "ex:pages": "305-316", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate social responsibility", "Italy", "Multi-stakeholder approach", "Small and medium enterprises", "Social capital"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Francesco Perrini", "ex:email": "francesco.perrini@unibocconi.it"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:abstract": "The original intent of business education in America focused on the development of professional managers who would look after the interests of society. As economic and shareholder theories influenced business education, firm performance became the managerâ€™s top â€“ if not only â€“ priority. The economic responsibility of the firm also appears to be dominating scholarly interest in organisations as well. However, business firms constitute part of the fabric of society and closer attention should be paid by organisation researchers to the social responsibilities of the firm. In doing so, a more balanced research approach can be achieved. In this article, we give evidence that research within the study of the organisation, specifically in the field of management, has predominately turned its attention to the economic responsibility of the firm. We close by demonstrating that other fields within organisation research also appear to be favouring the study of performance and we offer suggestions as to how scholars might better address the firmâ€™s role in society beyond its economic responsibility. Copyright Springer 2006", "ex:volume": "65", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Are Organisation Researchers too Obsessed with the Economic Responsibility of the Firm?", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-0008-3", "ex:pages": "287-295", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["The business firm", "Social issues", "Economic responsibilities", "Organisation research", "Economic and social goals"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Jeremy Galbreath", "ex:email": "jeremygalbreath@hotmail.com"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Chinese Negotiators’ Subjective Variations in Intercultural Negotiations", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0300-0", "ex:pages": "529-537", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Confucianism", "Chinese", "Negotiation", "Culture", "Conjoint", "Accommodation"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Clyde Warden", "ex:email": "cwarden@cwarden.org"}, {"ex:name": "Judy Chen", "ex:email": "jfc@ocu.edu.tw"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "75", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "A Content Analysis of Whistleblowing Policies of Leading European Companies", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9236-9", "ex:pages": "25-44", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Business ethics", "Codes of conduct", "Codes of ethics", "Compliance", "Content", "Whistleblowing"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Harold Hassink", "ex:email": "h.hassink@aim.unimaas.nl"}, {"ex:name": "Meinderd Vries"}, {"ex:name": "Laury Bollen"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "86", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Urgency and Necessity of a Different Type of Market: The Perspective of Producers Organized Within the Fair Trade Market", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9766-4", "ex:pages": "51-61", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Fair trade", "Neo-liberalism", "Gender", "Bio-politics", "Governmentality", "Corporate social responsibility", "Sustainability", "Eco-tourism", "Food security", "Democracy", "Solidarity"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Francisco VanderHoff Boersma", "ex:email": "vanderbf@uciri.org"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "83", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Power and Size of Firms as Reflected in Cleaning Subcontractors’ Practices of Social Responsibility", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9647-2", "ex:pages": "673-683", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate social responsibility", "Firm size", "Power relations", "Cleaning subcontractors", "Inter-organization network"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Sarit Nisim"}, {"ex:name": "Orly Benjamin", "ex:email": "benjamo@mail.biu.ac.il"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:abstract": "The purpose of this exploratory study is to examine the use of an ethical intervention strategy â€“ counterexplanation â€“ on individualsâ€™ ethical decision-making. As opposed to providing reasons to support a decision in the case of explanation, counterexplanation is the provision of reasons that either speak against or provide evidence against a chosen course of action. The number of explanations and/or counterexplanations provided by the participants is expected to have a significant effect on ethical evaluation and intention. The number of explanations is expected to be negatively related to ethical decision-making while the number of counterexplanations is expected to be positively related to ethical decision-making. The experiment, that made use of five ethical vignettes, manipulated four treatment groups â€“ explanation, counterexplanation, explanation/counterexplanation, and counterexplanation/explanation. Participants were randomly assigned to one of the four reatments. They performed the requirements of their treatment before recording their ethical evaluations and intentions. As expected, larger numbers of explanations led to less ethical decision-making and larger numbers of counterexplanations led to more ethical decision-making. However, when both types of explanations are required, the order of counterexplaining before explaining is more desirable as it leads to more ethical decision-making. The study also reports that individuals with high social desirability bias (a tendency to present oneself in a culturally acceptable manner) may generate less counterexplanations. Implications of the findings are explained in the paper. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2007", "ex:volume": "73", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "An Exploratory Study of Counterexplanation as an Ethical Intervention Strategy", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9204-4", "ex:pages": "245-261", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Explanations", "Social desirability bias", "Ethical evaluations", "Ethical intentions"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Janne Chung", "ex:email": "jchung@schulich.yorku.ca"}, {"ex:name": "Gary Monroe"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "91", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Ethics of Celebrities and Their Increasing Influence in 21st Century Society", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0090-4", "ex:pages": "313-318", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2010", "ex:keyword": ["Ethics", "Celebrities", "Mission creep", "Fame", "Addiction", "Internet"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Chong Choi", "ex:email": "russell_choi@hotmail.com"}, {"ex:name": "Ron Berger", "ex:email": "berger_r@zahav.net.il"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Compass and Dead Reckoning: The Dynamic Implications of ISCT", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0335-2", "ex:pages": "659-664", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Social contract theory", "Corporate social responsibility", "Business ethics", "Isct"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Thomas Donaldson", "ex:email": "donaldst@wharton.upenn.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:abstract": "Technology used in online marketing has advanced to a state where collection, enhancement and aggregation of information are instantaneous. This proliferation of customer information focused technology brings with it a host of issues surrounding customer privacy. This article makes two key contributions to the debate concerning digital privacy. First, we use theories of justice to help understand the way consumers conceive of, and react to, privacy concerns. Specifically, it is argued that an important component of consumersâ€™ privacy concerns relates to fairness judgments, which in turn comprise of the two primary components of distributive and procedural justice. Second, we make a number of prescriptions, aimed at both firms and regulators, based on the notion that consumers respond to perceived privacy violations in much the same way they would respond to an unfair exchange. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2006", "ex:volume": "67", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Marketing Dataveillance and Digital Privacy: Using Theories of Justice to Understand Consumersâ€™ Online Privacy Concerns", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9007-7", "ex:pages": "107-123", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Digital privacy", "Fairness", "Online behavioural marketing", "Theories of justice"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Laurence Ashworth"}, {"ex:name": "Clinton Free", "ex:email": "cfree@business.queensu.ca"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:abstract": "As a consequence of the changing conditions of doing business, we can observe the emergence of an increasing number of industrial and company-specific codes of conduct, as well as social and environmental standards. This paper considers these initiatives as being self-regulating governance mechanisms, which are characterized by a process of voluntary adherence on the part of firms to certain mechanisms or principles that seek to promote a â€œgood society.â€\\x9D Two specific internationally established standards are discussed: Social Accountability 8000 (SA 8000) and AccountAbility 1000 (AA 1000). These institutionalized approaches are described and then contrasted in relation to a number of different factors, particularly the degree to which they foster â€œreflexivity,â€\\x9D in terms of how businesses think about these issues, and â€œdialog,â€\\x9D in terms of how businesses interact with stakeholders. Such questions are relevant to the ways in which these standards might be introduced and implemented, and which of these institutionalized approaches are the most promising for international businesses in developing countries. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2007", "ex:volume": "73", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Social Standards: Toward an Active Ethical Involvement of Businesses in Developing Countries", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9193-3", "ex:pages": "11-20", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Social standards", "Social accountability 8000", "Accountability 1000", "Reflexive modernity", "Reflexivity", "Dialog", "Institutionalization", "Developing countries"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Thomas Beschorner", "ex:email": "thomas.beschorner@uni-oldenburg.de"}, {"ex:name": "Martin MÃ¼ller", "ex:email": "martin.mueller@uni-oldenburg.de"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "Recognizing the growing interdependence of the European Union and the importance of codes of conduct in companiesâ€™ operations, this research examines the effect of a countryâ€™s culture on the implementation of a code of conduct in a European context. We examine whether the perceptions of an activityâ€™s ethicality relates to elements found in company codes of conduct vary by country or according to Hofstedeâ€™s (1980, Cultureâ€™s Consequences (Sage Publications, Beverly Hills, CA)) cultural constructs of: Uncertainty Avoidance, Masculinity/Femininity, Individualism, and Power Distance. The 294 individuals, who participated in our study, were from 8 Western European countries. Their responses to our 13 scenarios indicate that differences in the perceptions of ethicality associate primarily with the participantsâ€™ country as opposed to their employer (i.e., accounting firm), employment level, or gender. The evidence also indicates that these country differences associate with Hofstede constructs of Individualism and Masculinity. Copyright Springer 2007", "ex:volume": "70", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Effect of Country and Culture on Perceptions of Appropriate Ethical Actions Prescribed by Codes of Conduct: A Western European Perspective among Accountants", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9113-6", "ex:pages": "327-340", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Codes of conduct", "Ethical perceptions", "Country culture"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Donald Arnold", "ex:email": "ArnoldD@union.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Richard Bernardi"}, {"ex:name": "Presha Neidermeyer"}, {"ex:name": "Josef Schmee"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:abstract": "The academic literature reveals the need to undertake more in-depth field studies in order to discover the organisational culture, the difficulties and the perceptions surrounding CSR in SMEs. This study presents the results of analysis of four case studies on Catalan companies that stand out for their social and environmental practices. The conclusions of this paper are the result of dialogue with the main actors â€“ four medium-sized companies â€“ focusing on their actions, understandings and resistance with regard to CSR. The methodological perspective used was Grounded Theory, with the aim of the study being to contribute towards formalising CSR in SMEs, in their daily practices, by analysing some primary data. The results obtained show how difficult it is for SMEs to understand CSR, beyond the explanation of the specific practices carried out by the companies. They highlight the role played by the values of the founding director in the implementation of CSR programmes; they reveal that SMEs still have a long way to go towards learning how to inform both internal and external stakeholders of their best practices, and; finally, they show the interesting links that SMEs establish between responsible practices, improved competitiveness and economic results. Finally, the text points out the implications that the results of this analysis may have on creating ways of promoting CSR in SMEs. We believe that, in light of the opinions expressed by the companies, public organisations should try to concentrate on creating a favourable framework for responsible competitiveness, as a way to deal with CSR when addressing SMEs. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2006", "ex:volume": "67", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "SMEs and CSR: An Approach to CSR in their Own Words", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9181-7", "ex:pages": "227-240", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Business case study", "Csr motivations", "Csr perception", "Public policy", "Qualitative research", "Smes", "Responsible competitiveness"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "David Murillo", "ex:email": "david.murillo@esade.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Josep Lozano"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "ISCT, Hypernorms, and Business: A Reinterpretation", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0334-3", "ex:pages": "645-658", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Social contract", "Integrative social contracts theory", "Moral free space", "Hypernorms", "Stakeholder theory", "Donaldson", "Dunfee", "Human rights"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "George Brenkert", "ex:email": "brenkg@georgetown.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "76", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Corporate Identity of a Socially Responsible University â€“ A Case from the Turkish Higher Education Sector", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9274-3", "ex:pages": "55-68", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate identity", "Corporate social responsibility", "Corporate philanthropy", "University", "Turkey"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "M. Atakan", "ex:email": "atakans@bilgi.edu.tr"}, {"ex:name": "Tutku Eker", "ex:email": "tutku@bilgi.edu.tr"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "91", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Political Dimension: Added Value for Cross-Cultural Analysis. Nozawa and Smits, Two CEOs and Their Public Statements", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0085-1", "ex:pages": "319-327", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2010", "ex:keyword": ["Cultural differences", "Political analysis", "Public statements", "Responsibility", "Makoto", "Spijt", "Ceo", "Nozawa", "Yamaichi", "Smits", "Kpn"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Robert Es", "ex:email": "esvanr@xs4all.nl"}, {"ex:name": "Thomas Pels"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "76", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Corporate Social Responsibility Practices and Environmentally Responsible Behavior: The Case of The United Nations Global Compact", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9265-4", "ex:pages": "163-176", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate social responsibility", "Economics", "Environmentally responsible behavior", "Ethics", "The united nations global compact", "Turkish case study"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Dilek Cetindamar", "ex:email": "dilek@sabanciuniv.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "66", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Nature of the Firm, Agency Theory and Shareholder Theory: A Critique from Philosophical Anthropology", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9052-2", "ex:pages": "33-42", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Nature of the firm", "Agency theory", "Shareholder theory", "Personalism", "Common good"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Joan Fontrodona", "ex:email": "fontrodona@iese.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Alejo Sison", "ex:email": "ajsison@unav.es"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "76", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Corporate Social Responsibility of Pharmaceutical Product Recalls: An Empirical Examination of U.S. and U.K. Markets", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9292-1", "ex:pages": "427-449", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate social responsibility", "Pharmaceutical industry", "Product recalls", "Shareholder wealth", "Uk and US comparison"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Eng Cheah", "ex:email": "Cheah_Eng.Tuck@nottingham.edu.my"}, {"ex:name": "Wen Chan"}, {"ex:name": "Corinne Chieng"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Corporate Social Responsibility and the “Divided Corporate Self”: The case of Chiquita in Colombia", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0313-8", "ex:pages": "595-603", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate integrity", "Corporate social responsibility", "Corporate responsibility", "Chiquita", "Colombia"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Virginia Maurer", "ex:email": "virginia.maurer@cba.ufl.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:abstract": "We explore the extent to which Boards use executive compensation to incite firms to act in accordance with social and environmental objectives (e.g., Johnson, R. and D. Greening: 1999 , Academy of Management Journal 42(5), 564â€“578 ; Kane, E. J.: 2002 , Journal of Banking and Finance 26, 1919â€“1933.). We examine the association between executive compensation and corporate social responsibility (CSR) for 77 Canadian firms using three key components of executivesâ€™ compensation structure: salary, bonus, and stock options. Similar to prior research (McGuire, J., S. Dow and K. Argheyd: 2003 , Journal of Business Ethics 45(4), 341â€“359), we measure three different aspects of CSR, which include Total CSR as well as CSR Strengths and CSR Weaknesses. CSR Strengths and CSR Weaknesses capture the positive and negative aspects of CSR, respectively. We find significant positive relationships between: (1) Salary and CSR Weaknesses, (2) Bonus and CSR Strengths, (3) Stock Options and Total CSR; and (4) Stock Options and CSR Strengths. Our findings suggest the importance of the structure of executive compensation in encouraging socially responsible actions, particularly for larger Canadian firms. This in turn suggests that executive compensation can be an effective tool in aligning executivesâ€™ welfare with that of the â€œcommon goodâ€\\x9D, which results in more socially responsible firms (Bebchuk, L., J. Fried and D. Walker: 2002 , The University of Chicago Law Review 69, 751â€“846; Zalewski, D.: 2003 , Journal of Economic Issues 37(2), 503â€“509). In addition, our findings suggest the importance of institutional context in influencing the association between executive compensation and CSR. Further implications for practice and research are discussed. Copyright Springer 2006", "ex:volume": "69", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "An Examination of the Structure of Executive Compensation and Corporate Social Responsibility: A Canadian Investigation", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9073-x", "ex:pages": "149-162", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate governance", "Executive compensation", "Social performance", "Social responsibility"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Lois Mahoney", "ex:email": "lois.mahoney@emich.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Linda Thorn"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:abstract": "This paper explores research in educational psychology and learning theory in a search for insights to enhance business ethics training Useful educational principles uncovered are then applied to the development of an ethics training initiative for sales professionals. The paper concludes with suggestions for future research to help enrich business ethics training. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2007", "ex:volume": "70", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Business Ethics Training: Insights from Learning Theory", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9083-8", "ex:pages": "61-85", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Business ethics", "Business ethics training", "Ethical decision-making", "Facilitatorâ€“participant interaction", "Inductive learning", "Self-discovery", "Selling ethics", "Unethical selling behavior"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "John Weber", "ex:email": "john.a.weber.1@nd.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "84", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Fairness in International Trade and Investment: North American Perspectives", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0206-x", "ex:pages": "405-425", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["North america", "Wto", "Nafta", "Asym- metrical dependency", "Fairness", "Protectionism", "Fair play", "Procedural justice", "Distributive justice", "Commutative justice", "Transfer pricing"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Frederick Bird", "ex:email": "fbird@uwaterloo.ca"}, {"ex:name": "Thomas Vance"}, {"ex:name": "Peter Woolstencroft"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "74", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The United Nations Convention Against Corruption and its Impact on International Companies", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9524-z", "ex:pages": "481-496", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Bribery", "Convention against corruption", "Corruption", "Extortion", "International business", "United nations"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Antonio ArgandoÃ±a", "ex:email": "argandona@iese.edu"}]}, {"ex