ial responsibility and performance, however. Based on the approach proposed by Simons, we argue that organisational reporting about social responsibility can be viewed as a learning tool in some instances. Under this view the design and implementation of corporate social reporting procedures may lead to individual and organisational dynamic changes that foster organisational performance. Research propositions are then derived from the analysis. Copyright Springer 2006", "ex:volume": "65", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Social Reporting as an Organisational Learning Tool? A Theoretical Framework", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-6405-9", "ex:pages": "359-371", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate social responsibility", "Social reporting", "Organisational learning"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Jean-Pascal Gond"}, {"ex:name": "Olivier Herrbach", "ex:email": "olivier.herrbach@u-bordeaux4.fr"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "74", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Ethics of Insider Trading Revisited", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9532-z", "ex:pages": "497-507", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Insider trading", "Market manipulation", "Fairness", "Property rights"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Peter-Jan Engelen", "ex:email": "p.engelen@econ.uu.nl"}, {"ex:name": "Luc Liedekerke", "ex:email": "Luc.vanliedekerke@econ.kuleuven.ac.be"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "80", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Environmental Reporting: The U.K. Water and Energy Industries: A Research Note", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9463-8", "ex:pages": "697-710", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Content anlaysis", "Environmental reporting", "Energy industry", "Water industry"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Stephanie Stray", "ex:email": "Stephanie.Stray@wbs.ac.uk"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:abstract": "This article explores how neutralisation can explain peopleâ€™s lack of commitment to buying Fair Trade (FT) products, even when they identify FT as an ethical concern. It examines the theoretical tenets of neutralisation theory and critically assesses its applicability to the purchase of FT products. Exploratory research provides illustrative examples of neutralisation techniques being used in the FT consumer context. A conceptual framework and research propositions delineate the role of neutralisation in explaining the attitude-behaviour discrepancies evident in relation to consumersâ€™ FT purchase behaviour, providing direction for further research that will generate new knowledge of consumersâ€™ FT purchase behaviour and other aspects of ethical consumer behaviour. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media B.V. 2007", "ex:volume": "74", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Why People Donâ€™t Take their Concerns about Fair Trade to the Supermarket: The Role of Neutralisation", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9222-2", "ex:pages": "89-100", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Attitude-behaviour gap", "Ethical consumerism", "Ethical decision-making", "Fair trade purchase", "Neutralisation"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Andreas Chatzidakis", "ex:email": "lixac2@nottingham.ac.uk"}, {"ex:name": "Sally Hibbert"}, {"ex:name": "Andrew Smith"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Confucian/Chopsticks Marketing", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0307-6", "ex:pages": "393-397", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Kim-Shyan Fam", "ex:email": "kim.fam@vuw.ac.nz"}, {"ex:name": "Zhilin Yang"}, {"ex:name": "Mike Hyman"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:abstract": "Prior research shows that mutual fund investors are often aware of up-front charges like sales loads, but they are less mindful of annual operating expenses, even though both types of fees lower overall performance. This study documents the historical trend and recent abuse of annual mutual fund expenses. As the industry becomes more adept at segmenting customers by level of investment sophistication, we claim that load mutual fund companies take advantage of this ability and charge higher expenses to their target customer: the less-knowledgeable investor. No-load fund companies, which tend to attract the more sophisticated investor, offer lower expenses. For example, over 2000â€“2004 the average annual expense ratio of load equity funds was 50 basis points higher than no-load equity funds. We show evidence of this widening cost disparity since the early 1990s among new and existing equity, bond, and index funds. We also document a growing abuse of sales distribution or 12b-1 fees among funds that are closed to new investors, almost all of which are load funds. Thus, load fund investors are more susceptible to paying higher expenses and receiving lower returns over time. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2007", "ex:volume": "70", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Use and Abuse of Mutual Fund Expenses", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9077-6", "ex:pages": "23-32", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["12b-1 fees", "Asset management fees", "Expense ratios", "Mutual funds", "Sales loads"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Todd Houge", "ex:email": "todd-houge@uiowa.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Jay Wellman"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "CSR and the Corporate Cyborg: Ethical Corporate Information Security Practices", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0312-9", "ex:pages": "579-594", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate governance", "Corporate social responsibility", "Information security", "Identity theft", "Nondisclosure"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Andr