s within concepts of â€˜practiceâ€™, and argues for the importance of the context in architecture where narrative can be used to learn and to integrate past and present experience. Narrative reflection also takes in the future, and in the case of architecture there is a positive but not yet well accepted move (particularly within the â€˜academyâ€™) to realise the imperative nature of architectureâ€™s responsibility with respect of global sustainability. Architects, more perhaps than other professions, use the faculty of imagination in their work, and this paper therefore maintains that architects as artists are uniquely qualified to exercise â€˜moral imaginationâ€™ when it comes to situations where moral deliberation is needed. Pragmatism has given a new impetus to the importance of imagination in moral reflection, and I focus on John Deweyâ€™s categories of â€˜empathyâ€™ and â€˜dramatic rehearsalâ€™ as descriptors of moral imagination as applied in situations. I argue in conclusion firstly that empathy between end-users and architects is an essential but not always realised part of morality in architecture, and secondly that â€˜dramatic rehearsalâ€™, when extended more widely that a given situation, may lead architects to question the social, political and ecological contexts of their work and thus motivate them to prioritise the â€˜ethicalâ€™ in all the choices they make. Copyright Springer 2006", "ex:volume": "66", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Art of Moral Imagination: Ethics in the Practice of Architecture", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-005-5600-4", "ex:pages": "307-317", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Jane Collier", "ex:email": "j.collier@jims.cam.ac.uk"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "90", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Assessing the Impact of Public–Private Partnerships in the Global South: The Case of the Kasur Tanneries Pollution C