hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-005-5587-x", "ex:pages": "225-231", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Strategy", "Poverty", "Partnerships", "Internationalisation"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Alan Singer", "ex:email": "alan.singer@canterbury.ac.nz"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "This article helps to clarify and articulate the ideological, legal, and ethical attitudes regarding software as intellectual property (IP). Computer software can be viewed as IP from both ethical and legal perspectives. The size and growth of the software industry suggest that large profits are possible through the development and sale of software. The rapid growth of the open source movement, fueled by the development of the Linux operating system, suggests another model is possible. The large number of unauthorized copies of software programs suggests that many people do not believe in laws regarding software copyright. There are many and varied views of software as IP, even within the information systems (IS) profession. In this article, four distinct subgroups of IS professionals are identified. The article describes the four subgroups and their respective ideological views on software ownership; it explores the subgroupsâ€™ attitudes regarding software laws; and finally, it explains the ethical positions embraced by each subgroup. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2007", "ex:volume": "73", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "An Exploration of the Ideologies of Software Intellectual Property: The Impact on Ethical Decision Making", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9215-1", "ex:pages": "409-424", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Computer ethics", "Copyright", "Free software", "Intellectual property", "Software", "Open source advocate"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Matthew McGowan", "ex:email": "mmcgowan@bradley.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Paul Stephens"}, {"ex:name": "Dexter Gruber"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "84", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Marxism, Business Ethics, and Corporate Social Responsibility", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9725-0", "ex:pages": "565-576", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Business ethics", "Corporate social responsibility", "Fiduciary responsibility", "Friedman", "Milton", "Marxism", "Prisoner’s dilemma", "Profit maximization"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "William Shaw", "ex:email": "wshaw@email.sjsu.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "80", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Promoting Stewardship Behavior in Organizations: A Leadership Model", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9440-2", "ex:pages": "121-128", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Courage", "Intergenerational", "Intrinsic motivation", "Leadership", "Stewardship", "Trust"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Morela Hernandez", "ex:email": "morela.hernandez@duke.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "Calls for the expansion of ethics education in the business and accounting curricula have resulted in a variety of interventions including additional material on ethical cases, the code of conduct, and the development of new courses devoted to ethical development [Lampe, J.: 1996]. The issue of whether ethics should be taught has been addressed by many authors [see for example: Hanson, K. O.: 1987; Huss, H. F. and D. M. Patterson: 1993; Jones, T. M.: 1988â€“1989; Kerr, D. S. and L. M. Smith: 1995; Loeb, S. E.: 1988; McDonald, G. M. and G. D. Donleavy: 1995]. The question addressed in this paper is not whether ethics should be taught but whether accounting students can reason more ethically after an intervention based on a discrete and dedicated course on accounting ethics. The findings in this paper indicate that a discrete intervention emphasising dilemma discussion has a positive and significant effect on studentsâ€™ moral reasoning and development. The data collected from interviews suggest that the salient influences on moral judgement development include: learning theories of ethics particularly Kohlbergâ€™s theory of cognitive moral reasoning and development; peer learning; and moral discourse. The implications from the findings in this study suggest that moral reasoning is responsive to particular types of ethics intervention and educators should carefully plan their attempts to foster moral judgement development. Copyright Springer 2006", "ex:volume": "65", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Making a Difference with a Discrete Course on Accounting Ethics", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-0020-7", "ex:pages": "391-404", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Accounting students", "Ethics education", "Ethics interventions", "Moral discourse", "Moral reasoning and development", "Kohlberg", "Dit"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Steven Dellaportas", "ex:email": "s.dellaportas@ballarat.edu.au"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "92", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Exceeding Our Grasp: Curricular Change and the Challenge to the Assumptive World", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0141-x", "ex:pages": "79-85", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2010", "ex:keyword": ["Assumptive world", "Consilience", "Curricular redesign", "Ethical decision making", "Organic education"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Samuel Natale", "ex:email": "NATALE3@Adelphi.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Sebastian Sora"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "81", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Whistle-Blowing and Morality", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9529-7", "ex:pages": "579-585", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Business ethics", "Code of ethics", "Duty", "Engineering ethics", "Moral luck", "Moral obligation"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Mathieu Bouville", "ex:email": "m-bouville@imre.a-star.edu.sg"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:abstract": "Usury is a concept often associated more with religiously based financial ethics, whether Christian or Islamic, than with the secular world of contemporary finance. The problem is compounded by a tendency to interpret riba, prohibited within Islam, as both usury and interest, without adequately distinguishing these concepts. This paper argues that in Christian tradition usury has always evoked the notion of money demanded in excess of what is owed on a loan, disrupting a relationship of equality between people, whereas interest was seen as referring to just compensation to the lender. Although it is often claimed that hostility towards â€˜usuryâ€™ has been in retreat in the West since the protestant Reformation, we would argue that the crucial break came not with Calvin, but with Jeremy Bentham, whose critique of the arguments of Adam Smith, upholding the reasonableness of the laws against usury, led to the abolition of the usury laws in England in 1854. There has to be a role for law, whether Islamic or secular, in regulating financial relationships. We argue that by retrieving the necessary distinction between demanding usury as illegitimate predatory lending and interest as legitimate compensation, we can discover common ground behind the driving principles of financial ethics within both Islamic and Christian tradition that may still be of relevance today. By re-examining past ethical discussions of the distinction between usury and just compensation, we argue that the worldâ€™s religious traditions can make significant contributions to contemporary debate. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2007", "ex:volume": "72", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Usury and Just Compensation: Religious and Financial Ethics in Historical Perspective", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9151-0", "ex:pages": "1-15", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Usury", "Interest", "Bible", "Islamic finance", "Middle ages", "Predatory lending", "Religion", "Financial ethics"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Constant Mews", "ex:email": "Constant.Mews@arts.monash.edu.au"}, {"ex:name": "Ibrahim Abraham", "ex:email": "Ibrahim.Abraham@arts.monash.edu.au"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "92", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Toward Greater Consciousness in the 21st Century Workplace: How Buddhist Practices Fit In", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0150-9", "ex:pages": "211-225", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2010", "ex:keyword": ["Consciousness", "Buddhism", "Spirituality", "Workplace", "Swot analysis", "Buddhist practices"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Joan Marques", "ex:email": "jmarques01@earthlink.net"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "91", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Impact of Diversity Promise Fulfillment on Professionals of Color Outcomes in the USA", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0096-y", "ex:pages": "501-518", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2010", "ex:keyword": ["Diversity", "Diversity climate", "Justice", "Psychological contract", "Commitment", "Turnover intentions"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "E. Buttner", "ex:email": "ehbuttne@uncg.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Kevin Lowe"}, {"ex:name": "Lenora Billings-Harris"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "Nothing is more common in moral debates than to invoke the names of great thinkers from the past. Business ethics is no exception. Yet insofar as business ethicists have tended to simply mine abstract formulas from the past, they have missed out on the potential intellectual gains in meticulously exploring the philosophic tradition. This paper seeks to rectify this shortcoming by advocating a close reading of the so-called â€œgreat books,â€\\x9D beginning the process by focusing on Aristotle. The Nichomachean Ethics and The Politics points to Aristotleâ€™s emphasis on tying business morality to a universal conception of the good life. This conception defines personal happiness to chiefly consist in practicing the virtues, a life in which both desire and the pursuit of wealth is kept under check. According to Aristotle, virtue reaches its height with the exercise of the intellectual virtues of prudence and wisdom â€“ the first manifest in the leadership of organizations, and the second in the philosophic search for truth. From an Aristotelian point of view, therefore, the greatest ethical imperative for business is to give individuals opportunities to thoughtfully participate in the management of company affairs and to contemplate the ultimate meaning of things. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2006", "ex:volume": "67", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Seek the Good Life, not Money: The Aristotelian Approach to Business Ethics", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9026-4", "ex:pages": "341-357", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Aristotle", "Virtue", "Happiness", "Good life", "Wealth", "Leadership", "Wisdom"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "George Bragues", "ex:email": "gbragues@uoguelph.ca"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "82", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Applicability of Corporate Social Responsibility to Human Resources Management: Perspective from Spain", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9560-8", "ex:pages": "27-44", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate social responsibility", "Human resources", "Interest groups", "Sa8000 standard", "Spain"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Fernando Fuentes-García", "ex:email": "fernando.fuentes@uco.es"}, {"ex:name": "Julia Núñez-Tabales"}, {"ex:name": "Ricardo Veroz-Herradón"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:abstract": "Nuclear power has never been free from the stifling involvement of government. Heavy regulation has reduced the ability of entrepreneurs to develop and provide new means for the generation of energy using nuclear fuel. The strict parameters dictated by government officials are based upon outdated technology, an improper regulatory philosophy, and preclude innovation in nuclear power generation. Anti-market environmentalists misunderstand the implications of a free market in nuclear power and argue against it based on problems that are actually caused by government involvement. Our position is neither for nor against nuclear power. We advocate a hands-off policy where the nuclear industry is left to its own devices, free from governmental regulations and subsidies: free to succeed or fail on its own. Thus, our position is neither right-wing conservative (removing regulations), nor left-wing liberal (removing subsidies). Very much to the contrary of both positions, we propose a free-market in nuclear power. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2006", "ex:volume": "67", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Nuclear Power", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9003-y", "ex:pages": "37-49", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Nuclear", "Energy", "Price anderson", "Subsidies", "Government interference", "Nimby", "N7", "O13", "P28", "Q4"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "John Levendis", "ex:email": "johnlevendis@cba.loyno.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Walter Block"}, {"ex:name": "Joseph Morrel"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "86", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Emergence of Corporate Social Responsibility in Chile: The Importance of Authenticity and Social Networks", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0190-1", "ex:pages": "191-206", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Authenticity", "Chile", "Corporate social responsibility", "Developing countries", "Latin america", "Network theory", "Social networks"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Terry Beckman", "ex:email": "tbeckman@business.queensu.ca"}, {"ex:name": "Alison Colwell", "ex:email": "acolwell@bsr.org"}, {"ex:name": "Pegg