tility and reasonableness as a criterion to apply to real world phenomena. The paper discusses some behavioral patterns under alternative moral positions taken by observers and the firm, critiques some alternative moral principles, and considers some dynamics of moving toward, defending and maintaining, and breaching or breaking reputational bliss. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2007", "ex:volume": "72", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Concept of Reputational Bliss", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9173-7", "ex:pages": "323-333", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Reputation", "Moral positions", "Normative criteria"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Barry Mitnick"}, {"ex:name": "John Mahon", "ex:email": "mahon@maine.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:abstract": "Accounting educators are in the midst of creating new opportunities for students to enhance their abilities to recognize ethical dilemmas, establish criteria by which to make ethical decisions, and establish support mechanisms and strategies to facilitate their ethical decision-making. CPA firms, professional organizations and state boards of accountancy are co-operating to increase requirements for ethics education for candidates taking the CPA exam. The current situation is confusing and sub-optimal regarding the use of precious learning time in college programs. A new dialogue between the three stakeholders, creative learning approaches, and additional resources can lead to a more consistent and optimal learning paradigm regarding the ethics education of accountants. Research evaluating the effectiveness of various approaches is needed to effectively apply limited resources in an area critical to the reputation capital of the accounting profession. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, B.V. 2007", "ex:volume": "70", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Normative Impact of CPA Firms, Professional Organizations, and State Boards on Accounting Ethics Education", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9082-9", "ex:pages": "15-21", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Ethics", "Accounting", "Education", "Cpa", "Exam", "University", "Students"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Kevin M. Misiewicz", "ex:email": "misiewicz.1@nd.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Organizational Moral Learning: What, If Anything, Do Corporations Learn from NGO Critique?", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0112-2", "ex:pages": "157-173", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Conflict", "Crisis", "Kohlberg", "Legitimacy", "Moral learning", "Organizational development", "Organizational learning"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Heiko Spitzeck", "ex:email": "heiko.spitzeck@cranfield.ac.uk"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "Recent research on the role of ethics in the organizational culture literature found practically the whole literature reduced to a debate between ethical rationalism and ethical relativism. The role of the past in the form of tradition to maintain and improve moral reflection is completely missing. To address this gap in the literature on the level of practice, the concepts of moral memory and moral tradition are applied to data on 22 companies that have long-standing moral practices. In this way, the practice of moral traditions can be explored with recent conceptual advances and a list of best practices delineated. Moral memory is the recollection of and attachment to the succession of past events and experiences that maintains moral tradition. Moral tradition is the continuing transmission and reception of related moral themes through multiple generations of employees. It is found that companies that maintain moral traditions tend to develop â€œfamilyâ€\\x9D cultures with considerable compassion for workers as persons who have non-economic needs and rights. These companies also temper the role of leadership, insisting that leaders are responsible for and are evaluated by the companyâ€™s moral traditions. Finally, moral traditions are essential mechanisms through which companies paradoxically both stimulate and limit competitive behavior. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2007", "ex:volume": "72", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Moral Memory: Why and How Moral Companies Manage Tradition", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9177-3", "ex:pages": "395-409", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Moral memory", "Moral tradition", "Moral culture"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Steven Feldman", "ex:email": "spf@case.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "91", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Unethical and Unwell: Decrements in Well-Being and Unethical Activity at Work", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0083-3", "ex:pages": "275-297", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2010", "ex:keyword": ["Well-being", "Ethics", "Workplace"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Robert Giacalone"}, {"ex:name": "Mark Promislo", "ex:email": "ragiacal@temple.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "92", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "How do Small and Medium Enterprises Go “Green”? A Study of Environmental Management Programs in the U.S. Wine Industry", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0168-z", "ex:pages": "463-478", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2010", "ex:keyword": ["Energy conservation", "Environmental management systems", "Recycling", "Small and medium enterprises", "Stakeholder pressures", "Theory of planned behavior"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Mark Cordano", "ex:email": "mcordano@ithaca.edu"}, {"ex:name": "R. Marshall"}, {"ex:name": "Murray Silverman"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "78", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Philosophical Foundations of Workplace Spirituality: A Critical Approach", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9369-5", "ex:pages": "575-600", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Consequential approaches", "Contextual models", "Deontology", "Organisational positive outcomes", "Respectful pluralism", "Workplace spirituality", "Utilitarianism", "Virtue ethics"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "George Gotsis", "ex:email": "ggotsis@phs.uoa.gr"}, {"ex:name": "Zoi Kortezi"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "90", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Joint Moderating Impact of Moral Intensity and Moral Judgment on Consumer’s Use Intention of Pirated Software", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0046-8", "ex:pages": "361-373", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Use intention of pirated software", "Moral intensity", "Moral judgment", "Theory of planned behavior"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Mei-Fang Chen", "ex:email": "mfchen@ttu.edu.tw"}, {"ex:name": "Ching-Ti Pan"}, {"ex:name": "Ming-Chuan Pan"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "89", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Project CARE: Placer Dome’s Efforts to Help Laid-off South African Miners Find Remunerative Work", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-010-0376-6", "ex:pages": "183-190", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["South africa", "Laid-off workers", "Alternative employment", "Placer dome"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Frederick Bird", "ex:email": "fbird@uwaterloo.ca"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "83", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Studying Ethical Judgments and Behavioral Intentions Using Structural Equations: Evidence from the Multidimensional Ethics Scale*", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9644-5", "ex:pages": "627-640", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Ethical judgment", "Confirmatory factor analysis", "Structural equation models"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Nhung Nguyen", "ex:email": "nnguyen@towson.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Michael Biderman"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:abstract": "When it comes to cheating in higher education, business school students have often been accused of being the worst offenders; if true, this may be a contributing factor in the kinds of fraud that have plagued the business community in recent years. We examined the issue of cheating in the business school by surveying 268 students in business and other professional schools on their attitudes about, and experiences with, cheating. We found that while business school students actually cheated no more or less than students in other professional schools, their attitudes on what constitutes cheating are more lax than those of other professional school students. Additionally, we found that serious cheaters across all professional schools were more likely to be younger and have a lower grade point average. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media B.V. 2007", "ex:volume": "72", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Cheating During the College Years: How do Business School Students Compare?", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9165-7", "ex:pages": "197-206", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Academic dishonesty", "Cheating", "Cheating attitudes", "Cheating behaviors", "Cheating in business schools", "Cheating in professional schools", "Ethics"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Helen Klein", "ex:email": "kleinh@gvsu.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Nancy Levenburg", "ex:email": "levenbun@gvsu.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Marie McKendall", "ex:email": "mckendam@gvsu.edu"}, {"ex:name": "William Mothersell", "ex:email": "mothersw@gvsu.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:abstract": "Union security has long been an industrial relations controversy. While compulsory unionism supporters say it benefits the working class, right-to-work advocates denounce it as an unethical infringement of individual rights and freedom. Unfortunately, neither side has adequately addressed the shortcomings of their viewpoint, nor the broader worker concerns about effective representation beyond just â€œunionismâ€\\x9D. In this paper, we examine the ethical and practical problems of compulsory (union security) and voluntary (right-to-work) unionism and propose a new resolution, compulsory proportional representation, that has the advantages of: (a) ensuring workersâ€™ freedom to associate or not associate, (b) promoting freedom to contract, (c) allowing free competition in representation in line with anti-trust principles, (d) improving industrial peace and efficiency, (e) enhancing fairness and social justice, and (f) addressing the employerâ€“employee power imbalance. It is superior to either voluntary unionism, which often lead to management unilateralism, or compulsory unionism, where workers are compelled to join unions against their will. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2007", "ex:volume": "73", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "A New Approach to Resolving the Right-to-work Ethical Dilemma", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9203-5", "ex:pages": "231-243", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Compulsory unionism", "Freedom of association", "Right-to-work", "Union security", "Voluntary unionism", "Worker representation"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Helen Lam", "ex:email": "helenl@athabascau.ca"}, {"ex:name": "Mark Harcourt", "ex:email": "mark@mngt.waikato.ac.nz"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:abstract": "Integrating â€œethics all the way throughâ€\\x9D an organization suggests that the issue of moral agency and the corporation be reconsidered. Is the corporation a moral agent in some sense or is it no more than the people who are a part of the organization? Views which stress the role of the individual lose sight of the whole corporate entity, and views which think of the corporation as a collective lose sight of the individual. A view which rejects both these alternatives sees the corporation as a type of community where there is a dynamic tension between the corporation as a whole and the individuals who are part of the organization. This view has implications relative to the focus of efforts to integrate ethics throughout an organization. Copyright Springer 2006", "ex:volume": "66", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Integrating Ethics All the Way Through: The Issue of Moral Agency Reconsidered", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-005-5588-9", "ex:pages": "233-239", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Rogene Buchholz", "ex:email": "buchholz@loyno.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Sandra Rosenthal", "ex:email": "rosenth@loyno.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "89", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Using the Analytical Hierarchy Process (AHP) to Construct a Measure of the Magnitude of Consequences Component of Moral Intensity", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-0006-8", "ex:pages": "391-407", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Ethics", "Moral reasoning", "Moral intensity", "Magnitude of consequences", "Analytical hierarchy process", "Nature of harm", "Mathematical model", "Law", "Legal data", "Jury awards", "Decision making", "Decision support"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Eric Stein", "ex:email": "ews3@psu.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Norita Ahmad"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "84", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Transparent Practices: Primary and Secondary Data in Business Ethics Dissertations", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9717-0", "ex:pages": "417-425", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Business ethics", "Datasets", "Doctoral research", "Open data", "Primary data", "Secondary data"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Shawn Nicholson", "ex:email": "nicho147@msu.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Terrence Bennett"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "87", "ex:source": "Jou