 of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Degussa AG and its Holocaust Legacy", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0147-4", "ex:pages": "183-194", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2010", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate social responsibility", "Holocaust", "Historical legacy", "Atonement", "Business ethics case"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Al Rosenbloom", "ex:email": "arosenbloom@dom.edu"}, {"ex:name": "RuthAnn Althaus", "ex:email": "althaus@ohio.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:abstract": "Archetypal psychology suggests the possibility of a leadership archetype representing the unconscious preferences of human beings as a species about the appropriate relationships between leaders and followers. Mythological analysis compared Godâ€™s leadership in the Abraham myth with modern visionary, ethical and situational leadership to find similarities reflecting continuities in human thinking about leadership over as long as 3600Â years. Godâ€™s leadership behavior is very modern except that God is generally more relationship oriented. The leadership archetype that emerges is of a leader that develops his/her follower by reliably maintaining a vision, behaving according to firm ethical values even when it weakens the leaderâ€™s authority, accepting suffering when the follower is unreliable, and always forgiving even when the follower behaves with hubris in an attempt to overthrow the leader. If Godâ€™s leadership principles were mandatory in management, many dysfunctional leaders would be disqualified and many of the negative consequences of poor leadership might be averted. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media B.V. 2007", "ex:volume": "72", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Leadership Archetype: A Jungian Analysis of Similarities between Modern Leadership Theory and the Abraham Myth in the Judaicâ€“Christian Tradition", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9159-5", "ex:pages": "115-129", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Archetypal psychology", "Archetype", "Jung", "Leadership", "Visionary ethical situational forgiveness", "God", "Abraham", "Myth", "Narrative analysis", "Mythological analysis"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Neil Abramson", "ex:email": "nabramso@sfu.ca"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "66", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Business Ethics Training: Face-to-face and at a Distance", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9053-1", "ex:pages": "117-126", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Customized ethics training", "Distance learning", "Discourse ethics"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Warren French", "ex:email": "wfrench@terry.uga.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "92", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Stakeholder Forces of Socially Responsible Supply Chain Management Orientation", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0156-3", "ex:pages": "305-322", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2010", "ex:keyword": ["Supply chain", "Clothing", "Sweatshop", "Social responsibility"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Haesun Park-Poaps", "ex:email": "hpark@lsu.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Kathleen Rees"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Human Rights as a Dimension of CSR: The Blurred Lines Between Legal and Non-Legal Categories", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0315-6", "ex:pages": "561-577", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["George kell", "Global compact", "Human rights", "John ruggie", "Kofi annan", "Norms on the responsibilities of transnational corporations", "Universal declaration of human rights"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Ann Mayer", "ex:email": "mayera@wharton.upenn.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "A Multidimensional Approach to the Influence of Environmental Marketing and Orientation on the Firm’s Organizational Performance", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9962-2", "ex:pages": "263-286", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Environmental marketing", "Environmental orientation", "Sustainability", "Operational performance", "Commercial performance", "Economic performance"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Elena Fraj-Andrés", "ex:email": "efraj@unizar.es"}, {"ex:name": "Eva Martinez-Salinas"}, {"ex:name": "Jorge Matute-Vallejo"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "84", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "A Genealogy of Business Ethics: A Nietzschean Perspective", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9718-z", "ex:pages": "427-456", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Christianity", "Egoism", "Equality", "Justice", "Morality", "Nietzsche", "Religion", "Science", "Stakeholder"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Skip Worden", "ex:email": "skipworden@gmail.com"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "74", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Women Leaders in a Globalized World", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9516-z", "ex:pages": "425-435", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Globalization", "Leadership", "Women leaders", "Systems thinking"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Patricia Werhane", "ex:email": "WerhaneP@darden.virginia.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:abstract": "Finance is grease to the economy. Therefore, we assume that it may affect corporate social responsibility (CSR) and the sustainability of economic development too. This paper discusses the transmission mechanisms between finance and sustainability. We find that there is no simple one-to-one relationship between financial development and sustainable development but there are various â€“ often indirect â€“ linkages. It appears that most of the literature concentrates on the role of public shareholders when it comes to changing corporate policy and performance in a more sustainable direction. However, this focus neglects the potential impact of the credit channel and private equity on a firmâ€™s non-financial policies and performance. These very powerful mechanisms can govern business policies and practices. Therefore, there appears to be much more scope for finance to promote socially and environmentally desirable activities and to discourage detrimental activities than has been acknowledged in the academic literature so far. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2006", "ex:volume": "68", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Finance as a Driver of Corporate Social Responsibility", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9037-1", "ex:pages": "19-33", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Banks", "Corporate social responsibility", "Development", "Ethics", "Financial markets", "Socially responsible investments", "Sustainable development", "G200", "G300", "L210", "M140", "Z130"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Bert Scholtens", "ex:email": "L.J.R.Scholtens@rug.nl"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "80", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Corporate Social Performance Content of Innovation in the U.K.", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9464-7", "ex:pages": "711-725", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["M14", "O31", "Corporate social performance", "Innovation"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Stephen Pavelin", "ex:email": "s.pavelin@reading.ac.uk"}, {"ex:name": "Lynda Porter"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:abstract": "This paper examines how good management can repair fractured relationships within organisations, addressing problems that if left unattended will threaten the future existence of many of these companies. It analyses why there is a mood for change in management thinking, and what direction that change can take. Part of the challenge is how managers can best satisfy the objectives of corporate social responsibility initiatives, and repair organisational and fractured community relationships. A possible role for management is to examine alternative ways of thinking about the potential benefits for the organisation that can be achieved by enhancing employee relationships. In this regard, this paper offers strategies to examine managementâ€™s adverse affects on workersâ€™ life-plans. The art of interpretation is used to expose how bureaucratic logic ignores workersâ€™ rights and potentially damages the corporationâ€™s longevity. Interpretation, as opposed to procedure, suggests that organisations are not simply profit mechanisms, but active and dynamic civil societies. By better understanding the facilitating processes of administrative and management thinking, it is possible that we can develop alternative strategies that empower individuals to circumvent the negative consequences of instrumental rationality and enable them to act more responsibly in the public interest. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2007", "ex:volume": "71", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "A Common Pitch and The Management of Corporate Relations: Interpretation, Ethics and Managerialism", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9132-3", "ex:pages": "161-178", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Civil society", "Corporate social responsibility initiatives", "Hermeneutics", "Organisational and fractured community relationships"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Glen Lehman", "ex:email": "glen.lehman@unisa.edu.au"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "87", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Global Software Piracy: Searching for Further Explanations", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9884-z", "ex:pages": "269-283", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Culture", "Economic development", "Ict", "Software piracy"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Deli Yang", "ex:email": "d.yang@bradford.ac.uk"}, {"ex:name": "Mahmut Sonmez", "ex:email": "m.sonmez@lboro.ac.uk"}, {"ex:name": "Derek Bosworth", "ex:email": "derek.bosworth@btinternet.com"}, {"ex:name": "Gerald Fryxell", "ex:email": "fryxell@ceibs.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "This paper draws from the fields of history, sociology, psychology, moral philosophy, and organizational theory to establish a theoretical connection between a social/organizational influence (ethical work climate) and an individual cognitive element of moral behavior (moral awareness). The research was designed to help to fill a gap in the existing literature by providing empirical evidence of the connection between organizational influences and individual moral awareness and subsequent ethical choices, which has heretofore largely been merely assumed. Results of the study provide evidence that ethical work climate (EWC) is a primary predictor of individual moral awareness, and that the influence of social factors often overrides the effects of individual differences in a work group setting. Implications for future research are provided. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2006", "ex:volume": "68", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "An Examination of the Relationship Between Ethical Work Climate and Moral Awareness", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9030-8", "ex:pages": "409-432", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Ethical work climate", "Moral awareness"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Craig VanSandt", "ex:email": "szappe@minitab.com"}, {"ex:name": "Jon Shepard", "ex:email": "jshepard@vt.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Stephen Zappe", "ex:email": "smz122@psu.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Introduction to Central America and Mexico: Efforts and Obstacles in Creating Ethical Organizations and an Ethical Economy", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0292-9", "ex:pages": "225-230", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Denis Collins", "ex:email": "dcollins@edgewood.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Julie Whitaker", "ex:email": "jwhitaker@edgewood.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "91", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Islam and CSR: A Study of the Compatibility Between the Tenets of Islam and the UN Global Compact", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0097-x", "ex:pages": "519-533", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2010", "ex:keyword": ["Csr", "Islam", "Un global compact", "Environment", "Human rights", "Labour rights"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Geoffrey Williams", "ex:email": "enquiries@oww-consulting.com"}, {"ex:name": "John Zinkin", "ex:email": "jzinkin@streamx.com"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "A Novel Approach to Business Ethics Training: Improving Moral Reasoning in Just a Few Weeks", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9969-8", "ex:pages": "367-379", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Business ethics training", "Moral judgment", "Moral reasoning", "Defining issues test"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "David Jones", "ex:email": "dajones@bsad.uvm.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:abstract": "The purpose of this study is to understand the drivers of social responsibility in purchasing (PSR). This study replicated and extended the range of empirical application of the model developed by Carter and Jennings (Journal of Business Logistics 25(1), 145–186, 2004). Consequently, the present study contributes to the nomological validity of concept of PSR or Purchasing Social Responsibility. The method used is derived from the previous study by Carter and Jennings (Journal of Business Logistics 25(1), 145–186, 2004), and the present study extends the application of that method to an Asian environment. The data were obtained from 197 respondents in Thailand. This sample was largely composed of purchasing and supply chain managers. Respondents were asked to indicate how different dimensions of corporate social responsibility (CSR) affect PSR. The findings of the present study suggest that all the six hypothesized paths have been substantiated. Individual values and people-oriented organizational culture are the most powerful predictors of PSR. This article contributes towards filling the gap in understanding the determinants of PSR in managing supply chains, particularly in an Asian context. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media B.V. 2009", "ex:volume": "85", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "RETRACTED ARTICLE: Corporate Social Responsibility in Purchasing and Supply Chain", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9733-0", "ex:pages": "355-370", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate social responsibility", "Purchasing", "Supply chain", "Thailand"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Mohammad Salam", "ex:email": "mbamas@yahoo.com"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "This article presents the results of a study that investigated the roles that oneâ€™s money ethic, religiosity and attitude toward business play in determining consumer attitudes/beliefs in various situations regarding questionable consumer practices. Two dimensions of religiosity â€“ intrinsic and extrinsic religiousness â€“ were studied. A global scale of money ethic was examined, as was a global measure of attitude toward business. Results indicate that both types of religiosity as well as oneâ€™s money ethic and attitude toward business were significant determinants of at least some types of consumer ethical beliefs. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2007", "ex:volume": "73", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Consumersâ€™ Ethical Beliefs: The Roles of Money, Religiosity and Attitude toward Business", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9212-4", "ex:pages": "369-379", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Attitude toward business", "Consumer ethics", "Religiosity", "Role of money"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Scott Vitell", "ex:email": "yotam@bgu.ac.il"}, {"ex:name": "Jatinder Singh"}, {"ex:name": "Joseph Paolillo"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Conciliating Work and Family: A Catholic Social Teaching Perspective", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0119-8", "ex:pages": "513-524", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Catholic social teaching", "Corporate social responsibility", "Work–family balance", "Work–family conflict", "Work–family enrichment"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Gregorio Guitián", "ex:email": "gguitian@unav.es"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Ambition Versus Conscience, Does Corporate Social Responsibility Pay off? The Application of Matching Methods", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9826-9", "ex:pages": "133-153", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate social responsibility", "Selection bias", "Matching method", "G30", "M14"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Chung-Hua Shen"}, {"ex:name": "Yuan Chang", "ex:email": "ccuecon@yahoo.com.tw"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "78", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Ethical Leadership for the Professions: Fostering a Moral Community", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9309-9", "ex:pages": "39-46", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Ethical leadership", "Moral community", "Professional business"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Linda Sama", "ex:email": "lsama@pace.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Victoria Shoaf", "ex:email": "shoafv@stjohns.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:abstract": "We examine how UK listed companies set executive pay, reviewing the implications of following best practice in corporate governance and examining how this can conflict with what shareholders and other stakeholders might perceive as good behaviour. We do this by considering current governance regulation in the light of interviews with protagonists in the debate, setting out the dilemmas faced by remuneration-setters, and showing how the processes they follow can lead to ethical conflicts. Current â€˜bestâ€™ practice governing executive pay includes the use of market benchmarks to determine salary and bonus levels, significant levels of performance-related pay, the desire for executives to hold equity in their companies, the disclosure of total shareholder return compared to an index, and a perceived need for conformity, in order to grant legitimacy to policies. Whilst each of these may in some circumstances lead to good practice, each has the potential to cause dysfunctional behaviour in executives. Overall, we conclude that although best practice might drive good executive behaviour that coincides with the companyâ€™s and key stakeholdersâ€™ objectives, there are many reasons why it should not. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2006", "ex:volume": "67", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Does â€˜Best Practiceâ€™ in Setting Executive Pay in the UK Encourage â€˜Goodâ€™ Behaviour?", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9006-8", "ex:pages": "75-91", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Compensation", "Ethics", "Executive", "Governance", "Remuneration", "Stakeholder"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Ruth Bender", "ex:email": "r.bender@cranfield.ac.uk"}, {"ex:name": "Lance Moir"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Putting a Stake in Stakeholder Theory", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0310-y", "ex:pages": "605-615", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate citizenship", "Corporate governance", "Corporate social responsibility", "Shareholder primacy", "Social initiatives", "Stakeholder theory"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Eric Orts", "ex:email": "ortse@wharton.upenn.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Alan Strudler"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "80", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "A Perspective of Collective Consciousness of Business Organizations", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9475-4", "ex:pages": "889-898", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Ethics", "Market", "Organizational consciousness", "Social and spiritual consciousness"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Ashish Pandey", "ex:email": "ashishp75@rediffmail.com"}, {"ex:name": "Rajen Gupta", "ex:email": "rgupta@mdi.sc.in"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "In a world which can be increasingly described as a â€œsociety of organizations,â€\\x9D it is incumbent upon organizational researchers to account for the role of organizations in determining the well-being of societies and the individuals that comprise them. Workplace spirituality is a young area of inquiry with potentially strong relevance to the well-being of individuals, organizations, and societies. Previous literature has not examined ethical dilemmas related to workplace spirituality that organizations might expect based upon the co-existence of multiple ethical work climates, nor has previous literature accounted for the relevance of the cosmopolitan (external, societal) source of moral reasoning in the ethical treatment of workplace spirituality. The purpose of this paper is to address these gaps by articulating two such ethical dilemmas related to workplace spirituality: the â€œquiet desperationâ€\\x9D dilemma and the instrumentality dilemma. Moreover, I propose two theoretical contexts that foster â€œboth-andâ€\\x9D rather than â€œeither-orâ€\\x9D thinking, thereby mitigating (moderating) the relationships between climate combinations and conflictual aspects of the ethical dilemmas. For the â€œquiet desperationâ€\\x9D dilemma, I propose a personâ€“organization fit perspective to emphasize diversity of individual preferences instead of a managerially prescribed uniformity of spirituality. For the instrumentality dilemma, I propose a multiparadigm approach to workplace spirituality research to avoid the privileging of one research interest over another (e.g., instrumentality, individual fulfillment, societal good). I conclude with suggestions for future research. Copyright Springer 2006", "ex:volume": "66", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Nurturing the Whole Person: The Ethics of Workplace Spirituality in a Society of Organizations", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-0014-5", "ex:pages": "357-375", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Workplace spirituality", "Social systems", "Ethical work climate", "Ethical dilemma", "Personâ€“organization fit", "Multiparadigm research"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Mathew Sheep", "ex:email": "sheepml@email.uc.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "74", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Stakeholder Capitalism", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9517-y", "ex:pages": "303-314", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Capitalism", "Stakeholder", "Ethics", "Economics", "Free market"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "R. Freeman", "ex:email": "freemane@darden.virginia.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Kirsten Martin", "ex:email": "martink@cua.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Bidhan Parmar", "ex:email": "Parmarb07@darden.virginia.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Islamic Work Ethic and the Emergence of Turkish SME Owner-Managers", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0107-z", "ex:pages": "211-225", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Islam", "Secularism", "Sme", "The theory of structuration", "Turkey", "Weber", "Work ethic"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Selçuk Uygur", "ex:email": "selcuk.uygur@brunel.ac.uk"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "86", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "An Optimally Viable Version of Stakeholder Theory", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9848-3", "ex:pages": "297-312", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Co-determination", "Competitive collaboration", "Contributory principle", "Economic functioning", "Risk", "Stakeholder", "Stockholder", "Work-related risk"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "J. Kaler", "ex:email": "john.kaler@ukf.net"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:abstract": "Urban communities in 21st century America are facing severe economic challenges, ones that suggest a mandate to contemplate serious changes in the way America does business. The middle class is diminishing in many parts of the country, with consequences for the economy as a whole. When faced with the loss of its economic base, any business community must make some difficult decisions about its proper role and responsibilities. Decisions to support the community must be balanced alongside and against responsibilities to owners, shareholders and relevant â€œstakeholdersâ€\\x9D in a relatively new context. Corporations in urban communities â€œhollowed outâ€\\x9D by white flight or urban sprawl must decide what level of support they can and should provide. This paper examines corporate decisions within the emerging urban prosperity initiatives, using the framework of integrative social contract theory proposed by Donaldson and Dunfee. We suggest that urban prosperity initiatives present a mandate on corporations sufficiently strong as to qualify as an authentic norm. Further, we argue that strict adherence to a corporate bottom line approach or â€œcorporate isolationismâ€\\x9D is not congruent with contemporary community standards. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2007", "ex:volume": "72", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Integrative Social Contract Theory and Urban Prosperity Initiatives", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9169-3", "ex:pages": "263-278", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Integrative social contract theory", "Authentic norm", "Community prosperity", "Community engagement", "Corporate social responsibility"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Anita Cava", "ex:email": "acava@miami.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Don Mayer"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "75", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Promise of a Managerial Values Approach to Corporate Philanthropy", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9257-4", "ex:pages": "345-359", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate financial performance", "Corporate philanthropy", "Managerial values", "Stakeholders"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Jaepil Choi"}, {"ex:name": "Heli Wang", "ex:email": "mnheli@ust.hk"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "84", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Working to Live or Living to Work: Should Individuals and Organizations Care?", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9703-6", "ex:pages": "167-172", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Work hours", "Work addiction", "Social costs", "Ethical issues"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Ronald Burke", "ex:email": "rburke@schulich.yorku.ca"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:abstract": "Despite a plethora of laws prohibiting discrimination in employment, supporting and enforcing equal employment opportunity (EEO) principles has proven to be an enormous challenge for those charged with this responsibility. The question often asked is who should exercise this role in organizations. Not surprisingly, there has been a call for HRM to become the guardian of EEO in organizations but should human resource managers be male or female, and/or would line managers be better positioned to assume this responsibility? This paper overviews the literature and then summarizes an empirical study that attempted to address the possible impact of these options as they exist in organizations. One hundred and eighty respondents who met the criterion of having interviewed one or more job applicants in the previous 6Â months were systematically selected from business telephone listings. Based on self-reported behaviors, no significant difference was found between the expected and actual distributions of HR and line managers in respect to whether decisions were made on unlawful grounds. The percentage of each respondent category that asked unlawful questions varied from 1% to 36% depending upon the attribute (unlawful ground of discrimination) under consideration. This begs the question as to what value HR managers contribute to EEO in the selection process. The second finding was that significantly less female managers admit to making decisions on the basis of unlawful questions than male managers. Thus, support was found for female line managers as guardians of EEO but no clear justification for HRM in this role. Copyright Springer 2006", "ex:volume": "65", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "HRM Role in EEO: Sheep in Shepherdâ€™s Clothing?", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-005-0846-4", "ex:pages": "13-21", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Discrimination in employment", "Equal employment opportunity", "Human resource managers", "Illegal/unlawful behavior"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Lynne Bennington", "ex:email": "lynne.bennington@rmit.edu.au"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:abstract": "This study examines factors impacting ethical behavior of 203 hospital employees in Midwestern and Northwestern United States. Ethical behavior of peers had the most significant impact on ethical behavior. Ethical behavior of successful managers, professional education in ethics and sex of the respondents also significantly impacted ethical behavior. Nurses were significantly more ethical than other employees. Race of the respondent did not impact ethical behavior. Overclaiming scales indicated that social desirability bias did not significantly impact the results of our study. Implications of this study for researchers and practitioners are discussed. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2006", "ex:volume": "69", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Factors Impacting Ethical Behavior in Hospitals", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9086-5", "ex:pages": "207-216", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Hospitals", "Ethical behavior", "Nurses", "Overclaiming", "Ethical optimism"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Satish Deshpande", "ex:email": "satish.deshpande@wmich.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Jacob Joseph", "ex:email": "ffjj@uaf.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Rashmi Prasad", "ex:email": "afrp2@cbpp.uaa.alaska.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "84", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Spiritual Leadership as a Paradigm for Organizational Transformation and Recovery from Extended Work Hours Cultures", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9695-2", "ex:pages": "265-278", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Spiritual leadership", "Workaholism", "Organizational transformation", "Organizational culture"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Louis Fry", "ex:email": "lwf@tarleton.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Melanie Cohen", "ex:email": "Melanie.cohen@hud.gov"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "77", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "De-marketing Tobacco Through Price Changes and Consumer Attempts Quit Smoking", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9356-x", "ex:pages": "405-416", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Addiction", "Canada", "Consumer behavior", "De-marketing", "Marketing", "Motivation", "Panel data", "Smoking", "Theory of planned behavior", "Tobacco"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Michelle Inness", "ex:email": "michelle.inness@ualberta.ca"}, {"ex:name": "Julian Barling"}, {"ex:name": "Keith Rogers"}, {"ex:name": "Nick Turner"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "81", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Ethical Behaviour of Tertiary Education Students in Cyprus", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9538-6", "ex:pages": "647-663", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Cyprus", "Tertiary education", "Students ethical standing"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Anastasios Zopiatis", "ex:email": "zopiatis@yahoo.com"}, {"ex:name": "Maria Krambia-Kapardis"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "74", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Communication of Corporate Social Responsibility: United States and European Union Multinational Corporations", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9513-2", "ex:pages": "373-389", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate social responsibility", "Corporate communications", "Transnational comparative analysis", "Social reporting"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Laura Hartman", "ex:email": "LHartman@depaul.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Robert Rubin"}, {"ex:name": "K. Dhanda"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "83", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Interpreting Structural Equation Modeling Results: A Reply to Martin and Cullen", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9634-7", "ex:pages": "365-368", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Sem modeling", "Fit indices", "Ethical climate theory"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Paul Dion", "ex:email": "dion@susqu.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "74", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Great Forgotten Issue: Vindicating Ethics in the European Qualifications Framework (EQF)", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9515-0", "ex:pages": "409-423", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Ethics", "Learning", "Competences", "Education", "Virtues"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Manuel GuillÃ©n", "ex:email": "Manuel.Guillen@uv.es"}, {"ex:name": "Joan Fontrodona", "ex:email": "Fontrodona@iese.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Alfredo RodrÃ­guez-Sedano", "ex:email": "arsedano@unav.es"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "Previous accounting ethics research berates auditors for ethical lapses that contribute to the failure of Andersen (e.g., Duska, R.: 2005, Journal of Business Ethics 57, 17â€“29; Staubus, G.: 2005, Journal of Business Ethics 57, 5â€“15; however, some of the blame must also fall on regulatory and professional bodies that exist to mitigate auditorsâ€™ ethical lapses. In this paper, we consider the ethical and economic context that existed and facilitated Andersenâ€™s failure. Our analysis is grounded in Akerlofâ€™s (1970, Quarterly Journal of Economics August, 488â€“500) Theory of the Market for Lemons and we characterize the market for audit reports as a market for lemons. Consistent with Akerlofâ€™s model, we consider the appropriateness of the countervailing mechanisms that existed at the time of Andersenâ€™s demise that appeared to have effectively failed in counteracting Andersenâ€™s ethical shortcomings. Finally, we assess the appropriateness of the remedies proposed by the Sarbanesâ€“Oxley Act of 2002 (SOA) to ensure that similar ethical lapses will not occur in the future. Our analysis indicates that the SOA regulatory reforms should counteract some of the necessary conditions of the Lemons Model, and thereby mitigate the likelihood of audit failures. However, we contend that the effectiveness of the SOA critically depends upon the focus and attention of theâ\\x90£Public Companies Accounting Oversight Board (PCAOB) towards assessing the ethical climates of public accounting firms. Assessments by the PCAOB of public accounting firmâ€™s ethical climate are needed to sufficiently ensure that public accounting firms effectively promote and maintain audit quality in situations where unconscious bias or economic incentives may erode the public accounting firmâ€™s independence. Copyright Springer 2007", "ex:volume": "70", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Andersen and the Market for Lemons in Audit Reports", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9115-4", "ex:pages": "363-373", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Auditor independence", "Audit quality", "Information asymmetry", "Market for lemons", "Public interest"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Steven Kaplan", "ex:email": "Steve.Kaplan@asu.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Pamela Roush", "ex:email": "pamela.roush@bus.ucf.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Linda Thorne"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Leadership and the Ethics of Care", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0105-1", "ex:pages": "3-4", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Care", "Crisis", "Duty", "Leadership ethics", "Leaders’ presence", "Nero"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Joanne Ciulla", "ex:email": "jciulla@richmond.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "76", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Creation of Value Through Corporate Reputation", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9285-0", "ex:pages": "335-346", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Social performance", "Financial performance", "Corporate reputation", "Stakeholder theory", "Value management", "Intangible assets"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "JosÃ© Luis SÃ¡nchez", "ex:email": "fernandezjl@unican.es"}, {"ex:name": "Ladislao SotorrÃ­o"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "As corporate social responsibility involves a voluntary business endeavour to address social and environmental issues beyond legal compliance, governments cannot fall back on hierarchical command-and-control policies to support it. As such, it is complementary with the increasing popularity of public policies known as New Governance policies, where the government is engaged in a horizontal inter-organizational network of societal actors and where public policy is both formed and executed by the interacting and voluntary efforts from a multitude of stakeholders. However, such policies are known to generate substantive uncertainty about the content of CSR and its related issues, strategic uncertainty regarding the behavior of the actors involved and institutional uncertainty related to the interaction process involved in the institutional change. We explore New Governance policy instruments to address these uncertainties in the context CSR and discuss the experiences with these methods in the European Union. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2007", "ex:volume": "73", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Dealing With Uncertainties When Governing CSR Policies", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9214-2", "ex:pages": "391-408", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate social responsibility", "Uncertainty", "New governance", "Public policy", "Policy instruments"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Jan Lepoutre", "ex:email": "jan.lepoutre@ugent.be"}, {"ex:name": "Nikolay Dentchev"}, {"ex:name": "AimÃ© Heene"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Determinants of Managerial Values on Corporate Social Responsibility: Evidence from China", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9828-7", "ex:pages": "105-117", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate social responsibility", "Profit maximisation", "China"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Liangrong Zu", "ex:email": "l.zu@itcilo.org"}, {"ex:name": "Lina Song", "ex:email": "lina.song@nottingham.ac.uk"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:abstract": "A mutual fund family incubates a fund when it creates a privately subsidized fund not available to the general investing public. It destroys unsuccessful incubator funds. The few successful funds will report higher incubation returns than the market return in advertisements intended to attract money from individual investors. This practice is currently allowed by the SEC. The evidence is that incubation returns are not a good predictor of subsequent fund performance and likely serve to mislead unsuspecting investors. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2007", "ex:volume": "70", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Mutual Fund Incubation and the Role of the Securities and Exchange Commission", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9081-x", "ex:pages": "33-37", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Mutual funds", "Incubation", "Securities and exchange commission"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Carl Ackermann", "ex:email": "Ackermann.1@nd.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Tim Loughran", "ex:email": "Loughran.9@nd.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "85", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Introduction: Corporate Social Responsibility Implementation", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9732-1", "ex:pages": "251-256", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Adam Lindgreen", "ex:email": "a.lindgreen@hull.ac.uk"}, {"ex:name": "Valérie Swaen", "ex:email": "valerie.swaen@uclouvain.be"}, {"ex:name": "François Maon", "ex:email": "francois.maon@uclouvain.be"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:abstract": "I offer a new cartography of ethical resistance. I argue that there is an uncharted interaction between managerial secrecy and organizational silence, which may exponentially increase the incidence of corruption in ways not yet understood. Current methods used to raise levels of moral conduct in business and government practice appear blind to this powerful duo. Extensive literature reviews of secrecy and silence scholarships form the background for an early stage conceptual layout of the co-production of secrecy and silence. Copyright Springer 2006", "ex:volume": "65", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Brother Secret, Sister Silence: Sibling Conspiracies Against Managerial Integrity", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-005-4710-3", "ex:pages": "219-234", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Organizational silence", "Secrecy", "Ethical resisters"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "William Maria", "ex:email": "b.demaria@business.uq.edu.au"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "85", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "An Integrated Approach to Implementing ‹Community Participation’ in Corporate Community Involvement: Lessons from Magadi Soda Company in Kenya", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9739-7", "ex:pages": "431-444", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate citizenship", "Corporate community involvement", "Community participation", "Social interaction", "Stakeholder relationships", "Developing countries"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Judy Muthuri", "ex:email": "lixjnm@nottingham.ac.uk"}, {"ex:name": "Wendy Chapple"}, {"ex:name": "Jeremy Moon"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "Moral hypocrisy is motivation to appear moral yet, if possible, avoid the cost of actually being moral. In business, moral hypocrisy allows one to engender trust, solve the commitment problem, and still relentlessly pursue personal gain. Indicating the power of this motive, research has provided clear and consistent evidence that, given the opportunity, many people act to appear fair (e.g., they flip a coin to distribute resources between themselves and another person) without actually being fair (they accept the flip only if it favors themselves). New evidence also indicates the power of moral hypocrisy in a situation more obviously relevant to business, resource allocation when one party has information about relative resource value that the other does not. Characteristics of modern business situations likely to encourage moral hypocrisy are outlined. We conclude that moral hypocrisy is not only a pragmatic virtue in modern business but is also fast becoming a prescriptive one. Copyright Springer 2006", "ex:volume": "66", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "â€˜Doing Business After the Fall: The Virtue of Moral Hypocrisyâ€™", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-0011-8", "ex:pages": "321-335", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Moral hypocrisy", "Moral integrity", "Trust", "Reputation", "Commitment problem"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "C. Batson", "ex:email": "dbatson@ku.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Elizabeth Collins"}, {"ex:name": "Adam Powell"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "82", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Reorienting the Business School Agenda: The Case for Relevance, Rigor, and Righteousness", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9607-x", "ex:pages": "985-999", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Altruism", "Business school agenda", "Management education", "Relevance versus rigor", "Righteousness", "Self-interest"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Andreas Birnik"}, {"ex:name": "Jon Billsberry", "ex:email": "j.billsberry@open.ac.uk"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "86", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "What Plato Knew About Enron", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9858-1", "ex:pages": "463-471", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Accounting fraud", "Corporate image", "Enron", "Ethics", "Kenneth lay", "Plato"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Michele Henderson", "ex:email": "hendersm@queens.edu"}, {"ex:name": "M. Gregory Oakes", "ex:email": "oakesm@winthrop.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Marilyn Smith", "ex:email": "smithm@winthrop.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "Egypt, a less affluent, predominantly Muslim country, suffers from numerous forms of environmental pollution, some severe. This study investigates pro-environmental behaviors of citizens in Cairo, Egyptâ€™s largest metropolis, and studies the relationship between pro-environmental behavior and demographic variables, beliefs, values, and religiosity. Analysis shows that three types of pro-environmental behavior are present: Public Sphere, Private Sphere, and Activist Behavior, with the latter occurring less frequently. Importantly, the study identifies an ecocentric value among respondents which is correlated with Public Sphere Behavior. It also confirms earlier research that characterized Egyptiansâ€™ perceptions of the environment as being set in the context of health and cleanliness. Religious teachings and religiosity are shown to be associated with pro-environmental behavior, thus lending support to the presence of an Islamic environmental ethic. Copyright Springer 2006", "ex:volume": "65", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Pro-environmental Behavior in Egypt: Is there a Role for Islamic Environmental Ethics?", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-0010-9", "ex:pages": "373-390", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Egypt", "Environmental behavior", "Environmental ethics", "Islam", "Individual values"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Gillian Rice", "ex:email": "riceg@t-bird.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "87", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Spanish Discourse on Corporate Social Responsibility", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9810-4", "ex:pages": "157-171", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Discourse", "Discursive fields", "Discourse analysis", "Crs", "Spanish discourse on CSR", "Stakeholders"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Natàlia Cantó-Milà", "ex:email": "ncantom@uoc.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Josep Lozano"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "81", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Impacts of Corporate Code of Conduct on Labor Standards: A Case Study of Reebok’s Athletic Footwear Supplier Factory in China", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9521-2", "ex:pages": "513-529", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Athletic footwear industry", "China", "Corporate codes of conduct", "Corporate social responsibility", "Labor standards", "Reebok", "Trade union", "Wages"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Xiaomin Yu", "ex:email": "shellymyu@yahoo.com.cn"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "78", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Hypocrisies of Fairness: Towards a More Reflexive Ethical Base in Organizational Justice Research and Practice", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9330-z", "ex:pages": "415-433", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Fairness", "Justice", "Managerialist research", "Organizational behavior", "Power"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Marion Fortin", "ex:email": "marion.fortin@durham.ac.uk"}, {"ex:name": "Martin Fellenz", "ex:email": "martin.fellenz@tcd.ie"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "79", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Corporate Social Responsibility, Investor Protection, and Earnings Management: Some International Evidence", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9383-7", "ex:pages": "179-198", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["G21", "G34", "G38", "M41", "Corporate governance", "Corporate social responsibility", "Earnings management", "Earnings opacity", "Investor protection"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Hsiang-Lin Chih", "ex:email": "hlchih@mail.ntpu.edu.tw"}, {"ex:name": "Chung-Hua Shen", "ex:email": "chshen@nccu.edu.tw"}, {"ex:name": "Feng-Ching Kang", "ex:email": "amykang@sw.ccu.edu.tw"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "To date, research into socially responsible investment (SRI), and in particular the socially responsible investment funds industry, has focused on whether investing in SRI assets has any differential impact on investor returns. Prior findings generally suggest that, on a risk-adjusted basis, there is no difference in performance between SRI and conventional funds. This result has led to questions about whether SRI funds are really any different from conventional funds. This paper examines whether the portfolio allocation across industry sectors and the stock-picking ability of SRI managers are different when compared to conventional fund managers. The study finds that SRI funds exhibit different industry betas consistent with different portfolio positions, but that these differences vary from year to year. It is also found that there is little difference in stock-picking ability between the two groups of fund managers. Copyright Springer 2006", "ex:volume": "65", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Do Socially Responsible Fund Managers Really Invest Differently?", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-0003-8", "ex:pages": "337-357", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Socially responsible investment", "Managed funds", "Portfolio composition", "Ethical investment"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Karen Benson", "ex:email": "k.benson@business.uq.edu.au"}, {"ex:name": "Timothy Brailsford"}, {"ex:name": "Jacquelyn Humphrey"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Isolating Cultural and National Influence on Value and Ethics: A Test of Competing Hypotheses", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9822-0", "ex:pages": "197-210", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Chinese culture", "Ethics", "Confucian value", "Comparative study"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Justin Tan", "ex:email": "jtan@schulich.yorku.ca"}, {"ex:name": "Irene Chow"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "91", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Ethical Judgments in Business Ethics Research: Definition, and Research Agenda", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0092-2", "ex:pages": "405-418", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2010", "ex:keyword": ["Ethical judgments", "Definition", "Research agenda"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "John Sparks", "ex:email": "sparks@udayton.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Yue Pan"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume