eator": [{"ex:name": "Pallab Paul", "ex:email": "ppaul@du.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Kausiki Mukhopadhyay"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "79", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Just Doing Business or Doing Just Business: Google, Microsoft, Yahoo! and the Business of Censoring China’s Internet", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9373-9", "ex:pages": "219-234", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["China", "Corporate responsibility", "‘don’t be evil’", "Google", "Internet censorship", "Microsoft", "Yahoo!"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Gary Dann", "ex:email": "edann@utm.utoronto.ca"}, {"ex:name": "Neil Haddow", "ex:email": "n_haddow@hotmail.com"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "In this paper, I examine the case made by Christopher McMahon for managerial democracy. Specifically, I examine the extent to which McMahonâ€™s account is able to address a series of objections against the case for managerial democracy as articulated by Thomas Christiano. Christiano articulates two sets of objections. First, Christiano argues that McMahon does not succeed in ruling out the possibility that managerial authority is best understood as promissory in its basis, in which case there is no presumption in favor of its democratic exercise. Second, Christiano raises a series of objections to the effect that even if we accept McMahonâ€™s account of the nature of managerial authority, the conclusion for the democratic exercise of that authority by workers at the level of individual economic enterprises does not follow. In the end, I argue that McMahonâ€™s account contains the resources to address these objections if one adopts a specific view about the moral limits to relationships that involve the submission of the will on the part of one person to another. Adoption of this view, however, appears to come at the expense of what I take to be the accountâ€™s commitment to liberalism. As such, what I understand this paper to reflect more generally is the apparent difficulty for liberals in arguing that there is something inherently morally troubling about capitalist work relations. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2007", "ex:volume": "71", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Managers, Workers, and Authority", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9145-y", "ex:pages": "347-357", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Mcmahon", "Managerial democracy", "Liberalism", "Christiano", "Authority"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Nien-hÃª Hsieh", "ex:email": "nhsieh@wharton.upenn.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "85", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "What’s in a Credo? A Critique of the Academy of Management’s Code of Ethical Conduct and Code of Ethics", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9786-0", "ex:pages": "515-525", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Academy of management", "Code of conduct", "Code of ethics", "Ethics"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Daniel Skubik", "ex:email": "dskubik@calbaptist.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Bruce Stening"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:abstract": "This paper is divided into two sections. In the first section, I discuss â€œwhat is spirituality?â€\\x9D and in the section that follows, I examine some of the implications of my definition to the teaching of spirituality in an undergraduate business ethics course. For the purposes of this paper, spirituality is defined as the planned experience (the inner feeling) of blending integrity and integration through 1 â€“ acceptance (of the past), 2 â€“ commitment (to the future), 3 â€“ reasonable choice, 4 â€“ mindful action, and 5 â€“continuous dialog (both internal and external). This definition is a work-in-progress and offered mainly as a point of departure rather than a final destination. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2007", "ex:volume": "73", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Spirituality In (and Out) of the Classroom: A Pragmatic Approach", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9207-1", "ex:pages": "287-299", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Teaching ethics", "Spirituality"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Moses Pava", "ex:email": "mpava@aol.com"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "66", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Cooperation and Competition in the Context of Organic and Mechanic Worldviews – A Theoretical and Case based Discussion", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9055-z", "ex:pages": "19-32", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Collusion", "Competition", "Cooperation", "Fair trade", "Mechanistic worldview", "Organic worldview", "Sustainability"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Knut Ims", "ex:email": "Knut.Ims@nhh.no"}, {"ex:name": "Ove Jakobsen", "ex:email": "ove.jakobsen@hibo.no"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "82", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Ethical Ideologies of Senior Australian Managers: An Empirical Study", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9568-0", "ex:pages": "145-155", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Australia", "Idealism", "Relativism", "Corporate ethical values", "Managers"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Mario Fernando", "ex:email": "mariof@uow.edu.au"}, {"ex:name": "Shyamali Dharmage", "ex:email": "s.dharmage@unimelb.edu.au"}, {"ex:name": "Shamika Almeida", "ex:email": "sfer8584@mail.usyd.edu.au"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Effect of the Governance Environment on Marketing Channel Behaviors: The Diamond Industries in the U.S., China, and Hong Kong", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0303-x", "ex:pages": "453-471", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["China", "Diamond industry", "Governance environment", "Hong kong", "Inter-organizational exchange", "Market exchange", "Marketing channel behavior", "Relation-based", "Rule-based", "U.s."], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Shaomin Li", "ex:email": "sli@odue.du"}, {"ex:name": "Kiran Karande", "ex:email": "kkarande@odu.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Dongsheng Zhou", "ex:email": "zdongsheng@ceibs.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:abstract": "In this paper, we develop an argument to show why we expect that multinational companies will ensure that they communicate credibly about their environmental responsibility, across all their subsidiaries. Credible environmental communication helps to increase the firmâ€™s legitimacy and reduce its liability of foreignness on an issue that is globally relevant. We develop a measure to test if there is a standardized level of environmental communication credibility on the country-specific web sites of MNC subsidiaries around the world and find, in fact, that there is considerable variation across countries, among subsidiaries of different firms and among subsidiaries of the same multinational. We discuss the reasons for this and the implications for firm legitimacy. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media B.V. 2007", "ex:volume": "71", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "How Standard is Standardized MNC Global Environmental Communication?", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9130-5", "ex:pages": "135-147", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Credibility", "Environmental communication", "Legitimacy", "Multinationals", "Subsidiaries"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Trevor Hunter", "ex:email": "thunter6@uwo.ca"}, {"ex:name": "Pratima Bansal"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "Following an extensive review of the moral intensity literature, this article reports the findings of two studies (one between-subjects, the other within-subject) that examined the effect of manipulated and perceived moral intensity on ethical judgment. In the between-subjects study participants judged actions taken in manipulated high moral intensity scenarios to be more unethical than the same actions taken in manipulated low moral intensity scenarios. Findings were mixed for the effect of perceived moral intensity. Both probable magnitude of consequences (a factor consisting of magnitude of consequences, probability of effect, and temporal immediacy) and social consensus had a significant effect; proximity did not. In the within-subject study manipulated moral intensity had a significant effect on ethical judgment, but perceived moral intensity did not. Regression of ethical judgment on age, gender, major, and the three perceived moral intensity factors was significant between-subjects, but not within-subject. Ethical judgment was found to be a more robust predictor of intention than perceived moral intensity using a within-subject design. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2007", "ex:volume": "72", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Effect of Moral Intensity on Ethical Judgment", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9174-6", "ex:pages": "335-357", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Ethical decision making", "Ethical judgment", "Moral intensity"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Joan McMahon", "ex:email": "jmcmahon@cnu.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Robert Harvey"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "85", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "“Too Good to be True!”. The Effectiveness of CSR History in Countering Negative Publicity", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9731-2", "ex:pages": "273-283", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Crisis communication", "Csr history", "Negative publicity", "Skepticism", "Reputation"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Joëlle Vanhamme", "ex:email": "jvanhamme@rsm.nl"}, {"ex:name": "Bas Grobben"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "87", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Heterogeneity of Socially Responsible Investment", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s1