 "Scott Yetmar", "ex:email": "s.yetmar@csuohio.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "85", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Call for Papers", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-0019-3", "ex:pages": "107-108", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Marc Jones"}, {"ex:name": "Carla Millar", "ex:email": "carla.millar@ashridge.org.uk"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "82", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Two Principles of Broadcast Media Ownership for a Democratic Society", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9595-x", "ex:pages": "821-834", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Broadcast media ownership", "Fcc", "John rawls", "Media", "Political constructivism", "Telecommunications"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Michael Buckley", "ex:email": "michael-buckley@lehman.cuny.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:abstract": "The moral status of business bluffing is a controversial issue. On the one hand, bluffing would seem to be relevantly similar to lying and deception. Because of this, business bluffing can be taken to be an activity that is at least prima facie morally condemnable. On the other hand, it has often been claimed that in business bluffing is part of the game and that therefore there is nothing morally questionable in business bluffing. In a recent issue of this journal, Fritz Allhoff puts forward a novel defence of business bluffing. In this article, I will examine Allhoffâ€™s arguments for the moral acceptability of business bluffing and argue that they are implausible. Copyright Springer 2006", "ex:volume": "65", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Allhoff on Business Bluffing", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-005-4665-4", "ex:pages": "163-171", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Allhoff", "Business bluffing", "Negotiations", "Rationality", "Role-differentiated morality"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Jukka Varelius", "ex:email": "varelius@hotmail.com"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "92", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Relationship-Oriented Cultures, Corruption, and International Marketing Success", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0152-7", "ex:pages": "251-267", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2010", "ex:keyword": ["Corruption", "Culture", "International management", "Marketing", "Relationship-oriented culture", "Piracy", "Linguistic distance", "Violence"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Jennifer Chandler", "ex:email": "jenc@hawaii.edu"}, {"ex:name": "John Graham", "ex:email": "jgraham@uci.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "78", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Factors that Influence the Intention to Pirate Software and Media", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9366-8", "ex:pages": "527-545", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Intention toward digital piracy", "Ethical behavior", "Theory of planned behavior", "Moral obligation"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Timothy Cronan", "ex:email": "pcronan@walton.uark.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Sulaiman Al-Rafee"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:abstract": "It has become common for business practitioners and management scholars to distinguish between compliance and ethics. According to the conventional distinction as expressed in Paineâ€™s formulation of Integrity Strategy, compliance is ordinarily a necessary but insufficient condition for ethics. Now that this distinction has been institutionalized in the most significant judicial, legislative, and regulatory developments in American business conduct management since the Enron failure, it is worth asking whether the current emphasis on ethics represents progress. Does it make logical and practical sense to impose ethics as a compliance requirement, or have we come full circle? I argue that assertions of organizational ethical progress, usually involving an increase in the number and or severity of compliance restrictions, do not get the conventional distinction quite right. Moreover, under the consensus distinction, there can be no such thing as organizational ethical progress. However, our ordinary ways of talking about business conduct management often betray logical confusions about the ethicsâ€“compliance relationship. While the metaphors we employ â€“ â€œhigher standards,â€\\x9D â€œraising the bar,â€\\x9D â€œgray areas,â€\\x9D and â€œcrossing the line,â€\\x9D etc. â€“ perform a worthwhile function as standards for external evaluation of business conduct, they also have a tendency to limit and impoverish our conception of what it is to be ethical. The idea that ethics matters is fundamental to Integrity Strategyâ€™s implicit claim, consistent with conventional wisdom and moral theory, that the objective of responsible conduct cannot be achieved solely by imposing from outside what is required but must also appeal to what is desired. Copyright Springer 2006", "ex:volume": "66", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Compliance and the Illusion of Ethical Progress", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-005-5589-8", "ex:pages": "241-251", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Christopher Michaelson", "ex:email": "cmichael@stern.nyu.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "74", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Social Role Conceptions and CSR Policy Success", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9512-3", "ex:pages": "363-372", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Social role conception", "Csr", "Corporate social performance", "Legitimacy"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Tobias GÃ¶ssling", "ex:email": "t.goessling@uvt.nl"}, {"ex:name": "Chris Vocht", "ex:email": "chris_vocht@hotmail.com"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "84", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Legitimating Market Egoism: The Availability Problem", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9675-6", "ex:pages": "89-95", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Market egoism", "Utilitarianism", "Deontology", "Availability problem"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Tony Lynch", "ex:email": "alynch@une.edu.au"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "81", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Four Design Criteria for any Future Contractarian Theory of Business Ethics", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9542-x", "ex:pages": "697-714", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Contractarianism", "Integrative social contracts theory", "Theories of business ethics"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Ben Wempe", "ex:email": "bwempe@rsm.nl"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:abstract": "This paper examines stakeholder responses to impression management tactics used by firms that express environmental commitment. We inductively analyzed data from 98 open-ended questionnaires and identified two impression management tactics that led respondents to believe that a firm was credible in its commitment to the natural environment. Approximately, half of the respondents responded to illustrative impression management tactics that provide images of, and/or broad-brush comments about, the firmâ€™s commitment to the natural environment. The other half responded to demonstrative impression management tactics, which provide specific facts and details about the firmâ€™s operations. The research results provide important insights into the effects of organizational transparency. In this paper, we explore these findings and provide directions for future research. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2006", "ex:volume": "67", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Seeing Is (Not) Believing: Managing the Impressions of the Firmâ€™s Commitment to the Natural Environment", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9021-9", "ex:pages": "165-180", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Impression management tactics", "Legitimacy", "Natural environment", "Stakeholders", "Transparency"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Pratima Bansal", "ex:email": "pbansal@ivey.uwo.ca"}, {"ex:name": "Geoffrey Kistruck", "ex:email": "gkistruck@ivey.uwo.ca"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "83", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Gender Diversity in the Boardroom and Firm Financial Performance", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9630-y", "ex:pages": "435-451", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Board of directors", "Corporate governance", "Endogeneity", "Firm value", "Women"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Kevin Campbell", "ex:email": "kevin.campbell@stirling.ac.uk"}, {"ex:name": "Antonio Mínguez-Vera", "ex:email": "antonio.minguez@upct.es"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "85", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Call for Papers: Special Issue/Forum", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0028-x", "ex:pages": "277-279", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Donna Wood"}, {"ex:name": "Antonino Vaccaro", "ex:email": "vaccaro@lisboa.ucp.pt"}, {"ex:name": "Adele Queiroz"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "85", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "From Chain Liability to Chain Responsibility", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9742-z", "ex:pages": "399-412", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Chain responsibility/liability", "Codes of conduct", "Csr strategies", "International framework agreement", "Occupational safety and health", "Outsourcing", "Stakeholders"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Rob Tulder", "ex:email": "rtulder@rsm.nl"}, {"ex:name": "Jeroen Wijk"}, {"ex:name": "Ans Kolk"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "86", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "What do Corporations have to do with Fair Trade? Positive and Normative Analysis from a Value Chain Perspective", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9757-5", "ex:pages": "3-26", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Fair trade", "Value chain", "Commodity chain", "Corporate social responsibility", "Social economy", "Co-operatives"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Darryl Reed", "ex:email": "dreed@yorku.ca"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "84", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Where Strategy and Ethics Converge: Pharmaceutical Industry Pricing Policy for Medicare Part D Beneficiaries", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9682-7", "ex:pages": "75-88", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Access", "Diffusion", "Ethics", "Pricing strategy"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Edward Balotsky", "ex:email": "ebalotsk@sju.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Latino Immigration and Social Change in the United States: Toward an Ethical Immigration Policy", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0291-x", "ex:pages": "377-391", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Immigration policy", "Mexico", "Discourse", "Culture", "Diversity", "Multiculturalism"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Ian Davies", "ex:email": "idavies@edgewood.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "77", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Positive Effect of Green Intellectual Capital on Competitive Advantages of Firms", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9349-1", "ex:pages": "271-286", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Green intellectual capital", "Green human capital", "Green structural capital", "Green relational capital", "Competitive advantage"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Yu-Shan Chen", "ex:email": "dr.chen.ys@gmail.com"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "92", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "An Empirical Investigation into the Role of Personal-Related Factors on Corporate Travel Policy Compliance", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0167-0", "ex:pages": "451-461", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2010", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate travel", "Corporate travellers", "Corporate travel policy", "Non-compliance", "Personal-related factors", "South africa"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Anneli Douglas", "ex:email": "anneli.douglas@up.ac.za"}, {"ex:name": "Berendien Lubbe"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "83", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Impact of Managerial Dependencies on Ethical Behavior", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9637-4", "ex:pages": "535-542", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Ethical behavior", "Specialized expertise", "Political connections", "Organizational independence", "Ethical optimism"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Satish Deshpande", "ex:email": "satish.deshpande@wmich.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Jacob Joseph", "ex:email": "ffjj@uaf.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Rashmi Prasad", "ex:email": "afrp2@cbpp.uaa.alaska.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:abstract": "The results of a survey of 272 practicing accountants and 374 accounting students enrolled in six universities are analyzed. Differences and similarities between the two groups with regard to their attitudes toward corporate social responsibility are examined. The results indicate that the students exhibit greater concern about the ethical and discretionary components of corporate responsibility and a weaker orientation toward economic performance. No significant differences between the two groups were observed with respect to the legal dimension of corporate social responsibility. Some explanations as well as limited generalizations and implications are developed. Copyright Springer 2006", "ex:volume": "66", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Corporate Social Responsibility: A Comparative Analysis of Perceptions of Practicing Accountants and Accounting Students", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-005-5572-4", "ex:pages": "157-167", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Social responsibility", "Business ethics", "Accountants"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Nabil Ibrahim", "ex:email": "nibrahim@aug.edu"}, {"ex:name": "John Angelidis"}, {"ex:name": "Donald Howard"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "The aim of this paper is to conduct an in-depth study on environmental management systems developed in the ceramic tiles sector. This study is conceived as an improvement on a previous survey related to an environmental diagnosis of the ceramic tiles sector where some incongruities between environmental explicit speeches and environmental actions were detected. Such incongruities revealed that firms assumed to be highly environmental committed while from facts this commitment was not so high proved. So, it was necessary to introduce case study research methodology to clarify and to understand the reasons of these inconsistencies. The main objectives of our case study research are two. The first one consists in determining the relationship between firms and environment, analysing environmental positions in companies assumed in their environmental strategy and their environmental behaviour reflected in facts, while the second one attempts to establish the role played by the accounting information system in the environmental management systems of the companies in the sector. Our case study research reveals the elaboration of a larger amount of environmental accounting information for internal use than for external one. This fact is due not only to the inexistence of regulations about environmental disclosures in Spain, at that time, but also to the importance of environmental internal accounting information for management which supports the prevalence of decision-usefulness theory in the implementation of environmental management systems. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2006", "ex:volume": "68", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Environmental Management Accounting: A Case Study Research on Innovative Strategy", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9029-1", "ex:pages": "393-408", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Accounting information systems", "Case study research", "Environmental accounting", "Environmental awareness", "Environmental communication", "Environmental management", "Innovative strategy"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Maria Masanet-Llodra", "ex:email": "masanet@cofin.uji.es"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:abstract": "Recent allegations of unethical decision-making by leaders in prominent business organizations have jeopardized the worldâ€™s confidence in American business. The purpose of this research was to develop a measure of managerial moral judgment that can be used in future research and managerial assessment. The measure was patterned after the Defining Issues Test, a widely used general measure of moral judgment. With content validity as the goal, we aimed to sample the domain of managerial ethical situations by establishing links to dimensions of managerial performance, as well as to the types of organizational justice issues managers encounter. Proposed scenarios were evaluated for realism by ethics officers and human resource managers. Results indicated that the new measure is reliable and correlates with a number of relevant variables in the hypothesized manner, demonstrating evidence of construct validity. Implications for future research and for human resources management are discussed. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2007", "ex:volume": "73", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Assessing Managersâ€™ Ethical Decision-making: An Objective Measure of Managerial Moral Judgment", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9206-2", "ex:pages": "263-285", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Moral judgment", "Measurement", "Ethical decision-making", "Manager"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Greg Loviscky", "ex:email": "gel102@psu.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Linda TreviÃ±o"}, {"ex:name": "Rick Jacobs"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "75", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Accounting and Medicine: An Exploratory Investigation into Physiciansâ€™ Attitudes Toward the Use of Standard Cost-Accounting Methods in Medicine", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9241-z", "ex:pages": "137-149", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Diagnostic related groups", "Evidence based best practices", "Grounded theory methodology", "Health care ethics", "Physician practices"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Greg Thibadoux", "ex:email": "greg-thibadoux@utc.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Marsha Scheidt"}, {"ex:name": "Elizabeth Luckey"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "89", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "A Study of Management Perceptions of the Impact of Corporate Social Responsibility on Organisational Performance in Emerging Economies: The Case of Dubai", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-0005-9", "ex:pages": "371-390", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate social responsibility", "Organisational performance", "Emerging economies", "United arab emirates"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Belaid Rettab"}, {"ex:name": "Anis Brik"}, {"ex:name": "Kamel Mellahi", "ex:email": "K.Mellahi@sheffield.ac.uk"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "92", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Bribery in International Business Transactions", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0136-7", "ex:pages": "15-32", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2010", "ex:keyword": ["Bribe payer’s index", "Bribery", "Corruption", "Institutional theory", "International trade", "Oecd convention"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Christopher Baughn", "ex:email": "cbaughn@boisestate.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Nancy Bodie"}, {"ex:name": "Mark Buchanan"}, {"ex:name": "Michael Bixby"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "89", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Role of Self-Definitional Principles in Consumer Identification with a Socially Responsible Company", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-0016-6", "ex:pages": "547-564", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Social responsibility", "Identification", "Brand attractiveness", "Brand coherence", "Brand distinctiveness", "Brand prestige", "Brand attitude", "Purchase intention"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Rafael Currás-Pérez", "ex:email": "curras@uv.es"}, {"ex:name": "Enrique Bigné-Alcañiz", "ex:email": "enrique.bigne@uv.es"}, {"ex:name": "Alejandro Alvarado-Herrera", "ex:email": "aah@uqroo.mx"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "75", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Routes of Moral Development and the Impact of Exposure to the Milgram Obedience Study", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9255-6", "ex:pages": "315-333", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Cognitive moral development", "Dit", "Kohlberg", "Milgram", "Obedience", "Rest"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Jerry Sheppard", "ex:email": "sheppard@sfu.ca"}, {"ex:name": "Marnie Young"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "84", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Global and Contextual Values for Business in a Changing World: Editorial", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0208-8", "ex:pages": "279-280", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Geoff Moore", "ex:email": "geoff.moore@durham.ac.uk"}, {"ex:name": "Christoph Stückelberger", "ex:email": "stueckelberger@globethics.net"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "Efforts to promote corporate social and environmental accountability (SEA) should be informed by an understanding of stakeholdersâ€™ attitudes toward enhanced accountability standards. However, little is known about current attitudes on this subject, or the determinants of these attitudes. To address this issue, this study examines the relationship between personal values and support for social and environmental accountability for a sample of experienced MBA students. Exploratory factor analysis of the items comprising our measure of support for SEA revealed two distinct factors: (1) endorsement of the general proposition that corporations and executives should be held accountable for the social and environmental impacts of their actions; and (2) agreement that the government should adopt and enforce formal SEA standards. Our findings indicate that the universalism value type is positively associated with general support for SEA, but not with support for government enforcement of accountability standards. In addition, we found that gender has a significant impact on support for government enforcement of SEA standards. Copyright Springer 2007", "ex:volume": "71", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Values and Attitudes Toward Social and Environmental Accountability: a Study of MBA Students", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-005-3893-y", "ex:pages": "381-394", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Personal values", "Social accountability", "Environmental accountability", "Mba students"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Kyoko Fukukawa", "ex:email": "K.Fukukawa@bradford.ac.uk"}, {"ex:name": "William Shafer", "ex:email": "weshafer@ln.hk.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Grace Lee", "ex:email": "gracelee@ln.hk.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "92", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Moderating Effect of Equal Opportunity Support and Confidence in Grievance Procedures on Sexual Harassment from Different Perpetrators", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0165-2", "ex:pages": "415-432", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2010", "ex:keyword": ["Attribution theory", "Equal opportunity", "Power", "Role identity", "Sexual harassment"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "M. Hershcovis", "ex:email": "sandy_hershcovis@umanitoba.ca"}, {"ex:name": "Sharon Parker", "ex:email": "s.parker@sheffield.ac.uk"}, {"ex:name": "Tara Reich", "ex:email": "umreich@cc.umanitoba.ca"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Nature of Responsibility in a Professional Setting", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0103-3", "ex:pages": "11-19", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Responsibility", "Imputability", "Accountability", "Liability", "Professional", "Leadership"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Simon Robinson", "ex:email": "S.J.Robinson@leedsmet.ac.uk"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "This article discusses the alleged anti-corruption effects of procurement reforms by presenting the European Act on Public Procurement and the increasing number of appeals filed by suppliers due to perceived misevaluations of tenders and perceived impairments of transparency. The delays and costs that arise from this right to appeal are studied in the Swedish context with the aim of contributing to the debate on corruption in two ways. First, instead of using the modern definition of corruption, the ancient definition is introduced to explain anti-corruption efforts, focusing on corruption as deviations from a pristine standard as opposed to corruption as the abuse of public power for private gain. Second, it will be argued that the fight against corruption in the practical implementation of the European Act on Public Procurement jeopardizes efficiency and might devaluate competence. However, striving for the total elimination of corruptionâ€“an evil that has to be fought disregarding the consequencesâ€“is integral in the war against it. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2007", "ex:volume": "73", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Transformation of Transparency â€“ On the Act on Public