ove the individuals who comprise them. They talk of corporate decision-making structures that help translate individual decisions and actions into corporate decisions and actions. Importantly both the advocates and the opponents of corporate personhood rely on a contractual model of corporateâ€“social interaction to explain corporate social responsibilty. However, this contractual model misses crucial aspects of the relationship between corporations and societies. Economic history reveals that the relationship between corporations and societies is essentially dynamic and heterogeneous and so extremely difficult to characterise in terms of a contract. The economic and the political aspects of this relationship are so finely intertwined with each other and it is impossible to extricate the one from the other. We need to be more conscious of the actual nature of corporateâ€“social interaction in order to deal more comprehensively with issues of corporate social responsibility. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2006", "ex:volume": "67", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Missing Dynamic: Corporations, Individuals and Contracts", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9032-6", "ex:pages": "393-406", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate personhood", "Corporate social responsibility", "Contract theory", "Economic history", "Society"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Arun Iyer", "ex:email": "arun.iyer@mu.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:abstract": "This study explores the impact of mood on individualsâ€™ ethical decision-making processes through the Graham [Graham, J. W.: 1986, Research in Organizational Behavior 8, 1â€“52] model of Principled Organizational Dissent. In particular, the research addresses how an individualâ€™s mood influences his or her willingness to report the unethical actions of a colleague. Participantsâ€™ experienced an affectively charged, unrelated event and were then asked to make a decision regarding whistle-blowing intentions in a public accounting context. As expected, negative mood was associated with lower intentions to report the unethical actions of others to a superior within the organization. The Graham model, which proposes that reporting intentions are impacted by the three determinants of seriousness, personal responsibility and cost, was employed to more clearly understand the nature of the affectâ€“reporting intention relationship. The role of affect was explained by demonstrating that two determinants mediate the relationship between mood and whistle-blowing intentions. Specifically, as seriousness and responsibility have a positive impact on reporting intentions, the reduction of these perceptions by negative mood reduces the intent to report. The negative impact of personal cost on reporting intentions was significant, although not as a mediator of mood. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2006", "ex:volume": "68", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Are Audit-related Ethical Decisions Dependent upon Mood?", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9066-9", "ex:pages": "191-209", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Affect", "Mood", "Whistle-blowing"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Mary Curtis", "ex:email": "curtism@unt.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Thomas W. Dunfee Tribute Issue: Introduction", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0336-1", "ex:pages": "539-540", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Thomas Robertson", "ex:email": "Robertson@wharton.upenn.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "87", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Assurance Services for Sustainability Reports: Standards and Empirical Evidence", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9809-x", "ex:pages": "289-298", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2