ak"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "89", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "How Corporate Social Responsibility Influences Organizational Commitment", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9993-8", "ex:pages": "189-204", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate social responsibility", "Organizational commitment", "Social identity theory", "Stakeholders", "Turkey"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Duygu Turker", "ex:email": "duygu.turker@yasar.edu.tr"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "75", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Personal Valuesâ€™ Influence on the Ethical Dimension of Decision Making", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9256-5", "ex:pages": "335-343", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Personal values", "Decision making", "Ethical dilemmas"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "David Fritzsche"}, {"ex:name": "E. Oz", "ex:email": "effyoz@psu.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "83", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Do Competitive Environments Lead to the Rise and Spread of Unethical Behavior? Parallels from Enron", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9659-y", "ex:pages": "703-723", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Social network", "Enron", "Theory of planned behavior", "Grassroots model", "Spread of unethical behavior", "Diffusion", "Corruption"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Brian Kulik", "ex:email": "kulikb@cwu.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Michael O’Fallon"}, {"ex:name": "Manjula Salimath"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Managerial Law Firm and the Globalization of Legal Ethics", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0104-2", "ex:pages": "21-34", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Comparative legal ethics", "International codes of ethics", "Law firm management", "Law firms", "Legal ethics", "Professional ethics", "Professions"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Bjorn Fasterling", "ex:email": "bjorn.fasterling@edhec.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "75", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Sustainable Development and Corporate Performance: A Study Based on the Dow Jones Sustainability Index", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9253-8", "ex:pages": "285-300", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Competitive advantage", "Value creating", "Sustainable development", "Performance", "Dow jones sustainability index"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "M. LÃ³pez", "ex:email": "mvlopez@ugr.es"}, {"ex:name": "Arminda Garcia"}, {"ex:name": "Lazaro Rodriguez"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:abstract": "Diversity scholars have emphasized the critical role of corporate leaders for ensuring the success of diversity strategic initiatives in organizations. This study reports on business school leadersâ€™ attributions regarding the causes for and solutions to the low representation of U.S. faculty of color in business schools. Results indicatethat leaders with greater awareness of racial issues rated an inhospitable organizational culture as a more important cause and cultural change and recruitment as more important solutions to faculty of color under-representation than did less racially aware respondents. Aware leaders also rated individual minority-group member responsibility for performance a less important solution than did less racially aware respondents. Implications are discussed. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2007", "ex:volume": "73", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Impact of Leader Racial Attitude on Ratings of Causes and Solutions for an Employee of Color Shortage", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9178-2", "ex:pages": "129-144", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Diversity", "Employee shortage", "Leaderâ€™s racial attitude", "Racial awareness", "Organizational climate"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "E. Buttner", "ex:email": "ehbuttne@uncg.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Kevin Lowe"}, {"ex:name": "Lenora Billings-Harris"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "81", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Does the Market Value Corporate Philanthropy? Evidence from the Response to the 2004 Tsunami Relief Effort", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9534-x", "ex:pages": "599-607", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate philanthropy", "Market reactions", "Social responsiveness"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Dennis Patten", "ex:email": "dmpatte@ilstu.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "81", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Multi-Stakeholder Labour Monitoring Organizations: Egoists, Instrumentalists, or Moralists?", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9484-3", "ex:pages": "117-142", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Codes of conduct", "Ethical cultures", "Fla", "Labour", "Maquilas", "Monitoring organizations", "Sai", "Stakeholders", "Transparency", "Wrap", "Wrc"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Jeff Everett", "ex:email": "jeff.everett@haskayne.ucalgary.ca"}, {"ex:name": "Dean Neu"}, {"ex:name": "Daniel Martinez"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "78", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Ethical Distance in Corrupt Firms: How Do Innocent Bystanders Become Guilty Perpetrators?", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9378-4", "ex:pages": "265-274", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Bystander", "Corruption", "Ethical distance", "Rationalization", "Business ethics"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Stelios Zyglidopoulos", "ex:email": "szyglidopoulos@yahoo.com"}, {"ex:name": "Peter Fleming"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "76", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Are Men Always Picked Over Women? The Effects of Employment Equity Directives on Selection Decisions", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9266-3", "ex:pages": "177-187", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Employment equity", "Minority qualifications", "Hiring decisions", "Social dominance theory", "Underrepresented men versus underrepresented women"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Eddy Ng", "ex:email": "esng@csupomona.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Willi Wiesner", "ex:email": "wiesner@mcmaster.ca"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:abstract": "Since Ackerman in Corporate social responsiveness, the modern dilemma (1973), pleaded for the institutionalisation of corporate social performance (CSP) in business processes, researchers have focused on the role of strategy in CSP. This article demonstrates that CSP is institutionalised within the governance structure. We will attempt to make this clear by means of a description of the Dutch system of corporate governance. Under certain circumstances Dutch companies are already bound to CSP due to prevailing legislation. A governance perspective shows that CSP is institutionalised within a companyâ€™s governance structure. â€œProcesses of responsivenessâ€\\x9D, since long regarded as a starting point of CSP-analysis, appear to be decision-making processes. Within these processes the expectations of the stakeholders can be institutionalised, trust can be built and interests can be incorporated. This makes CSP context-dependent. However, it is possible to analyse companies by comparing the companiesâ€™ individual governance structures. The article concludes that CSP-analysis can fruitfully extend into analysing in the role of the stakeholders in the influence-pathways that are incorporated within the governance structure. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media B.V. 2007", "ex:volume": "74", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "How Corporate Social Performance Is Institutionalised Within the Governance Structure", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9229-8", "ex:pages": "177-189", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate governance", "Corporate social performance", "Stakeholder influence"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Frank Graaf", "ex:email": "F.J.deGraaf@uva.nl"}, {"ex:name": "Cor HerkstrÃ¶ter"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "79", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Corporate Social and Financial Performance: An Extended Stakeholder Theory, and Empirical Test with Accounting Measures", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9398-0", "ex:pages": "299-310", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Panel data analysis", "Prospect decision theory", "Resource dependence theory", "Social responsibility", "Stakeholder theory"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Gerwin Laan", "ex:email": "gerwin.van.der.laan@rug.nl"}, {"ex:name": "Hans Ees"}, {"ex:name": "Arjen Witteloostuijn"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Measuring Unethical Consumer Behavior Across Four Countries", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9971-1", "ex:pages": "395-412", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Consumers", "International", "Misbehavior", "Unethical", "Latent class analysis"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Vince Mitchell", "ex:email": "v.mitchell@city.ac.uk"}, {"ex:name": "George Balabanis", "ex:email": "g.balabanis@city.ac.uk"}, {"ex:name": "Bodo Schlegelmilch", "ex:email": "bodo.schlegelmilch@wu-wien.ac.at"}, {"ex:name": "T. Cornwell", "ex:email": "tbettina@umich.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:abstract": "Software piracy is a serious problem in the software industry. Software authors and publishing companies lose revenue when pirated software rather than legally purchased software is used. Policy developers are forced to invest time and money into restricting software piracy. Much of the published research literature focuses on software piracy by end-users. However, end-users are only able to copy software once the copy protection has been removed by a â€˜crackerâ€™. This research aims to explore why, if copy protection is so difficult to remove, do crackers invest their skill and time in this activity instead of more lucrative and legal employment. This study develops a framework of neutralisation, justification and motivation and goes directly to the initial software crackers to determine what motivates their activities. The study first applies this framework in an anonymous online survey of crackers. The study then conducts cognitive interviews with eight crackers to explore and further validate the surveyâ€™s findings. The study finds the challenge of removing the copy protection from software as the strongest motivation for the actions of crackers. Desire for social participation, while found to be rewarding, was considered unnecessary for crackers to continue their actions. Higher social status was not a motivational factor but was a perceived by-product of cracking. The study also raises areas for future research. Copyright Springer 2006", "ex:volume": "65", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "What Motivates Software Crackers?", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-005-4709-9", "ex:pages": "173-201", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Software piracy", "Personal motivation", "Social justification", "Neutralisation"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Sigi Goode", "ex:email": "sigi.goode@anu.edu.au"}, {"ex:name": "Sam Cruise"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "85", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "King Car and the Ethics of Automobile Proponents’ Strategies in China", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9935-5", "ex:pages": "157-172", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Automobile", "Transportation", "China"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Martin Calkins", "ex:email": "martin.calkins@umb.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "84", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Ethical Values and Environmentalism in China: Comparing Employees from State-Owned and Private Firms", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0202-1", "ex:pages": "341-348", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate citizenship", "Environmentalism", "Employees", "State-owned enterprises and private companies in china", "Ethical values"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Rosa Chun", "ex:email": "rosa.chun@mbs.ac.uk"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "84", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Exploring the Geography of Corporate Philanthropic Disaster Response: A Study of Fortune Global 500 Firms", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9819-8", "ex:pages": "605-605", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Alan Muller", "ex:email": "amuller@uva.nl"}, {"ex:name": "Gail Whiteman"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "86", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Different Pathways that Suggest Whether Auditors’ Going Concern Opinions are Ethically Based", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9851-8", "ex:pages": "347-361", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Auditing", "Conflicts of interest", "Decision making", "Ethics", "Throughput model", "Warning signals"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Waymond Rodgers", "ex:email": "waymond.rodgers@ucr.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Andrés Guiral", "ex:email": "andres.guiral@uah.es"}, {"ex:name": "José Gonzalo", "ex:email": "josea.gonzalo@uah.es"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "The Sarbanesâ€“Oxley (SOX) Act was passed in 2002 in response to various instances of corporate malfeasance. The Act, designed to protect investors, led to wide-ranging regulation over various actions of managers, auditors and investment analysts. Part of SOX, and the focus of this study, targeted the disclosure by firms of â€œpro formaâ€\\x9D earnings, an alternate (from GAAP earnings), flexible and unaudited measure of firm performance. Specifically, SOX directed the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) to craft regulation which would reduce â€“ and preferably eliminate â€“ any pro forma earnings disclosure which might be â€œmisleadingâ€\\x9D. Examining earnings press releases over a 3-year period, this study addresses three questions. Were firms disclosing pro forma in a potentially misleading manner, what was the nature of this potentially misleading disclosure, and did SOX affect the disclosure practices? We find the following. In 2001 (prior to SOX), 53 firms â€“ over 10% of all U.S. S&P 500 firms â€“ were disclosing pro forma earnings in a potentially misleading manner. This was being done most commonly by using traditional GAAP terminology (e.g., â€œnet incomeâ€\\x9D) in the press release headline to describe what was later in the press release revealed to be a pro forma amount (i.e., â€œnet income excluding special itemsâ€\\x9D). By 2003 (subsequent to the SEC regulation), potentially misleading disclosure practices were seen in less than 1% of the earnings press releases of S&P 500 firms. This significant reduction suggests that managers, prior to the regulation, were either careless in their pro forma reporting practice, or were intentionally â€“ and unethically â€“ attempting to mislead investors. Either way, we conclude that the SEC regulation was both necessary and effective. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2006", "ex:volume": "69", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Misleading Disclosure of Pro Forma Earnings: An Empirical Examination", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9095-4", "ex:pages": "355-372", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Pro forma earnings", "Disclosure management", "Misleading", "Regulation"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Gary Entwistle", "ex:email": "entwistle@commerce.usask.ca"}, {"ex:name": "Glenn Feltham"}, {"ex:name": "Chima Mbagwu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "74", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Public Policies on Corporate Social Responsibility: The Role of Governments in Europe", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9514-1", "ex:pages": "391-407", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate social responsibility", "Public policies", "Governance", "Publicâ€“private partnership", "Welfare state"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Laura Albareda", "ex:email": "laura.albareda@esade.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Josep Lozano", "ex:email": "josepm.lozano@esade.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Tamyko Ysa", "ex:email": "tamyko.ysa@esade.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "82", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Learning from Multi-Stakeholder Networks: Issue-Focussed Stakeholder Management", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9573-3", "ex:pages": "233-250", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Stakeholder management", "Stakeholder dialogue", "Multi-stakeholder network", "Deliberation", "Conflict management", "Corporate citizenship", "Issue management"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Julia Roloff", "ex:email": "julia.roloff@esc-rennes.fr"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "85", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Responsible Leaders as Agents of World Benefit: Learnings from “Project Ulysses”", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9947-1", "ex:pages": "59-71", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Responsible leadership", "Leadership development", "Talent development", "Corporate citizenship", "Corporate social responsibility", "Business in society", "Cross-sector partnerships", "Project ulysses"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Nicola Pless", "ex:email": "nicola.pless@insead.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Thomas Maak", "ex:email": "thomas.maak@unisg.ch"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:abstract": "The study extends the Theory of Planned Behavior (TPB) in a cross-cultural setting, incorporating ethical judgments and locus of control in a comparison of Taiwanese and US businesspersons. A self-administered survey of 698 businesspersons from the US and Taiwan examined several hypothesized differences. Results indicate that while Taiwanese respondents have a more favorable attitude toward a requested bribe than US counterparts, and are less likely to view it as an ethical issue, their higher locus externality causes ethical judgments and behavioral intentions to conform to normative influences of in groups and superiors. In the Taiwanese sample, locus externality effectively functions as a countervailing pressure against the unethical behavior in the scenario. No such effect is found in the US sample. A path model fitted to the data shows that locus internals exhibit more consistency among attitudes, judgments, and behavioral intentions than locus externals. Implications for managers and researchers are discussed, and suggestions and precautions for development of efficacy-enhancement programs are offered. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2006", "ex:volume": "68", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Impact of Normative Influence and Locus of Control on Ethical Judgments and Intentions: a Cross-Cultural Comparison", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9043-3", "ex:pages": "113-132", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Cross-cultural", "Ethical judgments", "Ethical intentions", "Normative influence", "Locus of control", "Marketing", "Perceived efficacy"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "John Cherry", "ex:email": "jcherry@semo.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "87", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "An Analysis of International Accounting Codes of Conduct", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9811-3", "ex:pages": "173-183", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Accounting profession", "Codes of conduct", "Codes of ethics", "Ifac"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Curtis Clements", "ex:email": "curtis.clements@acu.edu"}, {"ex:name": "John Neill", "ex:email": "john.neill@coba.acu.edu"}, {"ex:name": "O. Stovall", "ex:email": "scott.stovall@coba.acu.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "80", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Manipulation of Voting Systems", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9438-9", "ex:pages": "13-21", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Electoral college", "U.s. presidential elections", "Vote trading", "Voting"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "David Hartvigsen", "ex:email": "Hartvigsen.1@nd.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Strengthening the Ties that Bind: Preventing Corruption in the Executive Suite", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0325-4", "ex:pages": "765-780", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Corruption", "Corporate governance", "Stock options backdating", "Executive and management ethics", "Private corruption", "Fiduciary duty"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Norman Bishara", "ex:email": "nbishara@umich.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Cindy Schipani", "ex:email": "schipani@unich.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "74", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Fiduciary Duties as a Helpful Guide to Ethical Decision-Making in Business", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9126-1", "ex:pages": "1-15", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Stephen Young", "ex:email": "cauxrt@aol.com"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:abstract": "There have been many attempts during the history of applied ethics that have tried to develop a theory of moral reasoning. The goal of this paper is to explicate one aspect of the debate between various attempts of offering a specific method for resolving moral dilemmas. We contrast two kinds of deliberative methods: deliberative methods whose goal is decision-making and deliberative methods that are aimed at gaining edifying perspectives. The decision-making methods assessed include the traditional moral theories like utilitarianism and Kantianism, as well as second order principles, such as principlism and specified principlism. In light of this assessment, we suggest taking a closer look at two perceptive models, casuistry and particularism. These models are used for dealing with moral dilemmas that provide for edifying perspectives rather than decision-making. These perceptive models, though less scientific and not as good at prescribing an action, are more human in the sense that they enrich our moral sensibilities and enhance our understanding of the meaning of the situation. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2007", "ex:volume": "71", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Moral Dilemmas in Business Ethics: From Decision Procedures to Edifying Perspectives", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9134-1", "ex:pages": "195-207", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Casuistry", "Decision theory", "Humanism", "Moral deliberation", "Particularism"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Yotam Lurie", "ex:email": "yotam@bgu.ac.il"}, {"ex:name": "Robert Albin", "ex:email": "albin@sapir.ac.il"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "78", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Character and Environment: The Status of Virtues in Organizations", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9335-7", "ex:pages": "343-357", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Virtue ethics", "Business ethics", "Social psychology", "Moral character", "Personality psychology"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Miguel Alzola", "ex:email": "malzola@rutgers.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "77", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Sowing the Seeds of Reason in the Field of the Terminator Debate", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9295-y", "ex:pages": "65-72", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Genetic modification", "Genetic use restriction technology", "Intellectual property", "Monsanto", "Resource-poor farmers", "Subsistence rights", "Terminator technology"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Keith Bustos", "ex:email": "kbustos@utk.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "79", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Local Responsiveness Pressure, Subsidiary Resources, Green Management Adoption and Subsidiary’s Performance: Evidence from Taiwanese Manufactures", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9382-8", "ex:pages": "199-212", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Green management", "Mncs", "Performance", "Resource", "Stakeholders"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Yu-Shu Peng", "ex:email": "yspeng@mail.ndhu.edu.tw"}, {"ex:name": "Shing-Shiuan Lin"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:abstract": "Increasingly through the 1990s, tobacco control advocates questioned the practice of public institutions investing in tobacco company stocks. The questioning was framed in at least three ways. First, is it ethical to fund public expenditures with profits from a product that causes addiction and disease? Second, is it sound social policy to derive public income from a product that increases healthcare costs and reduces worker productivity? Finally, is it sound fiscal policy to invest in an historically profitable industry facing multiplying legal and regulatory challenges? While the tobacco industry preferred to restrict discussion to the fiscal question, and offered an affirmative answer, its position was weakened by depressed stock prices brought on by actions of the industry as much as by tobacco control activism. As part of a campaign to restore its credibility as an investment vehicle with public fund managers, Philip Morris (PM) commissioned a report from the influential investment managers/advisors Wilshire Associates. However, Wilshire had only recently conducted such a study for the Washington State Investment Board (WSIB), assuring the board that the value tobacco stocks added to an investment portfolio â€“ if any â€“ was too small to be measured. Nonetheless, within a year, Wilshire produced a report for PM which appeared to laud the investment value of tobacco and to dismiss tobacco-excluded investment alternatives. This paper examines how Wilshire produced apparently diametrically opposed reports for clients with different interests. It reveals a pattern of potential conflicts of interest among tobacco companies, financial analysis firms, investment authorities, and institutional fund managers. It demonstrates substantial violations of two generally accepted ethical principles of business consulting: veracity and transparency. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2007", "ex:volume": "73", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Keeping Public Institutions Invested in Tobacco", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9188-0", "ex:pages": "161-176", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Divestment", "Ethics", "Consulting", "Public health policy", "Public investments", "Tobacco industry documents"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Nathaniel Wander", "ex:email": "nathaniel.wander@ucsf.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Ruth Malone"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "Tacit knowledge sharing discussed in this study is important in the area of business ethics, because an unwillingness to share knowledge that may hurt an organizationâ€™s survival is seen as being seriously unethical. In the proposed model of this study, distributive justice, procedural justice, and cooperativeness influence tacit knowledge sharing indirectly via two mediators: organizational commitment and trust in co-workers. Accordingly, instrumental ties and expressive ties influence tacit knowledge sharing indirectly only via the mediation of trust in co-workers. The model is assessed by using data from different companiesâ€™ employees, who attend an evening college in Taiwan for advance study. The test results of this study indicate that tacit knowledge sharing is affected by distributive justice, procedural justice, and cooperativeness indirectly via organizational commitment. Additionally, tacit knowledge sharing is also affected by distributive justice, instrumental ties, and expressive ties via trust in co-workers. The paths from procedural justice and cooperativeness to trust in co-workers are shown to be insignificant. Managerial implications of the empirical findings are also provided. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2007", "ex:volume": "70", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "To Share or Not to Share: Modeling Tacit Knowledge Sharing, Its Mediators and Antecedents", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9119-0", "ex:pages": "411-428", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Knowledge management", "Organizational commitment", "Trust in co-workers", "Justice", "Cooperativeness"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Chieh-Peng Lin", "ex:email": "jacques@vnu.edu.tw"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "91", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Applying Rawlsian Approaches to Resolve Ethical Issues: Inventory and Setting of a Research Agenda", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0073-5", "ex:pages": "127-143", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2010", "ex:keyword": ["Applied ethics", "Conflicting values", "Ethical methodology", "Justification", "Overlapping consensus", "Rawls", "Wide reflective equilibrium"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Neelke Doorn", "ex:email": "N.Doorn@tudelft.nl"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "77", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Using the PET Assessment Instrument to Help Students Identify Factors that Could Impede Moral Behavior", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9303-2", "ex:pages": "129-145", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Ethical decision-making", "Moral courage", "Moral intensity", "Pedagogy", "Situational pressure"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Debra Comer", "ex:email": "Debra.R.Comer@hofstra.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Gina Vega", "ex:email": "GVega@salemstate.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "76", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Nature and Management of Ethical Corporate Identity: A Commentary on Corporate Identity, Corporate Social Responsibility and Ethics", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9278-z", "ex:pages": "7-15", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Ac 2 ID test", "Corporate social responsibility", "Corporate identity", "Stakeholders", "Ethical identity"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "John Balmer"}, {"ex:name": "Kyoko Fukukawa", "ex:email": "k.fukukawa@brad.ac.uk"}, {"ex:name": "Edmund Gray"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "80", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Ethics and Lobbying: The Case of Real Estate Brokerage", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9434-0", "ex:pages": "23-35", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Brokerage", "Ethics", "Real estate", "Regulation"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "David Barker", "ex:email": "fdbarker@gsb.uchicago.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:abstract": "Two fundamental business ethics issues that repeatedly surface in the academic literature relate to businessâ€™s role in the development of public policy [Suarez, S. L.: 2000, Does Business Learn? (The University of Michigan Press, Ann Arbor, MI); Roberts, R. W. and D. D. Bobek: 2004, Accounting, Organizations and Society 29(5â€“6), 565â€“590] and its role in responsibly managing the natural environment [Newton, L.: 2005, Business Ethics and the Natural Environment (Blackwell Publishing, Oxford)]. When studied together, researchers often examine if, and how, corporations influence environmental policy decisions. Drawing from literatures onâ\\x90£corporate political activity, corporate social and environmental performance, and corporate environmental disclosure, we develop and empirically examine two research questions concerning the relations between corporate political expenditures, environmental performance, and environmental disclosure. The questions are: (1) Do corporations that are poorer environmental performers spend more on political activities than their better-performing counterparts? (2) Is there an association between corporationsâ€™ spending on political activities and the extent of their financial report environmental disclosures? We investigated these questions through analyses of data we gathered on a sample consisting of 119 U.S. environmentally sensitive firms for the 2001â€“2002 election cycle. After controlling for firm size and specific industry effects, our tests reveal a significant, inverse relationship between firm environmental performance and political spending. This is consistent with the notion that U.S. firms with relatively poorer environmental performance records engage more intensely in corporate political activities as part of their overall strategic management of their relationship with the state. In addition, a significant and positive association between the amount of political spending and the extent of environmental disclosure suggests that environmental disclosure and political spending are both proactive, complementary tactics to strategically manage public policy pressure. If corporationsâ€™ strategies are intentionally designed to unreasonably limit their environmental responsibilities or to misrepresent firm environmental performance, then we argue that these activities reflect a significant lapse in ethical conduct. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2006", "ex:volume": "67", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Corporate Political Strategy: An Examination of the Relation between Political Expenditures, Environmental Performance, and Environmental Disclosure", "ex:url": "http://h