anisational leaders. It argues that the relational and context-dependent nature of leadership necessitates reference to an ethical approach which explicitly takes these aspects into account. Such an approach is offered in the re-conceptualisation of ethical action on the part of leaders as a process of â€œcoming into right relationâ€\\x9D vis-Ã -vis those affected by their decisions and actions. Heideggerâ€™s notion of â€œdwellingâ€\\x9D is explored as a means of â€œcoming into right relationâ€\\x9D. Three aspects of dwelling: â€œstaying withâ€\\x9D, â€œcomportmentâ€\\x9D and â€œactive engagementâ€\\x9D are described and ways in which they might be practically enacted by leaders are suggested. The paper concludes by reflecting on the ways adopting a â€œdwellingâ€\\x9D approach to resolving ethical issues implies a re-conceptualisation of leadership itself. Copyright Springer 2006", "ex:volume": "65", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "When Deontology and Utilitarianism Arenâ€™t Enough: How Heideggerâ€™s Notion of â€œDwellingâ€\\x9D Might Help Organisational Leaders Resolve Ethical Issues", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-0019-0", "ex:pages": "87-98", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Business ethics", "Heidegger and ethics", "Leadership", "Leadership ethics", "Relational practices"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "D. Ladkin", "ex:email": "Donna.Ladkin@exeter.ac.uk"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "76", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Effects of Moral Development and Adverse Selection Conditions on Managersâ€™ Project Continuance Decisions: A Study in the Pacific-Rim Region", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9286-z", "ex:pages": "347-360", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Adverse selection", "Agency theory", "Moral development", "Project continuation"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "C. Chang", "ex:email": "jchang@mail.sdsu.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Sin-Hui Yen", "ex:email": "sinhui@mail.tku.edu.tw"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "76", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "A Few Bad Apples? Scandalous Behavior of Mutual Fund Managers", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9284-1", "ex:pages": "319-334", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Agency duality", "Agency theory", "Ethics", "Mutual funds", "Retirement benefits", "Reward structures"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Justin Davis", "ex:email": "davisj6@ohio.edu"}, {"ex:name": "G. Tyge Payne", "ex:email": "tyge.payne@ttu.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Gary McMahan"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "This paper considers the question of virtues appropriate to a corporate actorâ€™s moral character. A model of corporate appetites is developed by analogy with animal appetites; and the pursuit of initially virtuous corporate tendencies to an extreme degree is shown to be morally perilous. The author thus refutes a previous argument which suggested that (1) corporate virtues, unlike human virtues, need not be located on an Aristotelian mean between opposite undesirable extremes because (2) corporations do not have appetites; and (3) corporate virtues must serve the end of sustainable profit. If these disanalogies between corporate and human virtue no longer hold, then the stage is set for us to formulate a more adequate model of good corporate character that would encompass other-regarding virtues. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2007", "ex:volume": "70", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "On Corporate Virtue", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9117-2", "ex:pages": "391-400", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Appetites", "Aristotle", "Character", "Corporate agency", "Efficiency", "Golden mean", "Other-regarding", "Prudence", "Self-regarding"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Aditi Gowri", "ex:email": "ag@macroethics.ca"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "83", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Female Presence on Corporate Boards: A Multi-Country Study of Environmental Context", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9656-1", "ex:pages": "55-63", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate boards", "Environmental context", "Female directors", "Gender", "Multi-country", "Pay gap", "Political representation"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Siri Terjesen", "ex:email": "s.terjesen@qut.edu.au"}, {"ex:name": "Val Singh", "ex:email": "v.singh@cranfield.ac.uk"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "This paper examines a model of income and quality of life that controls the love of money, job satisfaction, gender, and marital status and treats employment status (full-time versus part-time), income level, and gender as moderators. For the whole sample, income was not significantly related to quality of life when this path was examined alone. When all variables were controlled, income was negatively related to quality of life. When (1) the love of money was negatively correlated to job satisfaction and (2) job satisfaction was positively related to both income and quality of life, income was negatively related to quality of life for full-time, high-income, and male employees. When these two conditions failed to exist, income was not related to quality of life for part-time, median- or low-income, and female employees. This model provides new insights regarding the impact of the love of money and job satisfaction on the incomeâ€“quality of life relationship. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2007", "ex:volume": "72", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Income and Quality of Life: Does the Love of Money Make a Difference?", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9176-4", "ex:pages": "375-393", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Income", "Quality of life", "The love of money", "Job satisfaction", "Employment status", "Income level",