Chris MacDonald", "ex:email": "chris.macdonald@smu.ca"}, {"ex:name": "Melissa Whellams"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:abstract": "Tax compliance is a concern to governments around the world. Prior research (Alm, J. and I. Sanchez: 1995, KYKLOS 48, 3â€“19) has attributed unexplained inter-country differences in compliance rates to differences in social norms. Economics researchers studying tax compliance in the United States (U.S.) (see for example J. Andreoni etÂ al.: 1998, Journal of Economic Literature 36, 818â€“860) have called for more attention to social (as opposed to economic) influences on tax compliance. In this study, we extend this prior research by explicitly examining the role of social norms [Cialdini, R. and M. Trost: 1998, The Handbook of Social Psychology (Oxford University Press, New York)] on tax compliance in three different countries. We test our research hypotheses using a hypothetical compliance scenario, which was administered in Australia, Singapore, and the U.S. There were differences in compliance rates and social norms among the three countries. Factor analysis of the social norm questions identified three distinct social norm constructs. Two of these factors were significant in explaining tax compliance behavior. The first and most influential factor was taxpayersâ€™ own personal moral beliefs, along with the beliefs of those close to them (e.g., friends and important others). The second significant factor represented societal views of proper behavior. We conclude that social norms help to explain tax compliance intentions and why tax compliance rates are higher than would be predicted by strictly economic models. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media B.V. 2007", "ex:volume": "74", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Social Norms of Tax Compliance: Evidence from Australia, Singapore, and the United States", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9219-x", "ex:pages": "49-64", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Social norms", "Tax compliance"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Donna Bobek", "ex:email": "Donna.Bobek@bus.ucf.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Robin Roberts"}, {"ex:name": "John Sweeney"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:abstract": "This paper acknowledges the paucity of attention regarding the development of ethics programs within an academic environment and describes in a case study how the Duquesne University schools of business attempted to introduce, integrate and promote its own ethics program. The paper traces the business schoolâ€™s attention to mission statements, curriculum development, ethics policy, program oversight and outcome assessment. Lessons learned are offered as suggestions for others seeking to develop and implement an ethics program in their school. Copyright Springer 2006", "ex:volume": "65", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Implementing an Organizational Ethics Program in an Academic Environment: The Challenges and Opportunities for the Duquesne University Schools of Business", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-005-3970-2", "ex:pages": "23-42", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Academic integrity", "Business schools", "Case study", "Code of ethics", "Ethics course", "Ethics programs", "Honor code", "Program assessment"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "James Weber", "ex:email": "weberj@duq.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:abstract": "The global corporate scandals such as Enron, Worldcom and Global Crossing have raised fundamental issues of business ethics as well as economic, social and anthropological questions concerning the nature of business competition and global capitalism. The purpose of this conceptual paper is to introduce the concept of â€œwelfare exchangeâ€\\x9D to the existing notions of economic, social and anthropological notions of business and exchange in markets and society in the 21st century. Global competition and business success in the 21st century continue to raise the nature of economic value and the interaction among diverse actors in international markets, institutions and society. We believe that the nature of such exchange between consumers and organizations, which can also be termed social marketing, need to increasingly take into account a welfare and ethical component. In this paper, we introduce our concept of welfare exchange to emphasize the importance of such welfare and ethical issues in the global business environment of the 21st century. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2007", "ex:volume": "74", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Consumer Trust, Social Marketing and Ethics of Welfare Exchange", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9128-z", "ex:pages": "17-23", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Welfare exchange", "Ethics", "Global capitalism", "Social marketing", "Consumer trust"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Chong Choi"}, {"ex:name": "Tarek Eldomiaty", "ex:email": "T.Eldomiaty@uaeu.ac.ae"}, {"ex:name": "Sae Kim"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "85", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Noble Markets: The Noble/Slave Ethic in Hayek’s Free Market Capitalism", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9748-6", "ex:pages": "57-66", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Free market capitalism", "Hayek", "Nietzsche", "Noble/slave ethics", "Will to power"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Edward Romar", "ex:email": "edward.romar@umb.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "77", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Softlifting: Exploring Determinants of Attitude", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9361-0", "ex:pages": "481-499", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Softlifting", "Ethics", "Piracy", "Attitude"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Tim Goles", "ex:email": "Tim.Goles@utsa.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Bandula Jayatilaka", "ex:email": "bandulaj3@gmail.com"}, {"ex:name": "Been