half of the managers scored at post-conventional level of reasoning while assessing the moral dilemmas. The reasoning scores varied for the three dilemmas. Copyright Springer 2007", "ex:volume": "71", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Managersâ€™ Moral Reasoning: Evidence from Large Indian Manufacturing Organisations", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9133-2", "ex:pages": "179-194", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Moral reasoning", "Business ethics", "Cross-cultural", "Ethical decision-making", "Moral judgement", "Cognitive moral development"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Manjit Monga", "ex:email": "manjit.monga@unisa.edu.au"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Failure of a Socially Responsive Gold Mining MNC in El Salvador: Ramifications of NGO Mistrust", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0288-5", "ex:pages": "245-268", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["El salvador", "Environment", "Multinational corporations", "Nongovernment organizations", "Mining"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Denis Collins", "ex:email": "dcollins@edgewood.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "84", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Sustaining Employee Owned Companies: Seven Recommendations", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9679-2", "ex:pages": "151-164", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Employee control", "Employee ownership", "Employee participation", "Employee share ownership plan", "Foundational values", "Industrial democracy", "Organizational culture", "Self-managed work teams", "Servant leadership", "Value based management"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "William Sauser", "ex:email": "sauser@business.auburn.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "81", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Ethical Cycles and Trends: Evidence and Implications", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9556-4", "ex:pages": "905-911", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Ethical cycles", "Ethical trends", "Ethical attitudes", "Teaching business ethics", "Enron", "M14", "B4"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Stephen Conroy", "ex:email": "sconroy@sandiego.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Tisha Emerson", "ex:email": "Tisha-Nakao@baylor.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "87", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Managing Efficient Capital Allocation with Emphasis on the Chinese Experience", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9814-0", "ex:pages": "111-135", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Banking ethics", "Banking regulations", "Basel I & II", "Risk-management", "Chinese banking"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Zhuang Cai"}, {"ex:name": "Peter Wheale", "ex:email": "whealep@wmin.ac.uk"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "81", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Sarbanes-Oxley Act of 2002: Has It Brought About Changes in the Boards of Large U. S. Corporations?", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9503-4", "ex:pages": "401-412", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate governance", "Boards of directors", "Sarbanes-oxley", "Board committees", "Board composition", "Board structure"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Alix Valenti", "ex:email": "valenti@uhcl.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:abstract": "Confronted with mounting pressure to ensure accountability vis-Ã -vis customers, citizens and beneficiaries, organizational leaders need to decide how to choose and implement so-called accountability standards. Yet while looking for an appropriate standard, they often base their decisions on cost-benefit calculations, thus neglecting other important spheres of influence pertaining to more broadly defined stakeholder interests. We argue in this paper that, as a part of the strategic decision for a certain standard, management needs to identify and act according to the needs of all stakeholders. We contend that the creation of a dialogical understanding among affected stakeholders cannot be a mere outcome of applying certain accountability standards, but rather must be a necessary precondition for their use. This requires a stakeholder dialogue prior to making a choice. We outline such a discursive decision framework for accountability standards based on the Habermasian concept of communicative action and, in the final section, apply our conceptual framework to one of the most prominent accountability tools (AA 1000). Copyright Springer 2006", "ex:volume": "65", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "From Stakeholder Management to Stakeholder Accountability", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-005-5355-y", "ex:pages": "251-267", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Accountability standards", "Discourse ethics", "Habermas", "Organizational accountability", "Stakeholder management", "Stakeholder dialogue"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Andreas Rasche", "ex:email": "arasche@hsu-hh.de"}, {"ex:name": "Daniel Esser", "ex:email": "esser@alum.mit.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "84", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Philanthropy, Integration or Innovation? Exploring the Financial and Societal Outcomes of Different Types of Corporate Responsibility", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9712-5", "ex:pages": "325-339", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate responsibility", "Corporate social responsibility", "Financial performance", "Corporate social performance"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Minna Halme", "ex:email": "minna.halme@hse.fi"}, {"ex:name": "Juha Laurila", "ex:email": "juha.laurila@tse.fi"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:abstract": "Concerns with improper collection and usage of personal information by businesses or governments have been seen as critical to the success of the emerging electronic commerce. In this regard, computer professionals have the oversight responsibility for information privacy because they have the most extensive knowledge of their organizationâ€™s systems and programs, as well as an intimate understanding of the data. Thus, the competence of these professionals in ensuring sound practice of information privacy is of great importance to both researchers and practitioners. This research addresses the question of whether male computer professionals differ from their female counterparts in their self-regulatory efficacy to protect personal information privacy. A total of 103 male and 65 female subjects surveyed in Taiwan responded to a 10-item questionnaire that includes three measures: protection (protecting privacy information), non-distribution (not distributing privacy information to others), and non-acquisition (not acquiring privacy information). The findings show (1) significant gender differences exist in the subjectsâ€™ overall self-regulatory efficacy for information privacy, and, in particular, (2) that female subjects in this study exhibited a higher level of self-regulatory efficacy than males for the protection and non-acquisition of personal privacy information. The identification of the factorial structure of the self-regulatory efficacy concerning information privacy may contribute to future research directed to examining the links between privacy efficacy and psychological variables, such as ethical attitude, ethical intention, and self-esteem. Studies can also be extended to investigate how different cultural practices of morality and computer use in men and women may shape the different development patterns of privacy self-efficacy. Understanding the different cultural practices may then shed light on the social sources of privacy competence and the appropriate remedies that can be provided to improve the situation. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2007", "ex:volume": "73", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Assessing Gender Differences in Computer Professionalsâ€™ Self-Regulatory Efficacy Concerning Information Privacy Practices", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9179-1", "ex:pages": "145-160", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Gender", "Information privacy", "Self-regulatory efficacy"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Feng-Yang Kuo"}, {"ex:name": "Cathy Lin", "ex:email": "cathy@nuk.edu.tw"}, {"ex:name": "Meng-Hsiang Hsu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "83", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Institutional Pillars and Corruption at the Societal Level", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9622-y", "ex:pages": "327-339", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Institutional pillars", "Organizational corruption"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Ji Li", "ex:email": "jili@hkbu.edu.hk"}, {"ex:name": "Jane Moy"}, {"ex:name": "Kevin Lam"}, {"ex:name": "W.L. Chris Chu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:abstract": "This paper raises the question of how ethical issues arising out of social inequities involving international business in developing countries can be represented, and articulates a conceptual framework that identifies and maps four different approaches to representing or making sense of such issues. A fieldwork-based case study on the child labor issue in Pakistanâ€™s soccer ball industry illustrates the argument that representational practices do matter, and that when representational approaches go awry, they end up savaging the well-being of the poor in the developing world. Copyright Springer 2007", "ex:volume": "73", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Representational Approaches Matter", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9199-x", "ex:pages": "77-89", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Child labor", "Corporate social responsibility", "International business", "Postcolonial", "Representation"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:na