lenges, allows application of concepts, creates a personal emotional engagement in the case, is relevant, holds students accountable for their position, and creates a setting that encourages students to think critically about ethics. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2006", "ex:volume": "67", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Using Live Cases to Teach Ethics", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9035-3", "ex:pages": "421-433", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Application of ethics", "Critical thinking", "Emotional engagement in ethics", "Increased awareness of ethics", "Live cases", "Student accountability", "Teaching ethics", "Teaching ethics in finance"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Victoria McWilliams", "ex:email": "victoria.mcwilliams@villanova.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Afsaneh Nahavandi", "ex:email": "anahavandi@asu.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "84", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Story and Narrative Noticing: Workaholism Autoethnographies", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9702-7", "ex:pages": "173-194", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Story", "Narrative", "Ethics", "Workaholic", "Autoethnography"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "David Boje", "ex:email": "dboje@nmsu.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Jo Tyler"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:abstract": "Western attempts to obtain Chinese compliance with intellectual property rights have a long history of failure. Most discussions of the problem focus on either legal comparisons or explanations arising from levels of economic development (based primarily on the example of U.S. disregard for such rights during the 18th and 19th centuries). After decades of heated negotiation, intellectual property rights is still one of the major issues of misunderstanding between the West and the various Chinese political entities. This paper examines the sources of this problem from the standpoint of traditional Chinese social and political philosophy (specifically Neo-Confucianism). It points out that the basic assumptions about the nature of intellectual property, which arose during the 17th and 18th centuries in Europe, are fundamentally at odds with the traditional Chinese view of the role of intellectuals in society. It suggests that policies which do not take these differences into account, but which attempt to transfer Western legal concepts without the underlying social constructs are responsible for much of the lack of success in the area of intellectual property rights. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2006", "ex:volume": "69", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Intellectual Property Rights and Chinese Tradition Section: Philosophical Foundations", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9059-8", "ex:pages": "1-9", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["China", "Intellectual property rights", "Neo-confucianism", "Confucian ethics", "Chinese ethics", "Copyright"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "John Lehman"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "85", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Mutually Dependent: Power, Trust, Affect and the Use of Deception in Negotiation", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9774-4", "ex:pages": "347-365", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Deception", "Dyadic negotiation", "Impressions", "Power", "Affect"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Mara Olekalns", "ex:email": "m.olekalns@mbs.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Philip Smith"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "77", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Work and The Most Terrible Life", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9353-0", "ex:pages": "335-345", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Business ethics", "Meaning of work", "Meaningful work", "Professional responsibility", "Tolstoy", "Work"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Christopher Michaelson", "ex:email"