Index: Asian Emerging Economies", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9459-4", "ex:pages": "643-651", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Business ethics", "Consumer sentiments", "Business ethics index", "Bei", "China", "India"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "John Tsalikis", "ex:email": "tsalikis@fiu.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Bruce Seaton"}, {"ex:name": "Tiger Li"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "80", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Management and Legal Issues Regarding Electronic Surveillance of Employees in the Workplace", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9449-6", "ex:pages": "175-180", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Security issues", "Surveillance of employees"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "David Halpern"}, {"ex:name": "Patrick Reville"}, {"ex:name": "Donald Grunewald", "ex:email": "Dgrune34@aol.com"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:abstract": "Social contract theory offers a powerful method and metaphor for the study of organizational ethics. This paper considers the variant of the social contract that has arguably gained the most attention among business ethicists: integrative social contracts theory or ISCT [Donaldson and Dunfee: 1999, Ties That Bind (Harvard Business School Press, Boston)]. A core precept of ISCT â€“ that consent to membership in an organization entails obligations to follow the norms of that organization, subject to the moral minimums of basic human rights â€“ is a reasonable and appealing notion. One potential challenge for those attempting to apply this idea, however, lies in the dynamic nature of social norms. Organizational norms evolve, often through the conscious efforts of community members and leaders. As currently formulated, ISCT offers a framework that under-appreciates the evolving nature of moral norms. In this paper, we extend ISCT by considering the circumstances under which the terms of and parties to social contracts change. We also consider a number of principles that should be considered as the terms and parties to organizational social contracts change. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2006", "ex:volume": "68", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Ties that Unwind: Dynamism in Integrative Social Contracts Theory 1", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9015-7", "ex:pages": "283-302", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Social contract", "Isct", "Ethics", "Dynamism", "Stakeholder", "Organizational change"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Robert Phillips", "ex:email": "rphilli3@richmond.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Michael Johnson-Cramer"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Evolution of Maquiladora Best Practices: 1965–2008", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0285-8", "ex:pages": "335-348", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Maquiladora industry", "Mexico", "Best practices", "Continuous improvement"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Jorge Carrillo", "ex:email": "carrillo@colef.mx"}, {"ex:name": "Robert Zárate", "ex:email": "robertzarate@uabc.mx"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "87", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "A Meta-Analytic Investigation of Business Ethics Instruction", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9875-0", "ex:pages": "133-151", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Ethics", "Business ethics", "Ethics instruction", "Ethics training", "Training effectiveness", "Meta-analysis"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Ethan Waples", "ex:email": "ewaples@lsus.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Alison Antes"}, {"ex:name": "Stephen Murphy"}, {"ex:name": "Shane Connelly"}, {"ex:name": "Michael Mumford"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "89", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Theorising Corporate Social Responsibility as an Essentially Contested Concept: Is a Definition Necessary?", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-0021-9", "ex:pages": "613-627", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate social responsibility", "Essentially contested concepts", "Business", "Society", "Definition"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Adaeze Okoye", "ex:email": "adaeze.okoye@canterbury.ac.uk"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "86", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Preserving Employee Dignity During the Termination Interview: An Empirical Examination", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9862-5", "ex:pages": "519-534", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Employee dignity", "Ethical termination practices", "Ethics in management", "Employee respect", "Termination interviews"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Matthew Wood", "ex:email": "mswood2@siu.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Steven Karau"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "86", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Impact of Ethics Education on Reporting Behavior", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9854-5", "ex:pages": "397-416", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Ethics education", "Anonymity", "Public disclosure", "Integration", "Ethical values"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Brian Mayhew"}, {"ex:name": "Pamela Murphy", "ex:email": "pmurphy@business.queensu.ca"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "80", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Linking Linear/Nonlinear Thinking Style Balance and Managerial Ethical Decision-Making", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9422-4", "ex:pages": "305-325", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Cognitive style", "Ethical philosophy", "Ethical decision-making", "Emotion", "Intuition", "Thinking style"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Kevin Groves", "ex:email": "kgroves@calstatela.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Charles Vance"}, {"ex:name": "Yongsun Paik"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:abstract": "This paper revisits the â€œmorality paysâ€\\x9D approach to answering the â€œWhy be moral?â€\\x9D question in business. First I argue that â€œmorality paysâ€\\x9D is weakest when it needs to be strongest, and thus inadequate to the task. Then I examine and reject a proposed virtue-ethics alternative, arguing that it either collapses into â€œmorality paysâ€\\x9D or else introduces a new problem. After sketching an account of moral reasons, I go on to argue that â€œmorality paysâ€\\x9D can be reframed, not so much as an answer to â€œWhy be moral,â€\\x9D but as a prescription for reforming corporate institutions. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2006", "ex:volume": "67", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Reframing â€œMorality Paysâ€\\x9D: Toward a Better Answer to â€œWhy be Moral?â€\\x9D in Business", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9001-0", "ex:pages": "1-14", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Why be moral?", "Ethics pays", "Morality pays", "Ethics", "Virtue ethics", "Moral reasons", "Moral motivation", "Hosmer"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "John Corvino", "ex:email": "j.corvino@wayne.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "77", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Marketing in Heterozygous Advantage", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9301-4", "ex:pages": "85-97", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Bioethics", "Marketing", "Heterozygous advantage"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Gregory Jones", "ex:email": "gtjones@gsu.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Reidar Hagtvedt"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:abstract": "An emergent body of literature examined why some firms apply some environmental initiatives while other firms do not take responsibility for their natural environment? Thus, firm environmental orientation (responsiveness and performance) are linked in the literature to several variables. Unfortunately, the relationship between firm environmental orientation and either available resources or firm size showed mixed results and inconclusive evidence. Therefore, the aim of this paper is to show empirically how available resources and firm size can explain differences in firm environmental responsiveness and environmental performance. Econometric results of environmental responsiveness using the logistic regression model demonstrated that firm size does appear to add something unique in explaining differences in environmental responsiveness while available resource can be safely dropped from the model. However, econometric analysis of environmental performance using the maximum-likelihood random effects model showed strong evidence that available resources and firm size are significant predictors of firm environmental performance. Copyright Springer 2006", "ex:volume": "65", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Reexamining the Expected Effect of Available Resources and Firm Size on Firm Environmental Orientation: An Empirical Study of UK Firms", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-6402-z", "ex:pages": "297-308", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Available resources", "Environmental orientation", "Environmental performance", "Environmental responsiveness", "Firm size", "Logistic regression", "Nested models", "Random effects model"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Khaled Elsayed", "ex:email": "K_Elsayed@mailer.eun.eg"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Non-Discrimination in Human Resources Management as a Moral Obligation", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0100-6", "ex:pages": "83-101", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Discrimination", "Diversity", "Human resources management", "Implicit association", "Csr"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Geert Demuijnck", "ex:email": "geert.demuijnck@edhec.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "91", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Cultural Competences: An Important Resource in the Industry–NGO Dialog", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0089-x", "ex:pages": "379-390", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2010", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate social responsibility", "Conflict", "Consumer", "Cultural competence", "Dialog", "Discourse", "Ethical dispute", "Forest industry", "Ngo"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Maria Joutsenvirta", "ex:email": "maria.joutsenvirta@gmail.com"}, {"ex:name": "Liisa Uusitalo", "ex:email": "liisa.uusitalo@hse.fi"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:abstract": "This essay seeks to give a contractarian foundation to the concept of Corporate Social Responsibility (CSR), meant as an extended model of corporate governance of the firm. It focuses on justification according to the contractarian point of view (leaving compliance and implementation problems to a related article, [Sacconi 2004b, forthcoming in the Journal of Business Ethics]). It begins by providing a definition of CSR as an extended model of corporate governance, based on the fiduciary duties owed to all the firmâ€™s stakeholders. Then, by establishing the basic context of incompleteness of contracts and abuse of authority, it analyses how the extended view of corporate governance arises directly from criticism of the contemporary neo-institutional economic theory of the firm. Thereafter, an application of the theory of bargaining games is used to deduce the structure of a multi-stakeholder firm, on the basis of the idea of a constitutional contract, which satisfies basic requirements of impartial justification and accordance with intuitions of social justice. This is a sequential model of constitutional bargaining, whereby a constitution is first chosen, and then a post-constitutional coalition game is played. On the basis of the unique solution given to each step in the bargaining model, the quest for a prescriptive theory of governance and strategic management is accomplished, so that I am able to define an objective-function for the firm consistent with the idea of CSR. Finally, a contractarian potential explanation for the emergence of the multi-fiduciary firm is provided. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2006", "ex:volume": "68", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "A Social Contract Account for CSR as an Extended Model of Corporate Governance (I): Rational Bargaining and Justification", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9014-8", "ex:pages": "259-281", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Fiduciary duties", "Stakeholder theory", "Theory of the firm", "Incompleteness of contracts", "Social contract", "Bargaining games", "Distributive justice", "Impartiality"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Lorenzo Sacconi", "ex:email": "lorenzo.sacconi@economia.unitn.it"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:abstract": "Recent, well-publicized accounting scandals have shown that the penalties outsiders impose on those found culpable of earnings management can be severe. However, less is known about how colleagues within internal labor markets respond when they believe fellow managers have managed earnings. Designers of responsibility accounting systems need to understand the reputational costs managers impose on one another within internal labor markets. In an experimental study, 159 evening MBA students were asked to assume the role of a manager in a company and respond to a scenario in which another manager (the target manager) has the opportunity to engage in earnings management. Participants provided causal attributions, assessed the morality of the target manager, and indicated whether they would change their judgments about the target managerâ€™s reputation. The study manipulated three between-subjects factors: (1) whether the target manager chose to engage in earnings management, (2) whether the companyâ€™s budgetary control system was rigid or flexible, and (3) whether the target managerâ€™s work history was average or above average. We found that causal attributions are affected more by the budgetary systems when the target did not manage earnings than when the manager did. We also found that morality judgments were significantly associated with the target managerâ€™s behavior, but not with the budgetary system. In addition, participantsâ€™ judgments about the target managerâ€™s reputation were more strongly associated with morality judgments than with causal attributions. We discuss implications of the role of reputation in management control systems design. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media B.V. 2007", "ex:volume": "74", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Moral Judgment and Causal Attributions: Consequences of Engaging in Earnings Management", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9226-y", "ex:pages": "149-164", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Budgetary control system", "Causal attributions", "Earnings management", "Moral judgment", "Work history"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Steven Kaplan"}, {"ex:name": "James McElroy"}, {"ex:name": "Susan Ravenscroft"}, {"ex:name": "Charles Shrader", "ex:email": "cshrader@iastate.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "84", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Introduction: The Wide Reach of Business Ethics", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9694-3", "ex:pages": "1-2", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Patrick Flanagan", "ex:email": "flanagap@stjohns.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Marilynn Fleckenstein"}, {"ex:name": "Patrick Primeaux"}, {"ex:name": "Victoria Schoaf"}, {"ex:name": "Patricia Werhane"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "92", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "A New Methodological Approach for Studying Moral Reasoning Among Managers in Business Settings", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0146-5", "ex:pages": "149-166", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2010", "ex:keyword": ["Moral reasoning", "Managerial ethics", "Ethics in b