ks; and third, to identify a number of related research imperatives â€“ in particular the importance of focusing efforts on gaining a deeper understanding of the deliberative process itself. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2007", "ex:volume": "70", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Constructing Good Decisions in Ethically Charged Situations: The Role of Dramatic Rehearsal", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9116-3", "ex:pages": "375-390", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Ethical decision-making", "John dewey", "Dramatic rehearsal", "Ethics"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "John McVea", "ex:email": "jfmcvea@stthomas.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "80", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Impact of Post-restatement Actions Taken by a Firm on Non-professional Investors’ Credibility Perceptions", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9442-0", "ex:pages": "61-76", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate governance", "Credibility", "Restatements", "Trust"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Elizabeth Almer"}, {"ex:name": "Audrey Gramling"}, {"ex:name": "Steven Kaplan", "ex:email": "steve.kaplan@asu.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Editorial Introduction: Towards a More Humanistic Management", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0129-6", "ex:pages": "413-416", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Domènec Melé", "ex:email": "mele@iese.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "83", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Proximity and Rationalisation: The Limits of a Levinasian Ethics in the Context of Corporate Governance and Regulation", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9639-2", "ex:pages": "565-577", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Levinas", "Corporate governance", "Corporate regulation", "The other", "Dialogue", "Mediation", "Rationality", "Bureaucracy"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Samuel Mansell", "ex:email": "sam.mansell@gmail.com"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "89", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "An Investigation of Real Versus Perceived CSP in S&P-500 Firms", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9999-2", "ex:pages": "283-296", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate reputation", "Corporate social responsibility", "Fortune america’s most admired companies", "Kld data regression analysis"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Catherine Liston-Heyes", "ex:email": "c.liston-heyes@rhul.ac.uk"}, {"ex:name": "Gwen Ceton"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "91", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Stakeholders’ Perceptions and Future Scenarios to Improve Corporate Social Responsibility in Hong Kong and Mainland China", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0091-3", "ex:pages": "391-404", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2010", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate social responsibility", "Stakeholder perception and expectation", "Future scenarios", "Supply chain", "Hong kong", "Mainland china"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Joyce Tsoi", "ex:email": "joyce.tsoi@brunel.ac.uk"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "80", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "An Integral Model of Collective Action in Organizations and Beyond", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9416-2", "ex:pages": "249-261", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Collective action", "Public good", "Developmental psychology", "Spirituality", "Integral psychology", "Psychology value"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Lu Tang", "ex:email": "ltang@usc.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "75", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "A Model for Fair Trade Buying Behaviour: The Role of Perceived Quantity and Quality of Information and of Product-specific Attitudes", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9259-2", "ex:pages": "361-380", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Attitudes", "Belgium", "Buying behaviour", "Fair trade", "Information"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Patrick Pelsmacker", "ex:email": "patrick.depelsmacker@ua.ac.be"}, {"ex:name": "Wim Janssens"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Multiple Communities and Controlling Corruption", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0320-9", "ex:pages": "805-813", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Corruption", "Integrative social contract theory", "International law", "Microsocial contracts"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Philip Nichols", "ex:email": "nicholsp@wharton.upenn.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "Although McMahon offers a potentially valuable extension of Joseph Raz's conceptualization of authority by distinguishing three different kinds of authority, this paper argues, first, that his account of the conditions and considerations that would justify managerial authority is problematic because it relies on a conception of reasons for action that excludes precisely the kind of rationality that plays an important role in theâ\\x90£explanation and justification of authority in economicâ\\x90£organization. This paper explains, second, why McMahon's thesis of the justificatory similarity of authority in governments and nongovernmental organizations can also be seen to hold for corporate governance of publicly owned firms more specifically. Finally, this paper raises some critical objections against McMahon's presumption of democratic governance in governments and NGO's alike. The thrust of these objections is that democratic corporate governance does not make sense in the publicly owned firms because: (1) it will not produce results that are fair or welfare maximizing, and (2) it will undermine the legitimacy of managerial authority in such firms. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2007", "ex:volume": "71", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Authority and Democracy in Corporate Governance?", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9146-x", "ex:pages": "359-370", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate governance", "Mcmahon", "Raz", "Authority", "Managerial democracy", "Economic theory of the firm"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "J. (Hans) van Oosterhout", "ex:email": "joosterhout@fbk.eur.nl"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:abstract": "Guanxi (literally interpersonal connections) is in essence a network of resource coalition-based stakeholders sharing resources for survival, and it plays a key role in achieving business success in China. However, the salience of guanxi stakeholders varies: not all guanxi relationships are necessary, and among the necessary guanxi participants, not all are equally important. A hierarchical stakeholder model of guanxi is developed drawing upon Mitchell etÂ al.â€™s ( 1997 ) stakeholder salience theory and Andersonâ€™s ( 1982 ) constituency theory. As an application of instrumental stakeholder theory, the model dimensionalizes the notion of stakeholder salience, and distinguishes between and among internal and external guanxi, core, major, and peripheral guanxi, and primary and secondary guanxi stakeholders. Guanxi management principles are developed based on a hierarchy of guanxi priorities and management specializations. The goal of this application of instrumental stakeholder theory is to construct, for Western business firms in China, a means to reliably identify guanxi partners by employing the principles of effective guanxi. These principles are described in the form of testable propositions that advance social scientific research in this area of international business ethics. Copyright Springer 2007", "ex:volume": "71", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Enabling Guanxi Management in China: A Hierarchical Stakeholder Model of Effective Guanxi", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9140-3", "ex:pages": "301-319", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["China", "Guanxi", "Guanxi management", "Stakeholder salience"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Chenting Su", "ex:email": "mkctsu@cityu.edu.hk"}, {"ex:name": "Ronald K. Mitchell"}, {"ex:name": "M. Joseph Sirgy"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:abstract": "When the Federal Communications Commission considered revamping its policies, many political activists argued that media conglomerates had failed to meet their duties to protect freedom of speech. Moveonâ€™s dispute with CBS over its proposed Superbowl advertisement and Michael Mooreâ€™s quarrel over distribution of his documentary, Fahrenheit 911, are cases in point. In matters of pure entertainment, the public expect companies to avoid offensive programming. The press, on the other hand, may well be forced to offend some audience members in order to create a viable forum for political dissent. As journalism and entertainment are increasingly inter-linked, an in depth moral analysis of the media corporation and its obligations becomes increasingly important. I explore Kantian, Utilitarian, and Rawlsian analyses of corporate obligation in the aforementioned cases. I then examine whether or not these results suggest anything more generally about the sorts of mission statements and ethical policies that ought to be endorsed by media conglomerates and whether non-business institutions also require changes. Ultimately, I suggest that at a minimum, media institutions should view the duty to promote the representation of diverse views in a democracy as an imperfect moral and civic duty rather than making programming decisions solely by reference to profit. Ideally, greater access to media access should not be increased for the most powerful unless doing so at the same time increases free speech opportunities for those who currently have the least access. Copyright Springer 2006", "ex:volume": "66", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Infotainment and the Moral Obligations of the Multimedia Conglomerate", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-005-5590-2", "ex:pages": "253-260", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate speech", "Free speech", "Infotainment", "Media ethics", "Multimedia conglomerates"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Mary Stoll"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "84", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "African Ubuntu Philosophy and Global Management", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0204-z", "ex:pages": "313-328", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Africa", "Common good", "Community", "Tradition", "Ubuntu", "Virtue"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "David Lutz", "ex:email": "david_w_lutz@yahoo.com"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:abstract": "This paper describes the research carried out into small and medium enterprises (SMEs) and corporate responsibility (CR) in the Northwest of England during Phase I of Responsibility Northwest, a partnership programme designed to significantly increase the CR of the region. By engaging with significant numbers of SMEs and SME support providers across the region, key insights were gained in three key areas: The current attitudes to, understanding of, and management of CR issues in the SME sector. The barriers to greater implementation of CR management. The opportunities for overcoming the barriers and improving regional CR. The research revealed a large diversity both in terms of understanding of the issues and their management. Seven key barriers to improve CR performance were identified which centred round the inappropriateness and inaccessibility of current CR approaches and support services on CR, certain characteristics of SMEs which tend to reduce their interest and opportunities for engaging in CR activities and supply-chain barriers. Fortunately there was significant agreement on the mechanisms which should be used to overcome these barriers, in particular the importance of delivering CR support through existing business networks that are valued and trusted by SMEs. These results have been used to create the partnership programme, Responsibility Northwest Phase II that runs until 2008 and aims to significantly increase the overall CR of Northwest England. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2006", "ex:volume": "67", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Generating Regional-Scale Improvements in SME Corporate Responsibility Performance: Lessons from Responsibility Northwest", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9184-4", "ex:pages": "275-286", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Business networks", "Corporate responsibility", "Northwest england", "Regional competitiveness", "Small and medium-sized enterprises"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Sarah Roberts"}, {"ex:name": "Rob Lawson", "ex:email": "r.lawson@snw.org.uk"}, {"ex:name": "Jeremy Nicholls"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "92", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Challenges to Legitimacy at the Forest Stewardship Council", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0154-5", "ex:pages": "279-290", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2010", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate responsibility", "Sustainability", "Forestry", "Legitimacy", "Global governance", "Certification systems", "Ecolabel"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Donald Schepers", "ex:email": "donald.schepers@baruch.cuny.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Micro Credit in Chiapas, México: Poverty Reduction Through Group Lending", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0286-7", "ex:pages": "283-299", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Micro credit", "Poverty reduction", "Joint liability and group lending", "Social responsibility"], "e