", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Institutionalization of Fair Trade: More than Just a Degraded Form of Social Action", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9758-4", "ex:pages": "63-79", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Fair trade", "Globalization", "Institutionalization", "New social economic movements", "New social movements", "Social action"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Corinne Gendron"}, {"ex:name": "Véronique Bisaillon", "ex:email": "bisaillon.veronique@uqam.ca"}, {"ex:name": "Ana Rance"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "87", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "A Stakeholder’s Perspective on Human Resource Management", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9868-z", "ex:pages": "31-43", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Human resource management", "Industrial restructuring", "Political alliances", "Stakeholder theory"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Michel Ferrary", "ex:email": "Michel.Ferrary@ceram.fr"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "80", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Corporations as Political Actors – A Report on the First Swiss Master Class in Corporate Social Responsibility", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9418-0", "ex:pages": "151-173", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Firms as political actors", "Global governance", "Stakeholder collaboration", "Conflict zones", "Corporate accountability", "Political responsibility", "Ngo legitimacy", "Consumer responsibility", "Hard and soft law", "Human rights"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Andreas Rasche", "ex:email": "arasche@hsu-hh.de"}, {"ex:name": "Dorothea Baur"}, {"ex:name": "Mariëtte Huijstee", "ex:email": "m.vanhuijstee@geo.uu.nl"}, {"ex:name": "Stephen Ladek", "ex:email": "sladek@internationalsolutionsgroup.com"}, {"ex:name": "Jayanthi Naidu", "ex:email": "j.naidu@qmul.ac.uk"}, {"ex:name": "Cecilia Perla", "ex:email": "cecilia_perla@brown.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Esther Schouten", "ex:email": "schouten@fsw.eur.nl"}, {"ex:name": "Michael Valente", "ex:email": "mvalente@schulich.yorku.ca"}, {"ex:name": "Mingrui Zhang", "ex:email": "zhangmingrui@hotmail.com"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:abstract": "This paper proposes that a corporationâ€™s vulnerability to public scrutiny drives its corporate giving. The hypothesis that companies donate for strategic motives is tested against the alternative that they do so for altruistic reasons. Court cases and news articles were selected as proxies for public scrutiny. Macroeconomic variables were used to gauge the level of public charitable need and test for altruism. Through examining the philanthropic behavior of 40 Fortune 500 companies over 7Â years, this paper finds that companies are strategic and altruistic in their giving. Copyright Springer 2006", "ex:volume": "69", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Impact of Public Scrutiny on Corporate Philanthropy", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9087-4", "ex:pages": "217-236", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Altruism", "Corporate giving", "Corporate philanthropy", "Strategic philanthropy", "D64", "G34"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Ailian Gan", "ex:email": "ailian.gan@gmail.com"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "In this paper, the nature of the contract of employment is explored from an ethical point of view. It is argued that certain normative arguments should be taken into account in order to justify such a contract. Furthermore, an argument is developed against the claim that (a) the individualâ€™s freedom of decision and (b) the practice of institutional arrangements are sufficient to justify a contract of employment. The dimensional analysis offered shows that further conditions are needed: (a) must be elaborated and interpreted to the extent that this condition is not sufficient â€“ rather sub-criteria regarding the agentâ€™s state of knowledge must be met; and (b) should be supplemented by a demand for fairness. A tentative analysis of existing work contracts is the starting point for the ethical analysis. The aim is to show what a legitimate, or reasonable, contract of employment will require. Finally, some important normative implications and consequences regarding the contractâ€™s normative status are discussed. Copyright Springer 2006", "ex:volume": "66", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Contract of Employment - Ethical Dimensions", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-0022-5", "ex:pages": "407-415", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Contract of employment", "Ethics", "Ethical justification", "Freedom of decision", "Institutional arrangements", "Voluntariness", "Work"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Anders Persson", "ex:email": "ap@infra.kth.se"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "89", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Leaders and Laggards: The Influence of Competing Logics on Corporate Environmental Action", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-0010-z", "ex:pages": "449-472", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Environmental performance", "Environmental reporting", "Institutional logics", "Legitimacy", "Corporate responsibility"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Irene Herremans", "ex:email": "irene.herremans@haskayne.ucalgary.ca"}, {"ex:name": "M. Herschovis", "ex:email": "sandy_hershcovis@umanitoba.ca"}, {"ex:name": "Stephanie Bertels", "ex:email": "stephanie_bertels@sfu.ca"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "80", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Imperfections and Shortcomings of the Stakeholder Model’s Graphical Representation", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9474-5", "ex:pages": "879-888", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Freeman’s model", "Graphical framework", "Stakeholder", "Stakeholder model", "Stakeholder reciprocity", "Stakeholder theory", "Strategy"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Yves Fassin", "ex:email": "y.fassin@skynet.be"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "78", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Ethics, Power and Communities: Corporate Social Responsibility Revisited", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9339-3", "ex:pages": "475-485", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Ally-building", "Communities", "Corporate social responsibility", "Ethics", "Inter-organizational", "Reciprocity", "Nissan", "Starbucks", "Pfeffer"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Denise Kleinrichert", "ex:email": "kleinrichert@ij.net"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:abstract": "The Principles of Corporate Governance require that business conduct conform to the law. In recent years, news reports of business misconduct have cast doubt on a conclusion that conformity is the prevalent practice. This article explores the influence of law on business conduct by comparing the lawâ€™s requirements and purposes with actual business conduct in the market. Specifically, it explores whether certain legal regimes are more effective than others in inducing greater commitment to legal compliance by corporate actors. The conclusion drawn is that the prevalent legal regime â€“ a vague common law or legislative mandate â€“ is typically associated with corporate conduct that evades or ignores the lawâ€™s mandate or its underlying purpose. Copyright Springer 2007", "ex:volume": "71", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Business Ethics: Law As A Determinant of Business Conduct", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9139-9", "ex:pages": "275-299", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate behavior", "Corporate governance", "Ethical obligation to comply with law", "Legal compliance", "Organizational theory"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Vincent Di Lorenzo", "ex:email": "dilorenv@stjohns.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "84", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Associations Between Epistemological Beliefs and Moral Reasoning: Evidence from Accounting", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9707-2", "ex:pages": "259-275", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Epistemological beliefs", "Moral reasoning", "Accounting education", "Ethics teaching"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Natalia M. Mintchik", "ex:email": "mintchikn@umsl.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Timothy A. Farmer"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "80", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Strategy Making and the Search for Authenticity", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9415-3", "ex:pages": "237-248", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Strategy", "Authenticity", "Collaboration", "Heidegger"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Jeanne Liedtka", "ex:email": "liedtkaj@darden.virginia.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Humanising Business Through Ethical Labelling: Progress and Paradoxes in the UK", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0125-x", "ex:pages": "583-600", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Ethical labelling", "Corporate responsibility", "Ethical business", "Civil society regulation", "Fairtrade"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Susanne Hartlieb", "ex:email": "susanne.hartlieb@web.de"}, {"ex:name": "Bryn Jones", "ex:email": "B.Jones@bath.ac.uk"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "Guanxi in China is a very ancient concept embedded in the Confucian concept of life and one that is a â€šhot' topic in that it is currently attracting increasing attention from both Western and Chinese scholars. One aspect of Guanxi which has been the subject of most of the research of late is the influence of Guanxi on firm performance. However, relatively few studies have examined how Guanxi at the individual level is transferred into a firm to influence its financial performance. This study first reclassifies Guanxi into obligatory, reciprocal, and utilitarian types at the individual level as a means to clarifying the confusion brought above from previous studies. It then provides a conceptual framework in which to systematically characterize the link between Guanxi at the individual level and organizational dynamics: that is, how is Guanxi at the individual level shifted to a firm and how does it affect organizational dynamics of that firm at the organizational level. Finally, it provides a deeper understanding of the financial implications of Guanxi to business firms in China. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2006", "ex:volume": "67", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Guanxi and organizational dynamics in China: a link between individual and organizational levels", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9031-7", "ex:pages": "375-392", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["China", "Guanxi", "Individual level", "Link", "Organizational dynamics", "Organizational level"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Yi Zhang", "ex:email": "yizhanghn@hotmail.com"}, {"ex:name": "Zigang Zhang"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "Did the September 11, 2001 terrorist attacks on the U.S. cause the values of teenagers in the U.S. to change? Did their previously important self-esteem and self-actualization values become less important and their survival and safety values become more important? Changes in the values of teenagers are important for practitioners, managers, marketers, and researchers to understand because high school students are our current and future employees, managers, and customers, and research has shown that values impact work and consumer-related attitudes and behaviors. Further, studies that compared higher to lower performing for-profit and not-for-profit companies have found that higher performing organizations had strong values that permeated their organizations [Collins J. C., and J. I. Porras: 1994, Built to Last: Successful Habits of Visionary Companies (New York, Harper Business); Oâ€™Reilly, C. A. and J. A. Chatman: 1996, in B. M. Staw and L. L. Cummings (eds.), Research in Organizational Behavior, vol. 18 (JAI Press, Greenwhich, CT), pp. 157â€“200; Oâ€™Reilly, C. A.: 1989, California Management Review 31(4), 9â€“25; Posner, B. Z., and W. H. Schmidt: 1996, Public Personnel Management, 25(3), 277â€“298; Rousseau, D.: 1990, Group and Organization Studies 15(4), 448â€“460; Schein, E. H.: 2004, Organizational Culture and Leadership. San Francisco, Jossey Bass)]. While one study of adults found value changes, no known studies have explored if the values of teenagers also changed post-9/11. This study filled that research gap by exploring the values of a random sample of 1000 U.S. teenagers in grades 9 to 12 pre- and post-9/11, using a demographic questionnaire and the Rokeach Value Survey. The research results indicated that teenage survival, safety, and security values (a world at peace, freedom, national security, and salvation) increased in importance while their self-esteem and self-actualization values (a sense of accomplishment, inner harmony, pleasure, self-respect, and wisdom) decreased in importance, mirroring the changes for adults. The meaning of these findings for practitioners, managers, marketers and researchers was discussed. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2006", "ex:volume": "69", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "9/11 Impact on Teenage Values", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9098-1", "ex:pages": "399-421", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Emotional or traumatic events", "9/11 impact", "Value change", "Teenage values"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Edward Murphy", "ex:email": "efmurphy@msn.com"}, {"ex:name": "Mark Woodhull"}, {"ex:name": "Bert Post"}, {"ex:name": "Carolyn Murphy-Post"}, {"ex:name": "William Teeple"}, {"ex:name": "Kent Anderson"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "87", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Is Corporate Responsibility Converging? A Comparison of Corporate Responsibility Reporting in the USA, UK, Australia, and Germany", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9794-0", "ex:pages": "299-317", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate social responsibility", "Country", "Industry", "Global standards", "Global compact", "Content analysis", "Leximancer"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Stephen Chen", "ex:email": "Stephen.chen@mq.edu.au"}, {"ex:name": "Petra Bouvain", "ex:email": "Petra.Bouvain@canberra.edu.au"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:abstract": "The paper reports on research undertaken in three organisations seeking to explore anomie at work. This research explores whether a distinction in the levels of anomie between peopleâ€™s perception of the work and non-work contexts exists in three organisations, that is whether people are more likely to feel more hopeless and helpless in their work or non-work life. It also looks at whether people in different organisations have significantly different levels of anomie. A significant difference in the non-work anomie between organisations, but no significant difference in work anomie between organisations, was found. In the three organisations researched, the anomie score in the non-work context is lower than in the work context, indicating that respondents perceive the work context as more anomic. The work anomie for the total sample was found to be significantly higher that the non-work anomie. The implications for ethical behaviour at work and business ethics are discussed. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2006", "ex:volume": "69", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Anomie and Ethics at Work", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9074-9", "ex:pages": "163-174", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Anomie", "Morality", "Business ethics", "Work anomie"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Eva E. Tsahuridu", "ex:email": "te21@gre.ac.uk"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "85", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Workplace Spirituality and Business Ethics: Insights from an Eastern Spiritual Tradition", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9776-2", "ex:pages": "377-389", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Business ethics", "Workplace spirituality", "Yoga", "Experiential theory building"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Patricia Corner", "ex:email": "trish.corner@aut.ac.nz"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "70", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Corporate Social Responsibility and Socially Responsible Investing: A Global Perspective", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9103-8", "ex:pages": "165-174", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate social responsibility", "Global investments"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Ronald Hill", "ex:email": "ronaldpaulhill@msn.com"}, {"ex:name": "Thomas Ainscough"}, {"ex:name": "Todd Shank"}, {"ex:name": "Daryl Manullang"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "83", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Anomie and the Marketing Function: The Role of Control Mechanisms", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9660-5", "ex:pages": "845-862", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Anomie", "Ethics codification", "Control mechanisms", "Marketing function", "Normlessness", "Output control", "Power", "Process control", "Resource scarcity"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Amit Saini", "ex:email": "asaini2@unl.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Mike Krush"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "78", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Impact of Social Darwinism Perception, Status Anxiety, Perceived Trust of People, and Cultural Orientation on Consumer Ethical Beliefs", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9364-x", "ex:pages": "487-502", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Consumer ethical beliefs", "Cultural orientation", "Perceived trust", "Perception", "Social darwinism", "Status anxiety"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Jyh-Shen Chiou", "ex:email": "jschiou@nccu.edu.tw"}, {"ex:name": "Lee-Yun Pan"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "87", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Corporate Social Responsibility for Developing Country Multinational Corporations: Lost War in Pertaining Global Competitiveness?", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9801-5", "ex:pages": "3-24", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Csr", "Chinese MNEs", "Competitiveness"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Philippe Gugler", "ex:email": "philippe.gugler@unifr.ch"}, {"ex:name": "Jacylyn Shi", "ex:email": "jacylyn.shi@wti.org"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:abstract": "Using traditional meta-analytic techniques, we compile relevant research to enhance conceptual appreciation of ethical climate theory (ECT) as it has been studied in the descriptive and applied ethics literature. We explore the various treatments of ethical climate to understand how the theoretical framework has developed. Furthermore, we provide a comprehensive picture of how the theory has been extended by describing the individual-level work climate outcomes commonly studied in this theoretical context. Meta-analysis allows us to resolve inconsistencies in previous findings as well as confirm the central tenets of the overall ethical climate framework. In addition, we consider the ethical climate relationships in the larger context of theâ\\x90£theoretical framework, using path analysis to test the structural relationships. Overall, our results provide evidence of the relationships between ethical climate perceptions and individual-level work outcomes. Based on our analyses, we offer future research directions important for further development of ECT. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2006", "ex:volume": "69", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Continuities and Extensions of Ethical Climate Theory: A Meta-Analytic Review", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9084-7", "ex:pages": "175-194", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Ethical climate", "Ethical decision-making", "Meta-analysis", "Organizational climate", "Path analysis", "Work climate"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Kelly Martin", "ex:email": "kelly_martin@wsu.edu"}, {"ex:name": "John Cullen", "ex:email": "cullenj@wsu.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "80", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Aftermath of Organizational Corruption: Employee Attributions and Emotional Reactions", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9471-8", "ex:pages": "823-844", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Corruption", "Employee reactions", "Ethical decision making", "Ethics scandal", "Unethical behavior"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Kathie Pelletier", "ex:email": "kathie.pelletier@cgu.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Michelle Bligh"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "80", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Ethnographer’s Apprentice: Trying Consumer Culture from the Outside In", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9448-7", "ex:pages": "85-95", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Anthropology", "Consumerism", "Ethnography", "Globalization", "Marketing"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "John Sherry", "ex:email": "jsherry@nd.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:abstract": "The Sarbanesâ€“Oxley Act of 2002 requires audit committees of public companiesâ€™ boards of directors to install an anonymous reporting channel to assist in deterring and detecting accounting fraud and control weaknesses. While it is generally accepted that the availability of such a reporting channel may reduce the reporting cost of the observer of a questionable act, there is concern that the addition of such a channel may decrease the overall effectiveness compared to a system employing only non-anonymous reporting options. The rationale underlying this concern involves the would-be reporterâ€™s likelihood of reporting, the seriousness with which the organization treats an anonymous report, and the organizationâ€™s ability to thoroughly follow-up the report. Thus, we explore the extent to which the availability of an anonymous reporting channel influences intended use of non-anonymous reporting channels. Further, in response to Sarbanesâ€“Oxley and the environment of financial scandals that led to its passage, many firms are strengthening their internal audit departments, and providing them with greater independence from upper managementâ€™s direct control. Accordingly, our examination tests whether the intended use of the internal audit department as an internal reporting channel is greater when the internal audit department is of â€œhighâ€\\x9D versus â€œlowâ€\\x9D quality. Finally, the study investigates intended reporting behavior across three different cases (e.g., settings). Results show that the existence of an anonymous channel does reduce the likelihood of reporting to non-anonymous channels, that generally the internal audit department quality does not affect reporting to non-anonymous channels, and that case-setting affects the type of channel to be used. Implications from the study are discussed. Copyright Springer 2007", "ex:volume": "71", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Intentions to Report Questionable Acts: An Examination of the Influence of Anonymous Reporting Channel, Internal Audit Quality, and Setting", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-0021-6", "ex:pages": "109-124", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Internal audit department quality", "Questionable acts", "Reporting intentions"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Steven Kaplan", "ex:email": "steve.kaplan@asu.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Joseph Schultz"}]},