tive Social Contracts Theory", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0327-2", "ex:pages": "751-764", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Social contract", "Integrative social contracts theory", "Moral free space", "Hypernorms", "Stakeholder theory"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Johan Wempe", "ex:email": "j.f.d.b.wempe@saxion.nl"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "83", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "A Value-based Framework for Understanding Managerial Tolerance of Bribery in Latin America", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9623-x", "ex:pages": "341-352", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Bribery", "Cultural values", "Latin america", "Attitudes towards bribery", "Individualism–collectivism."], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Juan Sanchez", "ex:email": "sanchezj@fiu.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Carolina Gomez"}, {"ex:name": "Guillermo Wated"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "83", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Ethical Case for Affirmative Action", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9625-8", "ex:pages": "369-379", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Affirmative action", "Ethics", "Diversity management"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Prue Burns"}, {"ex:name": "Jan Schapper", "ex:email": "Jan.Schapper@buseco.monash.edu.au"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "83", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Manager Trustworthiness or Interactional Justice? Predicting Organizational Citizenship Behaviors", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9631-x", "ex:pages": "453-467", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Manager trustworthiness", "Manager integrity", "Organizational justice", "Interactional justice", "Organizational citizenship behaviors"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Dan Chiaburu", "ex:email": "dsc188@psu.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Audrey Lim"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:abstract": "While Corporate Social Responsibility (CSR) has traditionally been the domain of the corporate sector, recognition of the growing significance of the Small and Medium Sized Enterprise (SME) sector has led to an emphasis on their social and environmental impact, illustrated by an increasing number of initiatives aimed at engaging SMEs in the CSR agenda. CSR has been well researched in large companies, but SMEs have received less attention in this area. This paper presents the findings from a U.K. wide study of socially responsible SMEs. The 24 companies studied were chosen as â€œexemplarsâ€\\x9D ofâ\\x90£CSR in SMEs. The aim of this study therefore is to progress understanding of both the limitations on and opportunities for CSR in SMEs through the exploration of exemplary characteristics in the study companies. Key areas of investigation were CSR terminology, the influence of managerial values, the nature of SME CSR activities, motivation for and benefits from engaging in CSR, and the challenges faced. The results of this study demonstrate some of the exemplary goals and principles needed to achieve social responsibility in SMEs, and begin to provide knowledge that could be used to engender learning in other SMEs. In particular, there is evidence that stakeholder theory may provide a framework in which SMEs and CSR can be understood. SMEs prefer to learn through networking and from their peers, so this is a possible avenue for greater SME engagement in CSR. This would require strong leadership or â€œchampioningâ€\\x9D from individuals such as highly motivated ownerâ€“managers and from exemplary companies as a whole. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2006", "ex:volume": "67", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Small Business Champions for Corporate Social Responsibility", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9182-6", "ex:pages": "241-256", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Champions", "Case studies", "Corporate social responsibility", "Small and medium sized enterprises", "Stakeholder theory"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Heledd Jenkins", "ex:email": "jenkinsHM1@cardiff.ac.uk"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "86", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Impact of Anti-Intellectualism Attitudes and Academic Self-Efficacy on Business Students’ Perceptions of Cheating", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9843-8", "ex:pages": "199-209", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Cheating", "Business students", "Anti-intellectualism", "Self-efficacy"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Rafik Elias", "ex:email": "relias@calstatela.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "79", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Moral Choice and the Concept of Motivational Typologies: An Extended Stakeholder Perspective in a Western Context", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9390-8", "ex:pages": "29-42", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Agency problem", "Stakeholder theory", "Motivational typologies", "Accountants and auditors"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Gordon Woodbine", "ex:email": "gordon.woodbine@cbs.curtin.edu.au"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "84", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "On the Quality and Legitimacy of Green Narratives in Business: A Framework for Evaluation", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9693-4", "ex:pages": "135-149", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Management", "Narrative", "Environment"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Lutz Preuss", "ex:email": "Lutz.Preuss@rhul.ac.uk"}, {"ex:name": "David Dawson", "ex:email": "DDawson@glos.ac.uk"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Effects of Personal Values on Auditor’s Ethical Decisions: A Comparison of Pakistani and Turkish Professional Auditors", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0102-4", "ex:pages": "53-64", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Pakistan", "Turkey", "Auditors", "Ethics", "Personal values"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Semra Karacaer", "ex:email": "semra@hacettepe.edu.tr"}, {"ex:name": "Raheel Gohar", "ex:email": "raheel@nims.edu.pk"}, {"ex:name": "Mehmet Aygün", "ex:email": "maygun65@hotmail.com"}, {"ex:name": "Cem Sayin", "ex:email": "cemail@hacettepe.edu.tr"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "The purpose of this study was to explore whether the performance of the green innovation brought positive effect to the competitive advantage. This study found that the performances of the green product innovation and green process innovation were positively correlated to the corporate competitive advantage. Therefore, the result meant that the investment in the green product innovation and green process innovation was helpful to the businesses. This study argued that the businesses should cognize the correct value and positioning of the green innovation. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2006", "ex:volume": "67", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Influence of Green Innovation Performance on Corporate Advantage in Taiwan", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9025-5", "ex:pages": "331-339", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Green innovation", "Green product innovation", "Green process innovation", "Competitive advantage", "Corporate environmental management", "Sustainable development"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Yu-Shan Chen", "ex:email": "yschen@yuntech.edu.tw"}, {"ex:name": "Shyh-Bao Lai"}, {"ex:name": "Chao-Tung Wen"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Decision-Making Process of Internal Whistleblowing Behavior in China: Empirical Evidence and Implications", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9831-z", "ex:pages": "25-41", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Whistleblowing", "Chinese culture", "Ethical organizational culture", "Positive affect"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Julia Zhang"}, {"ex:name": "Randy Chiu", "ex:email": "randychiu@hkbu.edu.hk"}, {"ex:name": "Liqun Wei"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "90", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Ecology-Driven Real Options: An Investment Framework for Incorporating Uncertainties in the Context of the Natural Environment", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0043-y", "ex:pages": "295-310", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Ecological economics", "Uncertainty", "Natural environment", "Real options", "Investment planning"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Timo Busch", "ex:email": "tobusch@ethz.ch"}, {"ex:name": "Volker Hoffmann"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "90", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Do Credible Firms Perform Better in Emerging Markets? Evidence from China", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-009-0038-8", "ex:pages": "221-237", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate credibility", "Corporate reputation", "Emerging markets", "Financial performance", "Market value"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Ran Zhang", "ex:email": "rzhang@gsm.pku.edu.cn"}, {"ex:name": "Zabihollah Rezaee", "ex:email": "zrezaee@memphis.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:abstract": "Organizational governance has historically focused around the perspective of principals and managers and has traditionally pursued the goal of maximizing owner wealth. This paper suggests that organizational governance can profitably be viewed from the ethical perspective of organizational followers â€“ employees of the organization to whom important ethical duties are also owed. We present two perspectives of organizational governance: Principal Theory that suggests that organizational owners and managers can often be ethically opportunistic and take advantage of employees who serve them and Principle Theory that focuses on guiding principles that are sometimes taken too far in organizations. In introducing these two new organizational governance perspectives, we offer insights into the value of rethinking ethical duties owed to organizational followers. Copyright Springer 2006", "ex:volume": "66", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Principal Theory and Principle Theory: Ethical Governance from the Followerâ€™s Perspective", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-005-5586-y", "ex:pages": "207-223", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2006", "ex:keyword": ["Ethical governance", "Principal theory", "Principle theory"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Cam Caldwell"}, {"ex:name": "Ranjan Karri", "ex:email": "rkarri@bryant.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Pamela Vollmar"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:volume": "82", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Political Roots of Corporate Social Responsibility", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-007-9594-y", "ex:pages": "807-819", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2008", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate social responsibility", "Activism", "Political strategy", "Institutions", "Governance", "State/societal complex"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "David Detomasi", "ex:email": "ddetomasi@business.queensu.ca"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Do Traditional Chinese Cultural Values Nourish a Market for Pirated CDs?", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9821-1", "ex:pages": "185-196", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Chinese values", "Face consciousness", "Other orientation", "Materialism", "Risk aversion", "Intention to buy pirated CDs"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Wendy Wan"}, {"ex:name": "Chung-Leung Luk", "ex:email": "mkclluk@cityu.edu.hk"}, {"ex:name": "Oliver Yau"}, {"ex:name": "Alan Tse"}, {"ex:name": "Leo Sin"}, {"ex:name": "Kenneth Kwong"}, {"ex:name": "Raymond Chow"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:abstract": "This research applies the impression management theory of exemplification in an accounting study by identifying and measuring differences in both auditor and public perceptions of exemplary behaviors. The auditors were divided into two groups, one of which reported self-perceptions (A-S) while the other group reported their perceptions of a typical auditor (A-O). There were two separate public groups, which gave their perceptions of a typical auditor and were divided based on their levels of accounting sophistication. The more sophisticated public group was comprised of bank loan officers (LO) while the less sophisticated public group consisted of investment club members (IC). Comparisons were made on 30 behaviors contained in the AICPA Code of Professional Conduct, which served as the basis for the research instrument. Profile analysis, a special form of MANOVA technique, was used to analyze the results. A-S perceptions were the highest of the four treatment levels and were significantly higher (i.e., more exemplary) than the perceptions of both the A-O and LO groups. The more sophisticated user group (LO) provided the lowest perceptions of the four treatment levels. For at least four of the six measures, the LO treatment group perceived the typical auditor to be less exemplary than both the IC and A-O treatments. There were no differences in perceptions between the A-O group and IC. Additional analysis revealed that auditors overrated the degree to which the public relied on financial statements. However, both public groups reported a reasonably high level of reliance on financial statements when making decisions. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2007", "ex:volume": "71", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Ethical Exemplification and the AICPA Code of Professional Conduct: An Empirical Investigation of Auditor and Public Perceptions", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9124-3", "ex:pages": "39-71", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Accounting code of ethics", "Professional conduct", "Impression management", "Exemplification"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Phil Brown", "ex:email": "pbrown@harding.edu"}, {"ex:name": "Morris Stocks", "ex:email": "acstocks@olemiss.edu"}, {"ex:name": "W. Wilder", "ex:email": "acwilder@olemiss.edu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:abstract": "Arriving at a moral judgment is not a straightforward or linear process in which ethical theories are simply applied to cases. Instead it is a process in which the formulation of the moral problem, the formulation of possible â€œsolutionsâ€\\x9D, and the ethical judging of these solutions go hand in hand. This messy character of moral problems, however, does not rule out a systematic approach. In this article, we describe a systematic approach to problem solving that does justice to the complex nature of moral problems and ethical judgment: the ethical cycle. Our goal is to provide a structured and disciplined method of addressing moral problems, which helps to guide a sound analysis of these problems. We will illustrate the usefulness of this cycle with an example. Further, we will discuss two general issues in applied ethics in relation to the proposed ethical cycle: the role of ethical theories and the place of individual judgment versus collective deliberation. Copyright Springer 2007", "ex:volume": "71", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "The Ethical Cycle", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9121-6", "ex:pages": "1-13", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Ethics", "Engineering", "Moral problems", "Designing", "Deliberation"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "I. Poel", "ex:email": "i.r.vandepoel@tbm.tudelft.nl"}, {"ex:name": "L. Royakkers", "ex:email": "l.m.m.royakkers@tm.tue.nl"}]}, {"ex:issue": "3", "ex:volume": "76", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Towards a Design Science of Ethical Decision Support", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-0