: "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Corporate Social Responsibility as Support for Employee Volunteers: Impacts, Gender Puzzles and Policy Implications in Canada", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9716-1", "ex:pages": "405-416", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate social responsibility", "Volunteering", "Gender", "Human resource policies"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Fiona MacPhail", "ex:email": "macphail@unbc.ca"}, {"ex:name": "Paul Bowles"}]}, {"ex:issue": "2", "ex:volume": "88", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "Some of the Recent Organizational Behavior Concepts as Precursors to Workplace Spirituality", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-008-9961-3", "ex:pages": "245-261", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": ["Organizational behavior", "Workplace spirituality"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Badrinarayan Pawar", "ex:email": "pawar@iimk.ac.in"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "A longitudinal study of 308 white-collar U.S. employees revealed that feelings of hope and gratitude increase concern for corporate social responsibility (CSR). In particular, employees with stronger hope and gratitude were found to have a greater sense of responsibility toward employee and societal issues; interestingly, employee hope and gratitude did not affect sense of responsibility toward economic and safety/quality issues. These findings offer an extension of research by Giacalone, Paul, and Jurkiewicz (2005, Journal of Business Ethics, 58, 295-305). Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, Inc. 2007", "ex:volume": "70", "ex:source": "Journal of Business Ethics", "ex:title": "On the relationship of hope and gratitude to corporate social responsibility", "ex:url": "http://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/s10551-006-9118-1", "ex:pages": "401-409", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": ["Corporate social responsibility", "Hope", "Gratitude"], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Lynne Andersso